\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid16673035 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you tell me when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 In - June 14th 1894.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Whereabouts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 In - Kirkblane, Caerlaverock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How many years did you live in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh, well, we came from there - now I was nine months old, not that I can remember anything, but we came - from there to Templand, where - my mother's people lived at that time
. Houses were - easily bought in these days, and - they got a house and father had worked in a farm previous to this, but - Corncockle quarry was in full production at that time, and - my father got a job right away in the quarry, looking after a steam pu
m
p, which was in the bottom - of the quarry, and it was there for the purpose of keeping the rocks clear for the men coming in to work every morning. It was shift work. He had two weeks - on day shift, two weeks on night work and a neighbouring man named T
hompson relieved him. So that in the evenings as a family for two - weeks we had no father at night. And - he was there for the long period of forty years, he never worked anywhere else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Where was he working when he was at Caerlaverock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What was he -?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of job did he do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well, he worked a pair of horse at a farm. Ploughman I suppose he would be, but - mother was cook at Kirkblane, Caerlaverock and of course they met at dances and - he used to have wee - does as they talked
 about at different farms and they would be meeting each other, and - they got married. And - as I told you came to live at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 Te}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
mpland. Now, we had - as a child I remember I used to - call my mother at home mammy up the raw, and grandma - was mammy down the 
raw. This raw was a row of houses, and I can remember there was about seven or eight steps - up to grandma's house and I can remember crawling up these steps as a child, there was nothing to hinder us to get about because - motors and things werenae much 
i
n vogue in these days. So that I had two homes really because as often as not I was down at her house, as in my own home. And then - my sister was born about two years after me, and my brother about three years after that, and another brother maybe three 
years and then there was a long pause, I was about - nearly leaving school when my youngest sister was born. Five of us all together.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Have you any idea how old your mother and father would be when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How what? Oh they would be quite 
young. Quite young, mother was married I think at twenty-one. So my father was just about two years older, they were quite young, they were just a young family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about your mother, did she do any work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh she did plenty
 of work. She - used to go I remember - to the farm, Corncockle, this was not far off the quarry, always at Christmas and New Year time, and used to help them to pluck turkeys and geese all by hand. I can remember that. And - she helped grandma a lot you 
know, because - grandma had a big family, she'd a family of - of eight. Three girls, my mother was the eldest of the family, then there was Uncle Toby, and - there was five boys and then - other two girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Probably there wouldn't be very much difference between your grandmother's youngest and you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
When I went to school - which I did when I was four, my aunt - was still at that school, and that's why I went to school - to get broken in as they called it before she left. She helped me to school - at
 four. Templand school. I was never anywhere else, but - at - and it was a three teacher - school. A small room was where the infants were taught, and the bigger room - was - like there was two parts of the room, there was a young - man, Ray, Mr Ray, just
 a young fellow he was, taught the ones that come in from the wee - room, and Mr Patterson had the bigger one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He would be the headmaster?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He - when I went first there was a Mr Ray there the schoolmaster but he was just leaving so that I never - 
then - no one else but Mr Patterson, a teacher like in the big room, and - we always used to think he was terribly hard man. One day at the club I was - talking to them on my young days and - and she'd been at - Templand school and of course - Were you at
 
Templand school with you man? You know, and folks looked. And I said, why, what was wrong? This was Mrs Vincent. Oh she was a hard taskmaster, I said, he was, but I've many time blessed him since, because - of the he kept - had to give you good grounding 
i
n every subject, and that's why - I can - write and - do things I do today. And - in holiday time, there was another girl and I used to get - there was little carts in these days, just like a pack of playing cards with - fifty-two in a pack and he used to
 have them and give her one half and me the other and we did this all over this because we were trying to better it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 These cards with work on them that you had to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 With work, sums, these terrible - problems, I used to one a day, all my
 holiday time. And - my friends this very pal that used to sit together, she used to do the other half. Then at - at the end of the holidays she used to go to Lockerbie for a test, see, to Lockerbie academy, and in the finish when we were really trying fo
r a bursary, she beat me by five marks, and went on as a teacher, she was through Glasgow - university, but I wasn't a bit sorry because - it seemed to take a lot out of you, you know, working so hard all the holidays. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was there only one person chosen for the bursary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well, at these days to begin with yes, there was the two of us chosen, and we'd no way of getting - she was a farmer's daughter - Lockerbie - you know, buses and - transport wasn't so great then as what it's now, but the fathe
r - the farmer came in his gig and ran us in to Lockerbie and of course there was children from other parishes there at the same - and just came in and laid the papers down and gave you so long to do. So - it was exciting and you had a day out, it was ver
y nice, and got - taken home I think at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say your mother plucked turkeys and so at Christmas, did she do any other work at the farm throughout the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh no, oh no, it's just - anybody - mother was a person like this - like what my gr
andmother was, if anyone was ill in the village and needed help they used to send for her. Any babies being born, go for Mrs Hardy, or go for Mrs Mitchell, I remember grandma always with her clean white apron on, she used to go and see to the mothers and 
b
abies, 'til such time as their own - people could come, there was no national health and things in these days. And - that's what she used to do, she used to help anyone that needed help, she'd no - steady work to go to, she'd plenty to do at home, because
 
- first of all, when this quarry started up, the men came from - England, Scotland, Ireland and Wales, there was every - nationality working in that quarry, and everybody in the village had one or more men billeted on them, I mean they came to us. We had 
t
wo at one time, we had a Welshman - and - an Irishmen. Oh they were at loggerheads, and unfortunately they had to occupy the same room, and mother used to sometimes be - you know, hard put to it to put up with the, especial when my father was at nights yo
u
 know, if they started, both of them. And - then we had a highland man, I remember - he was a very religious man, a man with a beard and he had the kilt - kilt in those days for church, and on the Sunday nights he used to say - sing me the Old Hundred. Th
a
t was his favourite - psalm. And - we used to sing to him and sing hymns, and - then he went away - in the holiday time to Edinburgh. And in those days there was no Post Office in the village, but there was a place they called the old Post Office House I 
d
on't know how it got that name, it must have had something to do - and - a postman used to walk six miles from Lockerbie - with our letters, come round the village, and he got there about eleven o'clock in the morning, he stayed there 'til two in this old
 
house, it was a decent enough house and - someone - Mrs Arbon it was, put a fire on for him, and had it nice for him and he brought something with him to eat and he could make a cup of tea. Then you had to have your letters - he didn't take parcels but yo
u
 had to have your letters down - by two o'clock, and he walked back to Lockerbie, six miles. Then that was changed. Mill House Bridge got a Post Office, that was a village about two miles off from us, and the postman had a bicycle, so - he used to come on
 
his bicycle and parcels and everything, on the carrier, big carrier he had, so - Bryce they called the first postman, I remember his name, and he was a nice old man, we used to go down as children you know if there was letters, and talk to him and he'd ta
l
k to us and then he would say, go on now, I'm going to be busy, he would be stamping - the letters. So - then we had a Sunday school. We had a Sunday school at Templand, it was held in the school, and the man who ran the Sunday school was a church Elder, 
a
 roadman, he was a roadman by trade, and he used to come on Sundays and we had - a Mr Littler come, a son, and - Miss Ewart, a dressmaker in Templand, and these were our teachers. And first of all we got a little text to learn, 'cos it was very small I us
ed to learn that as soon as I went home. That was one thing I always did, it was just to - get it - over and done with, used to learn it. And then when we got bigger we got verses from the scriptures, in the finish we got whole chapters.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you go to Sunday school and then go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Not so much to church because we were too far off the church, not until we were really bigger, into the bigger classes. We didn't go to church at all until we were big enough to walk for there was no other way to
 go. The church was three miles, but my father and mother - grandma and grandpa were regular attenders. In fact - the - on a Sunday morning the road was black with people, walking down to church in their Sunday best, there was three churches in all then. 
T
here was the parish church to which - we still belong, I joined it and I've been - a member of it all my life. Mr Neil Ray was the minister, in these far off days. Then at the parish church which - now - is going to be made into a house - it was Mr Lane, 
the Reverend Andrew Lane. And the Victoria UF church was - Mr Fleming. These were the three churches and they were all well attended. And - the parish church used to have c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 ntatas, that was - evenings for the children you know, with cups of tea, and - some 
of my school friends were - members, and they used to invite us to go with them and we used to be coming home - about ten or half past ten, walking up the road, and mother'll be down the road - waiting in case - yes, anything had happened to us but - noth
ing happened in these days, everything was - you know, quiet and peaceful. Not like it is nowadays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How old would you be when you went to church then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - when we got into the bigger classes, about ten. About ten we started going to church. Yo
u see - on the Saturdays when our parents were going to church - most of the mothers made soup, broth probably, that's what we had anyway, and it was only to heat up on a Sunday. Well - it was left at the side on the hob, and it was - we'd to see that the
 
fire wasane too big you know and - stir it now and again, I was getting older then of course, and put on the potatoes, the meat - was put into the broth just to heat through for maybe half an hour before it was time for them coming home, and then - after 
t
hat, after we'd had our dinner - we were sent for the walk. Werena allowed to play on Sundays these days, we could read - could read our story books or Bible stories but not allowed to play. And mother used to say - now, away for a walk up the road and re
m
ember what day it is. This was her rebuke now - you see. Yes. Aye. That's right. Then in - in an evening in the house then we used to - sing hymns. When father was at home he used to listen to us, and - on the other evenings - he used to play his fiddle, 
h
e was a great fiddler my father, a lovely fiddler, and he had friends, a gamekeeper not far off in Jardine Hall Lodge, and there was two of them there that used to have command concerts. But when we where our own in the house we used to - we just wooden c
h
airs in the kitchen those days, you know, my father had a nice chair and mother, the rest was wooden, and you used to stand up there and sing or recite, we did that, mother was a nice singer, and she used to sing to us, and tell us stories, you know, or r
ead stories to us, that was what we did in the evening when my father was out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Not just the Sunday nights, this would be any night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 This was any night, we had that, not the summertime of course, we were allowed to play but these are the winter n
ights I'm talking about. And - grandpa was a great one for stories, my grandfather, and he used to tell us stories, used to get us in the - even at the summertime - he used to get us out on to a seat that my father made at the door, by this time - our hou
s
es were close together, closer together. Grandpa used to come up and he would sit there and he had us children, not only us - but his own grandchildren but other children about listening to the tales he used to tell - about old Dumfries, and one of the ta
l
es he told us I remember was - I used to say to him, what was Dumfries like grandpa, in the old days? Oh, he said, it wasna the nice clean place it is now. He says, you know, when you used to go in to the markets, there were great market - he said, I said
, was there lavatories and that? And he said, no, there was no lavatories. And I said, how did you do? Well, he says, there was a man used to go round the stree}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 t with a pail, and a black cloa}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 k round him, and if you needed to do something on the street - he'd put this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 cloa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 k round you, black }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 cloak}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
 round you, and stood there. Now - this is true. That's true. That's many a long year ago you see. Grandpa was eighty-four when he died and grandma was sixty-nine. My mother was eighty-four and my father eighty-eight.
 So they're long lived. And another thing he told us, he went to what would be probably - I don't know if it was the last but it was very near the last hanging in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 D}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 umfries. When they were hanged in public. And that was Mary Timmony. I don't know if you'd e
ver heard of her. Yes. And mother told me - as - when I come in to mother, I said, fancy grandpa going to a hanging. She says, yes, he did, was he telling you that? I said, yes, he was. Well she said, I'll tell - I was older you see, I'll you the story of
 
that. She said, this Mary Timmony - had a baby. And her husband was supposed to be going - with an - Ann Hannay. And whether that was true or not mother said she didn't know, but this Mary Timmony was jealous of her husband, you see. And one day she took 
her baby, and - the beetle that she - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 posed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080  the clothes with -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 For the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
The washing, hid it in her shawl, and when she came to this laundry where this - woman was, she hit her over the head with the beetle and killed her, and went away ho
me as if nothing had happened. And of course when they found her - she was - somebody had seen it, not doing it but going towards the laundry. She would have got free owing to her child being seen, but she blamed it on her mother. She blamed the - hitting
,
 and it wasna her mother at all, and she was hanged. And she was so light that they had to put weights to her feet, to - you know, for the - that's right, that's quite true, mother told me, oh, she said, did he tell you that, he used to tell me things tha
t he maybe wouldna tell - the smaller ones. I was the oldest grandchild and called me after his wife you see so - so -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So he was a good story teller?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh he was, and so was grandma. Grandma - I used to go down each day on my way to school. We had
 - going from the house that we first lived in - to Corncockle cottage, these were houses - in connection with the quarry, and they were built of the red sandstone that Locharbriggs that my father used to maintain, there's a seam through from Corncockle t
o
 Locharbriggs, it's the same stone. And - we lived in one of these houses, well it was a wee bit further off from grandma but not much, and I used to go down every morning - on my way to school, this was just before I left school, to see if she wanted any
 messages, because all her family had left her then you see, and - I used to go down to see if she wanted messages, probably she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 wanted corn or meal for the hen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 s, she kept hens. And - when I went in - there was a wee - window that you could look into - befo
re you came to the back door and she was always sitting reading the paper. She was very religious, and - and she would tell me if she wanted anything and I went up - to the shop and got it you see. And - in their houses - round the village at that time, e
verybody had texts hanging on the wall, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 A framed on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes. Framed text, I can remember grandma's text. It was - casting all your care upon Him, for he cared for you. And she was - good in her daily - good living woman. And - then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 As you say it would be just like having another mother there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
It was certainly, yes, yes. And then - the uncles used to come home, now I had three uncles policemen. Two - were in Paisley. One was in Newcastle. They started at Lochleven being young po
licemen there then they shift. And then I had my mother's - sister next to her, Aunt Ann, she}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080  married a policeman - an Aberdee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
nian, and they went to live in Newcastle too. And the earliest of my memories is - I wasn't at school, but I could remember this a
s if it was yesterday. Uncle Tom came through - for holidays, through from Newcastle to Templand. And he was in my mother's, and he says, come on now, take your walk up the road. And he put me on his shoulder, I wouldn't be very big, and we walked up the 
r
oad. Oh they were big fellows, one of them was six feet four. Tallest man in the force he was in - Newcastle. So - in the distance I saw something coming towards me, and I wondered - this is what brings it to my memory, it was a soldier, a red coat with a
 
red coat and clear buttons, and tartan trousers, and I can remember saying, what's this? And he told me it was a soldier. A soldier who must have been - just coming home from the Boer War, a native must have been of Templand. Isn't that funny, now that's 
m
y earliest recollection, you know, it - any - anything that stands out in my memory. I could remember the first day I went to school - I was just four as I told you, and I can remember lying on this - wooden chair, you know, looking at my feet, and I woul
d
nae smile - I was waiting on man coming to take me. And - mother told me before I went that I was to do everything the teacher told me, just as you had to do at home. So - there was a - nice big fire in the grate, and a big - thing to keep us, the childre
n
 off it, you see. Yes, a big fire guard, and - the teacher's name was Miss Boyle, and I used to say since I'm grown up, Boyle by name and Boyle by nature, because she was very short tempered. The first day she'd to check me for talking, I just forgot wher
e
 I was, and started to talk to the girl beside me. The next day - I forgot again, so I never knew anything 'til I was rapped sharply over the knuckles with that cane, and brought the tears to my eyes, she never said anything, and - I could have cried you 
k
now, but I thought, well - I was told to do what the teacher told me so I said nothing. But - at playtime she said to my aunt she was sorry - she had - come down rather sharper than what she meant, she'd stinged my finger, so when I went home I just said 
t
o my mother, teacher put nice cream on my finger but my aunt had to tell my mother what had happened. What I - what I had said was - we were looking at picture books, and I recognized the picture, it was the story of Snow White and Rose Red and - I just s
a
id, oh there's Snow White and Rose Red, of course all the children looked. Naturally, and I got - well - but was all I said anyway. And - he says to me, often now, you've talked ever since. Aye. Oh dear. Then - when the quarry didn't get so busier, mother
 took a teacher to live with us and we had Miss Anderson, from - good few years, she was the infant teacher then when I was older.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 This was when there wasn't so many men working about the quarry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. And - Miss Anderson married the manager of the Cooper's, I remember that. Manager of the Cooper's in Dumfries, she was a nice soul.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was she a local girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, she's not living now, no, Mrs Rose was her name, I can even remember that, I've a good memory for long ago things. And - I remember
 mother - when my sister next to me went to school - she was very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
omesick and she cried and cried, and this Monday mother washing, and she looked out this wee window in the - we were living in the house grandma used to live in - in, and she saw Miss Ander
son bringing - my sister down in the play hours, she couldn't do anything with her, being homesick. And she says, I don't think you try very much, she said, you should have given her - you know - let her stop and made her do. So Miss Anderson was vexed an
d
 I think mother was - apologized, she was vexed too, but she'd a lot to do you know, she'd big washings, because these quarry clothes were dirty clothes, and there was nothing - no fine - things to take dirt out like we have now. It was soap and water, ye
s
. That's right. Then we had - we had hens, we had ducks, and we had two pigs, so that we never - were always kept one for ourselves because - in this house there was a big - what had been a milk house with big stone slabs, and that was a grand place for c
uring meat in you see, so mother had plenty to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Your mother cured the bacon herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye, she did it herself, grandma and her - they knew all about how to do it, and they were always baking you see, we'd always eggs, we didn't have so many du
ck eggs, because there was a big - what had been a quarry once not far off and it was about sixty feet deep and the ducks used to get onto that and swim about and they would lay their eggs there, so we got round about to see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have a big garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh we had a big garden. We had - grand lot of potatoes and then small potatoes - where - and - and we'd turnip and - greens, everything - you know that wasnae used for own used did for the pigs and that used to be boiled - once, sometimes twice a w
eek when we had two pigs, we didn't always have two, sometimes we'd just one. But we were sent away from home the days the pigs were killed, we went up to Grandma's because the pigs were - \{BLANK\}
 you know, pets, and - then - grandma used to come down and help to make the black puddings and white puddings and - oh, we had - we'd a grand - lot you know from the pigs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How about keeping things like that though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they all have to be used up right away? Or was there any way of keeping things like black puddings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh well - what the village people did, lots of them had pigs you know, and we used to share and share out, you know, if anybody was killing a pig, you may depend they were all round about to get bits of it, you know, just -
 we just gave them it, because - we got a share of theirs when theirs was killed you see. Aye. They were very friendly people in the village, very friendly, the whole lot of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say you lived in three different houses in Templand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Wait 'til 
I think how many houses we were in. Five years we were at School Terrace, that was near the school, and were still at School Terrace, my father and mother eventually bought the house, not the time - that we lived in then but the next to us. And when they 
died my eldest brother - now lives there. He lives there. And that was the house grandmother lived in too. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you tell me what sort of house it was?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How big was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It's not modern. It has - a living room. A small bedroo
m - off the living room. It has a back kitchen, and coal house inside, and then - it has - well it was a bedroom - to begin with - when we were small. Front room mother always called it but it was a room - where we had our parties in, and - a room upstair
s. Attic room upstairs, it was quite a - decent sized house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Is that where the lodgers stayed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
That's where we - when we were bigger, that's where were, after we - came from Corncockle cottage when my father had to retire, he wouldn't have retire
d but he had to owing - at sixty-five. But he didn't retire from work then. He worked on 'til he was eighty, and I don't think he would have been retired then if mother hadn't taken ill, but - as - girls of the family were all married, homes of our own. M
y
 youngest sister - lives in Templand still. She took two days nursing - mother, then my sister in Lockerbie went for two days, and I went for two days. And it got that she needed someone constantly there, and by this time my husband - my sister's husband 
h
ad taken ill, and she couldn't be there, so it meant - that we had alternately to us, my father then gave up his work. And - stayed home and that was a terrible punishment for him, you know, to stop working. He used to go away on his bicycle up to this fa
r
m. He'd been pally with this farmer all his life, and he used to go up and catch rabbits for him, clean out the hen houses, just do anything - any little jobs at all, so when - aye, when I used to go for Templand - we went - up with the eight o'clock bus 
i
n the morning, and I used to say, now - have a cup of tea and off to your pal's for the day. Because he knew I would be there all that night, and that pleased him more than anything, to get up to work. And - the same - next day, well, he had to come home 
e
arly because I would be going away home, and I've seen us being so tired at night, three miles we had to walk to get a bus for home, I seemed to be more in the roadside than out of it, you know, I was nearly falling asleep in the road. That was before I g
o
t a bicycle, but I had a bicycle in the finish. And - an old farmer, on the road, Mr Mollins, he used to be waiting for me - he knew about my time, - that I would be - coming home from Templand, he used to be walking about the road, watching for me to ask
 
for mother. He had known them when they were young. And when I told mother that Mr Mollins was out asking for them, she said, was he really? She was pleased you know. She says, do you know, that man never needed a dog when he was - looking after his sheep
,
 he could run faster than any dog. And I once told him that, he said, that's true, he said, I never had a dog when I kept sheep, he was on a farm too. But by this time he had a farm of his own, and one day - he - there was a ploughing match, and - my youn
g
est brother must be very like what my father was although he didn't appear to be to us but I mean - what my father was like in the olden days because he went to him and he says, is your name Halliday? He was pulling - he said, I kenned it. He was that lik
e my father, he told me about it. It's funny wasn't it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say your mother had big washings to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you tell me where she did them?
