 potatoes and things cleans boiler. That's right, you know, anything earthy cleans a boiler. Well she used to boil the clothes in this boiler, there was a fire it underneath, in the back kitchen. It was inside, and she used to boil and she'd a lovely wash
,
 and I used to think what nice clean washing she had. And then at times think about it now, because nowadays we've such grand things for washing with - you know, such as Daz and all these things, in these days I remember there was what you called - A1 soa
p
 powders. And this uncle - that was policeman - in - Paisley, Uncle John, he said to me - my beat's near Esdaile and McCallum's works. I says, Esdaile and McCallum, I had to think for a minute. I says, that's where the soap powder came from that mother us
ed to wash with, wasn't that funny. And the motto on it was - \{BLANK\} on the Sco}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 tch }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
isle. That was the - oh I can remember all these things. And we used to go for the milk, they're talking about tuberculosis now, we used to go for the milk, it was about a h
alf a mile from home, I used to walk, I was the eldest and - we had a can to carry it in, and - when it was the farmer's wife she just used to give us - two pints, that was just a penny you mind, but if it was the - the maid she used to give us a wee drop
 more, used to like when it was the maid, she used to put a wee drop more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She gave you a good bargain?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes, but I what I remember was - I used to clean that can every Saturday, that was my job, and I had it shining and always I liked clean and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did you use to clean it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well, it wasn't Brasso but it was stuff like brass and it had a nice smell, and oh that's a thing I can't remember the name of that. Those things have gone but I can't remember but I used to get it out o
nto this seat and clean it, I'd put it on, but not inside mind you. And then mother scalded it out with boiling water. That's what we used to get grand cans of milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have other wee jobs to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, we had jobs. Saturday especially. Well I had - it was a long lobby, I had this - this to wash out you know, big lobby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was it lino on the floor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Lino. And - wash the steps, scrub the steps, they were white cement steps, didn't put - put anything on them, just scrubbed them clean, and 
sweep the flagstones. Mother used to do it just with a - coarse brush, we hadnae to do anything to that, she did that herself. My sister used to clean the spoons, but - the butcher used to come at the Saturday, and it's the same Brown that's in Lochmaden 
y
et, Brown in Lockerbie - but - an older generation, he used to come with a little - what could you call it now - a - just a sort of wee cart affair, but it was all closed in, and he used to bring the papers with him, and the Weekly News - always came with
 
the Peoples Friend. And - when we saw the Weekly News, Jean McFarland that was my husband was talking about, this was what you used to read to grandpa, and it was down - alerted quick to see what Jean McFarland was doing today, and mother - she'd say, com
e on. No - no reading 'til your work's finished, used to take the papers from us and put them right up onto a big cupboard we had and we got no reading until the work was done. And I can re -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did the boys get jobs to do as well or was it just the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh the boys - they had rabbits, and they had to clean out the rabbits, clean the hen houses, and sometimes my father - made jobs for them, but - he liked doing his garden himself, but I don't suppose he kept them at the gardening like what - your 
- husband's father did, but - mother had a wee garden, she did the flower garden, she was always working in that flower garden, showing flowers. And - my brother Tom used to dig that over for her, the oldest brother, he used to dig that over. Of course th
e
 younger ones didn't get so much to do, because, by the time they - younger ones were born there was more labour saving devices coming onto the market, and they got off with lots of things that us elder ones - had to do, but we all got jobs. Even if it wa
s just going for messages down to the shop, the shop was a wee bit off you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you ever have to look after your younger brothers and sisters, was that one of your jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did we?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Have to help to look after your younger brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes. I can remember - you see when - when my youngest sister was born I was in the bigger classes school and had a lot of lessons to do and at night mother used to say, you might take the baby up the road in her pram, oh I used to - if she woul
dn't sleep I've told her since I used to give her many a smack. Because - it was because I had such a lot of lessons to do, got a lot of homework. I don't know whether it was the custom or not but we'd - I had to do a lot of homework, my sister next to me
 
never seemed to brother and she got on just as well, but - I seemed to like to - to do my lessons. I used to go into the bedroom away from the noise you know of the kitchen, and learn my lessons. My father used to sometimes be in when it was his time, lik
e
 when he was on night shift he would be at home through the day, and perhaps he would be putting in his time sheet, he'd a week desk that he wrote at, he was a good writer my father and - he used to be doing this and I remember one - day when we were doin
g
 I, my eldest brother come down to start making a noise and - my father's checked him for you know, making noise and - I don't know - he rose quickly to - to - go out of the room and he - he just come in contact with my ankle and gave my ankle a cut. And 
f
or weeks and weeks the schoolmaster used to let - the bandage to see all the different colours she used to change, the children. Aye. It's funny how you remember all these things. Then we used to have a - a singing master come to our school, a Mr Mickle, 
he used to come and he came for about three months. And - oh and we paid tuppence a night for two nights a week, that was four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
pence. My sister -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You went after school hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 After school hours. And then at the end of the three months they had t
wo nights of a concert that the school children gave and it was real splendid. I was a flower girl, they picked you see from the - you' - they'd inspect you, and when we had the concert it wasn't a very good time of the year for flowers, it was about Febr
u
ary, but I remember mother and my aunt, the aunt next like to me in age - made me a basket, did it all with ivy, and - arranged the flowers, it was real great armful, and I had to sing this song. And - then there was other ones - three fairies, these were
 
the first ones, then the flower girl, fruit girl, Cheery Tom an archer and hob goblins and - skipping games. My sister lost at her skipping game because she was too near the piano, and - there was her and another girl doing the skipping while we sang the 
song, and they tripped every now and again. And you could have heard her laughing. She was always a one for laughing. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were there many things in the village for youngsters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - we - usually - had evangelists come to the village, they must 
have known a good place to come to I think because the people were really good living people, don't suppose they were any better than anything else - anywhere else but I noticed it more - noticing all these texts in the houses. And - these - two men came 
o
nce, there was women came too, but I remember these men they stayed for a fortnight, and they bad a tent on the village green, and we used to go at night to listen to them and then they had us children going round the village, they learn - learned us chor
u
ses, and - through the day they used to go out and in the houses, grandpa used to have them in and have a grand talks with them, he was on his own then, grandma had passed away. And gran - grandpa used to have them in. And - then we had Punch and Judy sho
w
s in the village green, and - we had - people used to come - selling dishes you know, that used to put up a big tent and - they would stay for a week or a fortnight, we had lots of people came from outlying districts to the school, so that they came to th
e
se things too. There was a village Cumrue, maybe about a mile off, and then there was - Archwood Farm, Burns Farm, these were all places near at hand, and Millhouse Bridge, and all these outlying districts all come in with Templand, Kennel Bridge and all 
t
hese places so that we were a big community really, as a whole. And - the men used to bowl in the hall, we hadn't a hall to begin with, it was the school. But one of the men - that came to stay with us in the finish and who worked in the quarry was a mini
s
ter's son, unfortunately down in the world through drink, Mr Brown his name was, a very learned man. And he wrote to Carnegie, you've heard of Carnegie where we go for these things, well he wrote to Carnegie what a beautiful rector he was, and implored hi
m
 to help to get up - a - hall and it was through Mr Brown that we got the Templand Hall up. It's a different hall now, but - that was the first hall we had, lighted by oil lamps but it was a great thing for us you know when this hall was opened, so the bo
wling boards went down from the school to the hall.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of bowling was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Carpet. Carpet bowling, my father never entertained to that, but my two brothers and my sister, she next to me, was keen bowlers. Of course time's getting on - th
is was when they were grown up a bit, young men, when - and we had the dances - first of all in the school, we had dances every now and again, a bowlers dance and - we had concerts from - people coming from Lockerbie or Lochmaben, a co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 pany, and we had con
certs, we were well entertained. And - aye, we had - we had all the weddings. Not - not our wedding, we had our wedding just at home, it was war time then, but my sister's wedding - both my sisters wedding - my brother's wedding, no, my brother's wedding 
was at her home, but all our family affairs were in there as well as that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 There would be lots of weddings and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, lots of weddings there and they were all held there. Every - entertainment of any kind, you know, they used to
 have a day - what they call the sports day for the children, they used to just get it up amongst themselves, the village people, and then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have that sort of thing when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, yes, when I was at the school too they had i
t. They just used to get up a day and they would bake - they were great bakers you know, and they used to bake and - somebody would give tea and sugar and little prizes, the prizes werenae very much but they were - meant a lot to us children you know. And
 - and a dance at night to finish up which helped for the next time you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How old would you be before you were allowed to go to a dance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - oh, we had dances at home. Mother - in the house. Mother - every year from I can remember - went fr
om - we were - maybe no, I don't remember when the first went to school, but I can remember when my sister went, she - started making a New Year party. And grandpa and grandma would be there, and my aunt, she was a young woman dressmaking, she was learnin
g
 dressmaking in Lockerbie, and - maybe some - of the village people, not them all, she couldn't of course have put them up, but I can remember one year, there was thirteen of us sat down at the big table and we didn't know. I never knew either. And when m
o
ther went - oh and we had two small tables. You see, we took everything out of the room, we'd plenty of room. And - when mother mother went through and I came with her to go through, she says, there's thirteen sitting at our table. I said, oh never. I mea
n
, I'm superstitious. Well it was, it spoiled the night for us. Mother says, don't - but - I don't think anybody's noticed. So - after this the party was passed, Mr Erslin, next door neighbour got up to thank them for their hospitality, and right enough he
 
was dead within the year. It might only be superstitious, but - you know, couldnae help but think about it. We didn't tell anybody you know, but mother and I knew. And - that's what they say you know, that's an old superstitious custom. Well he got up to 
t
hank them and that's what happened. So then after that tea was passed, because everybody baked and helped you know, there was - plenty of everything, we used to go to it - after we were married too from - you know, 'cos she wasnae able - she'd a party eve
ry Christ - not Christmas, New Year. New Year. And some would sing and - so on, and - and there was a dance. Then - we used to walk home after that, but there was no other way of getting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about music for the dancing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh my father and I had two brothers melod}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 eo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
n players. Aye. They - they didn't - my father hope - hoped they would play the fiddle but they never learnt it, my husband can play, but my father was a great fiddler all his life, and a grand fiddler. And then a time when - I hear the
m now, that come to the club you know, the tunes that he used to play. He went - he went once to Dum - to - Lockerbie when - Scott Skinner was playing, and he piped in to Lockerbie, we were living in Lockerbie then, to hear this fiddler. And after he list
ened to him, it was the Cradle Song, and he says, Robert, I'm going home to burn my fiddle. And he really was a good fiddler wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Scott Skinner was exceptional wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And - skirls and reels and used to dance and - we'd grand nights, we really had, happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have parties at birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh no, we always remembered each others birthday, and if we were at home, you know, say on a Sunday or a Saturday, if we're all at home together, mother would make something special for the tea but it wasnae really a custom that she did it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get presents at birthday time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh got presents, yes, even if it wasnae very much. And Christmas time, oh - we used to go away to bed early, even when we were big and knew who Santa Claus, we never let on to father and mother that we didn't - that we knew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was this for the wee ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye. But we hung up our stockings too, and we had a - a range and it had a big brass - rail, mother used to keep it a lovely shine, we used to pu
t things through our stockings, and hang them up there, even when we were big, like before I went to work. But when we come out in the morning she'd say, hurry up now and get your clothes on, Santa's been. No sign of our stockings, they werena there. They
'
d be hanging on pictures or - on hooks outside the door. This was the things they used to do. And - there'd be an apple, or an orange, maybe a sixpenny piece, that was riches in these days. In the very toe and - cinders, oh she says, they've been hot cind
ers, he's put them in your stocking when they're cold to let you see it was too hot for him, that's what mother used to say, she used to make up stories, you know. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She must have been quite a character.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She was, and you know I must have tak
en it off her I think because - my own girl, and - I've lots of - my sisters two boys used to say, come on Auntie Mary, and tell us a story. And I used to make them up you know, make up stories and tell them, and the wee ones \{BLANK\}
 from anywhere and Miss
 Stewart'll say, come on, tell us a story, it's a wee boy and he's just six, and I have to make them up it's no good with the books. So - she used to - say - oh look where he's hung them, and I says, did he not leave anything for you? Oh no, we're too big
 
now, she used to say. My father used to go down to the shop you know, for - things - the shop sold everything, the - the - there was two shops but especially Miss Brydon's shop, it sold everything. And he used to get wee - sweetie mice and all these thing
s
, you know, be a wee toy you know, they would have got it when they were in Dumfries maybe because they occasionally used to go into Dumfries, and - Luke Scott's was a great place for the shop, now that was a shop - where the - Oaten's restaurant is now, 
Luke Scott's, and Plainstones where Binns is was McGowans, and grandma - used to go there, you could get dolls and all sorts of things, so I expect they would have bought these and hid them - before - the night for hanging up your stockings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of shop was Luke Scott's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - Luke Scott's, it sold everything - in the way of school bags, drapery, haberdashery, pails, spoons, knives, forks, it sold everything, John Luke Scott's. I've been in - with my mother and grandma and one thing I'll ne
ver forget, grandma - in Plainstones, the at was McGowans, they were going in for Christmas present, now I remember that, and - everything was very cheap those days because wages were small, and when we went in there was a phonograph playing music, and sh
e
 says, whatever's that? And the assistant said, oh it's something new. And - she was always counting her change you know, and getting out her money. So when we went upstairs, I can't remember what they went upstairs for, but this thing was baring - very v
e
ry loud, there was another one upstairs, and she says, I think they just do that to get the money off you. She was an awful downright person, she never kept anything - inwardly, she let it - you know, she said it out you know. The girl laughed, you know, 
she said, oh we're not so bad as that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about clothes, did you buy clothes in Dumfries?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes, and mother was a great one for making things, at school we wore pinafores in these days, to keep our - frocks clean, and she used to make us pinafor
es, and - then my - my aunt had learned the dressmaking you see, and - she could make things for us. And - mother bought a sewing machine. A Singer sewing machine, that was a great event.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was that a turn the handle one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, it was a treadle one.
 Yes. And we daren't for the life that was in us touch it she - she'd would hardly let us dust it when we were dusting on that Saturday, and my sister, my youngest sister came in - got that in the finish, I don't know if she has it yet or not, but mother 
made many a thing. And - she made rugs. Mother made rugs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Your father worked on shift?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, he worked on shift, day shift and night shift.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When he was at home through the day did he help your mother in the house, was he good at doing odd jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh, well, my father wasna one that bothered much about the house, because - I mean - on his shifts he had - he was out at seven - on - on - morning shift like, on day shift, and - he took his dinner with him, a piece like, just and hi
s flask, and extra tea if he wanted a cup of tea, and - it was home again - by about five. Five at night time. And then the other man who came from Lochmabin cycled - Thompson, I remember his name, John Thompson, he was on like from then - 'til the mornin
g again, my father took over. Now it was fortnightly shifts, and he did that all the time we were small, that was his job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 That was a long shift.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It was long - you know, it wasnae really a hard job. What they had to do was - they had a great big 
- what would you call it, sort of furnace, and they had to keep this stocked with coals, well the coals was just beside the, big - big coals, and they had to keep the pressure up, you know, it hadnae go beyond a certain pressure, and that was pumping the 
water from the bottom of the quarry right up great big pipes, it must have been a good pressure to do that, and it ran past our house where we lived, latterly, not to begin with, but we used to call it the burn, sometimes it was fair in spate you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It would depend how much rain there had been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye. Aye, that's right, and that went on night and day. And that was to keep the - the face - as they called it, of the quarry - clear of water for the men coming in to work. This was the men on the - on
 the bottom, where they were cutting - the stone you see, they were cutting the free stone. They had saws down there for - for cutting and - for \{BLANK\}
 and that sort of things. And - and - they had a railway - ran from there to Nethercleugh, that's the ot
her side of Lockerbie. They had a wee - puggie they called it running there, and - two wagons - or three wagons, whatever much they had, and that stone went all over the country. It was grand stone, the same as what's at Locharbriggs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When you were wee did you ever go up to the quarry with your father when he was working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes. No, not - not when he was working. But on a Saturday, that was the day - when mother made the dinner through the day because we were all at home, the children, it was j
ust three of us then, and - my sister and I used to go up - and - take my father's dinner - he didnae take his dinner with him on a Saturday, we always took it up, sometimes it was stovies, you know, potatoes and - everything - together, vegetables, and -
 
when we got up there we used to - for all we'd had our own we used to get up there to his, and we thought it was far better, and we stayed there, we could stay there, we used to play just round about, he had a wee - a wee hut with a - a - wooden - you kno
w
, just made with slat, that's like railway slabs, and - he had - lots of things in there we used to play with, things we took up like for the children to play with, and we used to play there. And - and he - he took us I remember once to see wee foxes, the
y
 had a hole in the quarry face, up at the top this was. He could - put his engine right you see and leave it a wee while, wasnae far away, and showed us these wee - foxes at play, mother wasnae there of course, she was out likely hunting for these, oh the
y were lovely, can always remember that. Then there was any amount of rabbi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 ts in these days, could always }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
catch rabbits and - we'd plenty
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Would your father ever catch rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh he catched rabbits, he - he used to go when he had his off days, th
ey used to get a day off now and again, no very often mind you, just depended, holiday time when the men were away maybe for a wee holiday, they had to keep the water down just the same for you've no idea how it built up, I don't know where that water cam
e
 from. Of course, it - it's - springs, you see it's a terrible depth, it's derelict now, and I - I've been up several times looking over you know and it's a terrible place to see now, because the water's just about - that off the top of the quarry. It's g
o
t a fence round about, no supposed to be there but - I've been just to look over. And - the - latterly - they had an electric engine I think I told you that, aye, that got all electric when the electricity come in and - it dindnae need much attention at a
l
l you know. And it - it had guard rails round it and I tell you about my father taking the brush off and giving - he was always liked to keep the things clean, anything that would clean he was always cleaning it. Now old man Thompson, he was a nice old so
u
l too, he used to cycle - back and forward to Lochmaben, and - was there for a long long time, and then he died, but - but this time - the electricity was there you see. And they new - new people took over the quarry. He was forty years there altogether. 
S
o that was - that was his job. Ad - and - and - he - he wouldnae retire but he had to retire when he was - age you see, to go, and - after that he went to - Templand House they call it now, Colonel Carr's in it now, but it was a Mr - what was his name cal
l
ed - Mr - Something. Aye. And he went there and - dd the garden. They had a gentleman farmer, he was a gentleman farmer when he was there, he maybe had been an insurance - and the time he was there, father and mother had their golden wedding. They had a -
 
a nice do in the hall for the Templand people, and of our own - relatives, and - Mr - it's funny, I can't remember his name, Mc something was his name, he had a man from Edinburgh staying with him, he was something to do - newspaper, Tom Kerr they called 
him. I've seen his name in the papers since. Well - he drew a portrait of father and mother as they were that night, in their - and that was - aye.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did your father take much to do with you children when you were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 With what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did he take much to do with you, would he put you to bed at night if he was at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh no, it was mostly mother that did that, mostly mother. And - mother took to do with this when we needed punishing, my father - never did anything like that. I - I remember 
once I - he was - he was awful cross this morning, he'd slept in, and - I was getting big then, mind, I was at school like, and - he blamed mother of course for not waking him, they had an alarm but I think they'd forgot to wind it up, and he didna like b
e
ing late, he was always like myself, he liked to be there before hand rather than late, and it was raging away this morning, I said to him, I'll tell grandma, and he - and he - he took his slipper off and chased me away down the road for all I was worth, 
but by the time he got me he never touched me. He was just angry at me speaking back to him, speaking, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was he good at telling stories to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No so much as my mother. He was a fiddler. He was a great fiddler, and that's how he entertained us
 at night. You know, always at night - when he was at home, he got down his fiddle and we used to have grand nights. Mother was a nice singer, she used to sing, although - he was too, my father sung all the Irish songs, I don't know where he had learned t
hem but I know lots of them -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What part of the country did he come from originally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Lochfoot. Lochfoot was where - was where he lived - his - his mother lived there, she was a widow. And the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I wondered if he had come from Ireland originally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No, it was just that he was fond of Irish songs I think he learned a lot of them, and - granny, that's my father's mother - they had lived - you know where the long wood is - in Dumfries, that's up the road, well - she lived in a little cottage, g
randpa, and he - he was not alive when - we were wee, he had leant on the railway, you know, a railway man, and - he had what they called silent pneumonia, he was dead in three days with it and she was left with eight of her family to bring up. Eight of t
hem. Three girls and the rest were boys. I think Uncle Joe was the eldest then my father. We got to know them all, they used to come you know and visit us and that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You did go visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. And then - when I grew up and went out to work I used 
to often cycle, and he was a great cycler my father, I used to often cycle to Lockfoot to see granny, she was living there then. She was an old body then you see, and - she was left with one son, Uncle Jack and he went away out to Canada, this was before 
t
he war like, and - he was working on a fruit farm, he was doing well and keeping her comfortably off here you understand. And - he came over with the Canadians, and - he came to see me twice when I was with Mrs Thompson, and the last time he came, whether
 
he had a premonition or not I don't know, but when he was going away he says, remember and always go and see your granny. And I said I would, which I did, I went with my father. He never came back again. He was killed. They never found him, just have been
 blown up they thought, so that was a terrible grief for her. And she was left - well - she would get a pension from him you see, and - and - oh she was terribly cut up about that, I think that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She must have had a very hard life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She had. Y
es. She had, she was a hard worker. Mother used to go and see her too. I remember mother - taking my youngest sister, this is now we lived at Templand, used to go weekends. And - we were getting bigger you see and could - look after the house. And - she u
s
ed to go for a weekend away to see gran. And - she had a wee granddaughter staying with her, one of the girls - a wee girl, Maggie they called her, and - my mother used to take clothes that were getting too small - for my youngest sister to her, and - I r
e
member mother telling us about her - she was fair delighted this wee thing with the clothes, she was always saying - mother slept in the - in the one bedroom they had, and they had a bed in the kitchen, and it was just - back to back, you could hear, and 
a
ll night my mother said she couldnae sleep for this wee kiddie saying, granny, when will I get on that nice white frock, she kept on about this the whole day, and mother had a sense of humour you know and she was telling us how delighted she was and she t
o
ld us about this, and my sister was sleeping beside her but she was listening to the conversation. Aye. So - she died - she was - funny thing - I canna just remember the year I was in hospital in Dumfries, I canna just remember that. But - to my surprise 
g
ranny came walking down the - the ward, and she noticed me just at once and she said, what are you doing in here? And she was in - she'd been chipping sticks and a splinter had gone into her eye, and it - she lost that one eye through that, they couldna s
a
ve it, but - that was the last time I saw her. I was just young - like young married, just in my twenties that happened, and - she died soon after so - and all - most of the family are die - are dead now. I think my father would be - except for Aunt Maggi
e and I've heard she's died since, I think he was the last of the family to die.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What were the sleeping arrangements in your own house at Templand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1866372\charrsid2967080 Oh - when we were wel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
l. Well, we had - to begin with we had just the two apartments you see, and 
- that was when we were very wee. Well - my sister - she's no - she's about two years younger than me, she was in a wee cot, and I had a bed - in the room. There was a bed in the kitchen, in a racess, and - and a wee cot, but we werenae there long after w
e got - bigger, when there was more of us, we got down to this what you call Shaw Cottage, and that had - two bedrooms, and a kitchen, back kitchen, and two attic rooms upstairs, there was - they were sloped - c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5838476\charrsid2967080 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 ilings but there were attic rooms. So we had plenty of - plenty of room there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have to go to bed at a certain time when you were school age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh well - no. We were usually put away to bed - summertime we didna go to bed, in fact they couldna get us in from our play. I always did my 
lessons though first when I come home from school before I went out to play. Mother used to tell me - she' used to say, I felt sorry for you sitting at your lessons, but I'm no sorry today because I can - you know. I know the advantage now. And Jean, my s
ister, she never bothered with lessons, and yet she got through just the same you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did your mother put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well, not when we were bigger, we were told to go and wash our faces and hands and faces, and then she come in to see that we w
ere really into bed, had we said our prayers and - that sort of thing. But - not when we were bigger, you know, she let - made us be independent and go to bed ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say you had to wash your face and hands before you went to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - bath was Saturday night, I remember that, I tell you - for - first - the girls were bathed, and - put into bed, but not to stay mind, you got up again after the boys were bathed. There was the two boys then. Then we were 
all sat round the fire, dressing jackets on, and - we got - glass of milk, home backed scone with blackcurrant jam, that was the - nicest thing we ever tasted, we looked forward to that. Mother was a grand baker of girdle scones. Girdle scones they were. 
And that was what we got for our supper after the bath and then off to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What kind of bath did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It - it - big - well - latterly we had a tub, when we got too big for the - but a big tin bath, but the tub that mother washed in, we had 
that latterly when we were bigger. I think so. And we were just as clean as what they are now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get a change of clothes or underclothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes, every week. Our clothes were changed every week. Then Monday was washing day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say your mother was a great baker of scones, did she ever make her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Not her own bread, no - no, she didn't make her own bread, we had the shops quite near us and - the bread was only }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7869821\charrsid2967080 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080  five}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7869821\charrsid2967080  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
pence ha'penny for two loaves. Isn't that terrible when you think of it now. And - aye, custom. Aye. But she made bannocks and these sort of things you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 With oatmeal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, just with - like you would make a scone, an oven scone, I make them myself sometime, just with - flour and - fat - margarine
 and lard, some sugar, and sometimes she made them just plain, and you could keep the sour milk if she'd any sour milk we'd any amount of buttermilk in these days, we used to go for buttermilk, and - if she wanted to make an extra special one she put an e
gg in it, we had hens you see, but they werena - yes, that was just like - you know, what a bannock's like, it just cuts like bread. But not all the bother that bread is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I was thinking of more like an oatcake kind of bannock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes. Yes. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And she made her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh, always had lovely jam she made, yes. With plenty of rhubarb, that was - a thing we were very fond of too when we was little, rhubarb jam, not so keen on it now, and my father liked brambles, there was any amount of b
rambles, he used to go and - that was a thing he did, he used to go and fish a lot, when he had spare time, and if he didn't bring fish at mushroom time he brought his basket full of mushrooms and mother used to make ketchup, mushroom ketchup, aye, but we
 
liked the fried mushrooms best, I've got him into that. And - brambles, he used to go if he'd time at all on a summer night you know, when it wasnae his turn on, used to go and help us to pull brambles, the roadsides were full of them, and washed them so 
- she occasionally made bramble jam, we'd always plenty of raspberry jam and - all these sort of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Would you mother use some of the brambles maybe for making puddings and things as well or did she just use them all for jam and jelly?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well -
 mother never bothered with the wine, but I - I know - people that did make it. Wine, all sorts. And jam. Oh aye, jelly, oh yes, it was bramble jelly not jam, there are too many seeds in. Aye, bramble and apple. But - even to this day - that Kate Arnold's
 mother that's having her golden wedding next month, her mother used to make all sorts of wines. Parsley wine, everything you could mention out of the garden, and it was good too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It would be strong stuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. And - I canna - rhubarb wine and -
 and bramble wine, it was really intoxicating the bramble wine. I remember tasting it once and I felt my head fairly wandering. And maybe something put in. Elderberry wine, all these things. And - even nettles, grandma used to get us to go up the roadside
s and gather the new nettles and she made nettle broth and it was lovely, just with the usual vegetables. Nettles. You see, they used a lot of these - things, and she used to make }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 embrocating}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080  and things from - horehound and all that - sort of thing, grandma did, she was a great one for cures you know, old fashioned - things, ointments and that. When I think of all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did she just do it for her own family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh she used to help other - people, I remember - if anyone sprained an ankle or arms or anything she used to give them this }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 embrocating}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
 she made to rub with and - it helped it. I remember I once sprained my ankle and I had to walk from Lochmaben to Templand without my shoe just on the side of the road, and - when I got there she made me sit in a ch
air and she rubbed my ankle with this stuff. In the night it was well down, it was right swollen you know, and I was able to go - back - not with my shoe - fastened, but I had it on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Better than it was anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get meat with your meals every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get meat every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No. No, we did not, not every day. Mostly - the butcher came once a week. And - latterly we had a butcher in Templand, but this was a man, I don't know where he came from, he had - a sor
t of gig affair that opened at the back, and he had the butcher meat, it was all nice and clean, hanging - on - clicks, you know, the - that were - the steak and mince and that. We used to get a - a good piece of meat at the weekend and - well mother made
 
broth or maybe meat for to make hot pot you know, and that would do us maybe two days. Well - that was really the best - time we had for meat. We got rabbits, and - any amount of potatoes we had, we'd - good gardens. And - plenty of vegetables, and someti
m
es we just got soup for dinner, if it was - broth we maybe had rice to follow. Not meat then, might make the meat do for the next day - sort of span it out like that. Then we'd always plenty of eggs and as I told you we kept pigs so we - we - although we 
didn't get butcher meat we'd always something. We never went hungry. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you remember ever seeing your mother taking less so that the rest of you or maybe your father could get more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Took what less?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you think your mother ever went without, went short herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
I don't think so, no, I don't think so. I remember in the wartime, now mother liked sweet things, she was very fond of sweet things, and my father gave up sugar - to let her get the - sugar, you know, for her tea and cocoa a
nd that - whe - he gave up - he - he used to say that - if you set yourself to do a thing, you could do it, that was his maxim. And - he once said to mother as she went out, I remember, and she said, are you not coming in to go to bed? Oh, he says, I coul
d
 do - without sleep. I've seen him do without it if he was busy in his garden. I've seen him do without it for one day, but he was jolly glad to get to bed the next. Aye, he used to do these kind of things. Or if he was keen to get away fishing or anythin
g
 like that. Aye. Aye. Aye. It was trout fishes my father, he never went for salmon. No. And I tell you where he used to go to, he used to go into the loch at Lochfoot, you know, the waterworks, he knew the man there. I forget his name. And he used to catc
h
 these pike, you know, and - they were quite terrible amount of bones in them but it wasnae - I've tasted it mind and it was lovely white flesh, but it was more boiled for the hens, you know, then the hens just had it, it was just for a - an outing for hi
m, he used to go there, he used to go out in a boat on the - on the loch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 But if he caught some trout for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh the trouts were lovely. Aye, they were lovely, the trouts. Lovely. Seemed to be plentiful, they're not so plentiful now. No, they do
n't seem to be, the Kinnel, he used to go and fish in the Kinnel and up to the morning, and there - there's not much in the Kinnel now at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Your father would his breakfast before the rest of you were up in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, he had. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 But were you all together for your meal at night usually?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 We were all together mostly at night for our meal, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about Sundays, what about breakfast time on Sundays, did you get a big Sunday breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - well, no - Sunday was mos
tly the church day. But - I - I told you before, we children didn't go to church, because - we had our Sunday school and then about every fortnight one of the ministers came up, there was three ministers in Lochmaben then, three churches, there's only one
 
now, and - the ministers took turn at coming up and we had meetings in the hall and we were made to go to them with both our parents, but it was mostly father that went to church, he had his bicycle you see, and - was no way of getting down, you had to wa
lk. So - he mostly went to church. And - we had a good dinner when he come home. Then we were sent away up - the road for a walk and told to behave ourselves, remember what day it was. Wasn't allowed to play on Sundays. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What if it was a wet day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well, we'd plenty of books and - things, we were told to read our story books or maybe - mother would tell us stories or - something like that, but you wasn't allowed to play on a Sunday, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You had quite a lot of books in the house then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 O
h we had, yes, we'd story books. Well we'd plenty of uncles and aunts coming you see for holidays and they used to bring us - story books and - and - Anderson's Fairy Tales, Grimms Fairy Tales, we'd all these - things. And the boys -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And you got papers every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And got papers every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get a daily paper as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No. Weekly paper, Weekly News and Peoples Friend. Aye. And - as I told you before we were not allowed - we'd our wee jobs to do on Saturday I tell you, and - well 
I can remember - the story that - was in the Friend in these days was called - Bond of Blood by a Miss C. Mitchell, and it was a lovely story, I used to hear mother and my aunt - that was just ten years older than me, talking about it, and when we got old
 
enough to read a book, I felt I wanted something more to read, and the first book I ever read was Aldersyde by Annie S. Swan. It was a lovely story and I've read it hundreds of times. Oh yes, and I had - that's the grandfather - I'd to read it to grandpa,
 
he used to come in before we had our jobs done, well, can I hear what Jean McFarland's doing? Oh no, it's too soon yet, they haven't go their work finished. So he had to go away until we had our work done. And she knew if we stopped we wouldna start again
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have any games to play in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I've heard of a bawbee for a ha'penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 But not a maik.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. That's a new one. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Could you beat him, could you beat your grandpa?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh he didna like whe
n you beat him. But - but we did beat him occasionally. No, he didn't like to be - he was a good player mind you but we got as good as him because we played that often. Ad - especially after grandma died, he used to come in more, grandma died - when she w
as sixty-nine, and he lived on to be - eighty-four. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Sometimes on a Sunday you would be in your own house and sometimes in your grandma's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, it was mostly in our own - own house that we played, aye, because thar's where the dominoes were yo
u see, and - we'd lots of games, we played tiddly winks and all, just - snakes and ladders and things -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And your mother and father would join in too would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well, no so much my father, my mother would - my father had his - he - he had wha
t he called his time to keep, you know, he had to keep his - time, aye and all that sort of thing and he used to be doing that sometimes at nights too. And mostly when he had time at all he got his fiddle down, he was very fond of it. And we had - a gamek
e
eper and his son lived not so far off us, and they were great too and were grand players too, had some grand nights, listening to them. Then we used to dance you know, caper about the - floor, us children. Aye. Aye, that's what they - that's - aye, aye, t
h
ey have, aye, and then my young sister, and my sister-in-law could - they could play the piano, just by ear, I never - I don't know I was out to work soon, and - we hadna got a piano then but when my youngest sister was - I think - I don't know what birth
d
ay she had but they bought her a - they got the chance of this piano, it was Mrs Meire' piano, and - she - they just - they - they - they just can play by ear and so can - so can my sister's daughters like, just need to sit down and play anything you like
 just by ear. Mary went to music but Miss Eldon said - it was just a throw away of money because she was reverting in - just her own - the way she did play.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you remember any funerals in the family when you were wee?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I don't remember any funerals in the family when I was wee but I remember funerals in the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you tell me what a funeral was like in the village then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - this whole family, they called them Colander, and he worked in the quarry, I remember - I can them you k
now quite plain, and Bill Calendar was in our class in school, and do you know, that family took consumption, and one by one the whole family went. Well that was the first time I'd ever seen anyone dead. And I was taken down to see Billy Colander. I wante
d
 to go. And - a - the funeral was - oh it was a dad affair you know, the minister came up and - and there was a service, I was in there, and - there was - the man from Lochmaben, McMinn they called him, brought the funeral hearse. And it had all - oh it w
as - the horses had plumes in their head, everything - and the men had - the hats with - black - oh mercy on - I was frightened for that, now I can tell, I didna like -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were you just quite young at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I was quite young, was at the school b
ut I was - maybe - eleven or twelve, and it made a great impression, you didna forget it for a long time. But - all the same I think - it was just so that I could see - she'd been very friendly, this wee girl with us and played with us, and I couldna beli
e
ve really that she was - gone, she was among the first to go, and that whole family went. We've often talked about it, mother and - us since, and they lived in a - they had two rooms and a kitchen - and mother used to wonder after, she said - she wondered
 
if the bedclothes had been washed and that after. You know, mother was very particular about that, I don't know but - the father and mother went as well and they all had the same trouble. There was two - there was other two girls and two boys and one by o
ne they were completely wiped out. Now you see - they never were taken away or anything, of course there was no sanatorium at Lochmaben in those days. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you remember going on any outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Any what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Outings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well 
there was - well - when there was Sunday school picnics, and - that was just in a farm cart, they were taking - maybe to a neighbouring farmer, one of the farmers sons - was our - one of our Sunday school teachers, who had - one - two, three, four Sunday 
s
chool teachers, a lot of children came to the Sunday school, and we used to go there to Fishbeck, that was the name of the farm. And - we got - tea and - bags, oh that was a great day and ran races you know and ' and had a grand time, we thought it was lo
v
ely, with flags waving and bunting on the horses, they had them all decorated you know. Maybe four or six carts, some of the children lived quite near the farm so they - just joined in. And they were - and then - then latterly - oh but it got better than 
t
hat latterly. I remember once being taken to Moffat by train and that was a great adventure. We marched to Nethercleugh station, which was - oh maybe three mile, aye, three mile from Templand, but we were all bigger children then, and got in the train. Wh
at an adventure it was, and up to Moffat. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was that your first time in a train do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
I think so. I think it would be. No. No. It wouldnae be. Because mother used to take us to Dumfries about Christmastime to see Santa Claus, that wa
s in McGowans in Plainstones where Binns is now, and we used to go in the train, from Lochmaben, to Dumfries, that was a great adventure too. But this was a grand - trip up to Moffat, we fair enjoyed ourselves because it was a lovely sunny day. And I reme
mber coming back we were fair tired, we got into the train, and back home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And especially if you'd got to walk another three miles when you got off the train?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. Sometimes we went to Lochmaben Castle for our picnics. You know, but that was thre
e miles down from Templand. And you had grand picnics there and they told as about - Robert the Bruce and - oh, when we were children used to supposed to be hunting for his fossil and digging up you know and - you never found it or anything but it was - i
t was wonderful to be there and to hear all about - them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you ever go any further a field with your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. We went once - mother as I told you had two brothers in Newcastle policemen. And we went once - my - sister next to me
, there must have been only the two of us, then. No, no, there was my brother because I remember he had a kilt on and they were all - entertained with this boy with a kilt on, they all come in to see him, but he was just a wee boy, not at the school. Newc
a
stle we went to for a week. Grandma was here so she would likely be doing anything my father would manage you know, but I mean he could always go down - down to grandma's, were quite near. And - we had a grand time. They took us - over to Gateshead, we sa
w
 - you know, the bridge over the Tyne and I remember the - children used to come and play around about and they were fair taken on with our - funny talks, Scotch. Aye. Then later on, before we let school we're allowed to go - our holidays to Paisley, my s
ister and I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 On your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye, on our own. Well - it wouldnae be on our own to begin with because - that aunt - the young - the aunt that was younger than me, she married a contractor there and he had a pony and trap, pony and - well it's a big h
igh trap, and he used to come through for holidays, so they would probably take us back, and we stayed a wee while with them, sometimes a fortnight wed go, and - then we went to - to our uncle Ken's where aunt - you know - the - seven children then, went 
t
o Uncle Ken's. And I remember when we come back - they brought us back, we were never in the train on our own or that, Uncle Ken used to take us places, they were kind to us when we were there, and - Uncle Matthew had to go - on business, about his busine
s
s and took us over Eskin Ferry once I remember that, it was an awful hot day and he went into a shop to buy us strawberries but by the time we got home the strawberries were all eaten up. This was strawberries for our tea. I remember these things. And whe
n
 we come home after our fortnight we went to bed at four o'clock in the afternoon, mother put us to bed, because we were so miserable - being back from the holiday. And she said, well you're never getting away again. And I don't think we ever were. Oh fai
r
 crying ourself to sleep. And - and another thing that vexed us - we had a cat that we'd had for years and years, Topsy we called it, and it wasna very well when we went away, do you know I was frightened to ask about it and it was dead right enough, they
'd had to get to put it to sleep, well between that and the misery of - all the good times being past we were put to bed at four o'clock in the afternoon.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have any other pets, did you have any dogs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mother was frightened of dogs and she liked them but she was frightened of them, no, we had rabbits, and we'd always a canary. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 The same one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh no, we had various ones. But mother always liked a c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 nary. And - we kept pet rabbits, we'd to clean them out and - go up the road and 
gather dandelions and - you know, food for them and - made them up with tea leaves and oatmeal. Aye. And - and then we - they could get out as long as we watched where they went you see, could get out in the garden on Saturdays when we were at home. So - 
a
nd pets, but mother - she liked dogs well enough and funny thing, grandma must have been the same because she had a big dog - I remember it's name, Sally, it was a - a collie, a sable collie, it was a beautiful dog, but it was one of the uncles that had b
r
ought it home. He - he was apprenticed to a grocer in Lockerbie, that was Uncle Sam, he brought this dog home. And it used to - lie in front of the fire and grandma was frightened to shift it to get the grate cleaned. So one day she said to him, Uncle Sam
, he wasnae so much older you see, he was next to the aunt - that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He was the second youngest then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye. Yes. And she said, Sam you'll have to take that dog away and try and get a home for it, for I'm frightened to shift it and it wouldnae touch
 you, but she just had a fear of it, I think mother must have been the same, she wasnae keen on dogs at all. And - Uncle Sam was vexed but he took the dog away. And he gave it to a man in Lockerbie, it was home before him at night. It must have been keen 
to be there. So that was the only dog }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 \endash  th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 at they ever had, that I can remember. She's a nice dog.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When you went shopping to Dumfries, did your father ever go with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well, my father - my father - went occasionally, if there was anything neede
d for the house, you know, if they were - going to buy anything for the house - my father us}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 ed to go, but - mother was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
one that - did the choosing really, my father would - maybe say, well would this no be better, but it always ended up with mother's -
 it seemed to depend on her, aye, but - she - chose things more than my father, and we had a woman used to come - these relatives in - Lochmaben yet, she used to come with a pack on her back. Aye. And - she'd the grandest things, you know, flannelette she
e
ts and - pillow slips and I don't know where she got them but they called her Mrs Kennedy, and - she used to come to the door - front door she always came to and she used to open the door, are you going to draw that long purse of yours today? This was alw
ays how she entered just herself. And sometimes mother bought things from her, for the house, towels or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080  tea}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
towels, sometimes sheets and - I of - many a time wonder mother seemed always to have good - do that, she must have been a saver you know, and - wh
en we were - when my sister marr - was married that same - Mrs Kennedy was alive and she gave us lovely cheese dishes, wedge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
wood - cheese dishes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 As a wedding present?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, as a wedding present. I have mine yet, my sister's broken hers, but - I
've got mine. 'Cos she'd more family and - me, no one about much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It was always your mother got the telling off to do, your father wasn't keen on that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes, my father never interfered, he used to - check us if we were doing wrong and the boys
 too, but he never - he never hit us or anything. He used to give us a telling off and that was enough. But mother used to skelp us, good and hard, if we was doing -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 With her hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, she did, oh yes, just with her hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of thing would you get skelped for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well, if we told fibs for instance. I can remember once I came home and - had.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Say if a child had hit your wee brother, you wouldn't go and wall}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 o}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 p the one that had done the hitting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - we - we might hav
e done but we were frightened for the parents because they seemed to be all alike. I remember once at school - I never forgot this - just in that same house but in later years for that family that was all - sorted the house you know, rebuilt and that. Wel
l
 - a fitter came from Glasgow to the quarry, you know, to - to do any work, permanent and a good wage then. Well - they were Glasgow folk, they called them Young, and the mother was a - fair terrible one for fighting with neighbours. And the woman that li
ved next door to her was a very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 impeccable}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
 body but they seemed to rub each other up the wrong way. And whether they had fought about children I don't know how the fight started, but in the finish this Mrs Young had this other person by the hair of the head
 and trailed her about the close. And the police came up from Lochmaben, there was a police - court over that, well - the children - there was a boy just about my age, Wal - Walter Gelon, he was in my class and he couldnae do his lessons very well, and we
'
re all standing this day around the stove, was a wee stove you could shut up, but the master opened; it when we were getting lessons and the heat come up. And we're all standing - just in a semi-circle, and - it was a geography lesson and he couldnae do i
t
, and he knew fine what he'd get. And the strap was there, and someone came to the door, do you know, he stuck in the stove, time the master was out and burnt the strap. Yes. And none of us dare say he'd done it, nobody. And he tried to get us to say but 
w
e wouldna speak, because you knew what they would do, they were terrible fighting children, these. Well he - he didna get the strap but he got the cane, and that was worse, for he got it round the legs and all, and he wasn't - it - it was - quick tempered
,
 the master you know. Well he ran out of the school. The boy was fair crying, he ran out and his mother went right to the quarry and brought his father. And when his father came knocking at the door he knocked the master down when he opened the door. That
 was another court case. Wasn't that terrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Just not like the other folk in the village at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No, they werena like the village, but they didna stay very long, maybe six month or that but she was a - she was a wee stout woman and round like a
 barrel and red hair and she was a terrible one, and her husband, I don't think he would have been as bad if it handae been for her. As Burns says the women are the bad ones. He always, said the women are the bad ones anyway. I don't think he would have b
een so bad but she would make him do it you see, for doing that to her children. Ah well, these folk are from Glasgow, and that was - the only - family in th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 e village I think, they were impec}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 cable people you know, mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say the policeman had to come from Lochmaben?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, the policeman had to come -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You didn't have any policemen here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 We had no policemen in the village. No. He'd to come from Lochmaben.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did he come round regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, occasionally he did, occasiona
lly he come round on his bike, I expect he had to get papers signed you see for coming on his rounds. Thought that since, he didna get them signed at our house or anything, but - he must have gone maybe to the shop or - there was a - two shops in the vill
a
ge, grocers, that was a - a sculptor in the village. A sculptor, yes, and he's daughter's still living at Eastriggs. She'd seen my name in the paper once and she asked one of the Eastrigg member if I - if my name was Haliday. You see. She'd eighty - in he
r eighties now and - Mary King, she used to go to school with my aunt, you know, the one I'm telling you about. Aye, a sculptor. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of things did he do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well, he made headstones. Beautiful headstone, and used to stand and watch him, 
and did all the lettering too of the quarry stone. And - he could do any sculpting and sometimes he went away and did jobs for other people, you know, at a distance. King they called him. And - he - there was a - shoemaker. One that - soled our shoes, or 
-
 clogs we used to wear to begin with when we were small. And - shoemaker. And I was trying to think if there was anything else, likely we got the - the Post Office back to the village, it was away a long time, but - the village - in the time that the quar
r
y was busy got full up of people you see, although there was - they were all staying - lodging, you understand, in the houses, it was a busy place then. In those days. Two - charabancs used to come up from Lochmaben with the men from Lochmaben worked ther
e. It was the main - source of income - for all round about, the quarry, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did the children in the village think about the policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh they were frightened for him. Yes, they were frightened for him, and - when we lived at the Shaw 
- Shaw cottage - the house next door got empty, and - we'd been playing on the Saturday and it was one of the boys from the next door again that broke the window. Well Willie Sproat, he threw a stone just for mischief you know, but none of us told. And he
r
e this policeman came, but not the Lochmaben one, a Johnston Bridge one. And I was quite a big girl then, I'd be about eleven or twelve, and I said to the boy he shouldna have done that but I never told mother he had done it or anything, never told - we n
e
ver told on each other. So - mother used to say not to tell tales you know. Well - this policeman came, it was a Saturday morning and - he said, get the children in. And mother wondered what on earth was wrong and she said, yes, and she was looking at us 
a
s much as to say, what have you been doing? Oh, he said - it's about the house next door, it's had a window broken and the occupier had - man that it belonged to had been to - to see if he could find out because he was going to nick the parents. He though
t it would be some of the houses near because there was just about four houses. And I said, oh it wasnae us, I said, it without thinking, I said, it was Will Sproat. That was all it wanted. I sure got a lot for telling him. I still -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You said your mother told you you should never tell tales?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you think your mother had more influence on the way you behaved than your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh I think so. There's no doubt about it. Aye, I think so, mother had more influence - over us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was your father the sort of person that you could go and talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 If you were worried about anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes. He would do anything for us. Especially me, they always said I was his favourite. Aye, mostly. He used to - he used to listen t
o me, I can think of that you know, when I was telling him anything. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He had quite a lot of patience with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, good patience he had, yes, we'd a good home life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You were obviously very fond of both your mother and father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were you the kind of family that showed your affection, did you kiss each other often or that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well, do you know, there wasnae so much of that unless it was special days. My; mot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 er used to but my father didn't. No. No, but my fa
ther used to put his arm round us and that and give you a pat on the back or - that sort of thing, but he wasnae one that kissed you a lot. No. No. No, he wasnae. Our uncles and that you know, my mother's side were more on for that but my father wasnae. N
o, he was a quiet - kind of man. Kindly ways he had with him. Very kind he was. And so was mother, they were equally - kind. And they were always good to us even when we were grown up you know, they were always - mother was always buying something for}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 us, a
ny time she came to see us - she always brought us something, my husband had a ten shilling - a - a half a sovereign she once gave him, you know, when they were getting scarce. She had two, she had a sovereign and a half sovereign. And she gave - the sove
r
eign to my aunt you know, because they belonged to grandpa I think originally, and - she gave - I thought she would have given it to me she given it to - him. She gave me - a two shilling piece, the first one minted when - that she had like, when the Geor
ge VI came I was always going to get a pin put in it. But I never had - had done it.
