\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you ever do any part time jobs while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you do any wee jobs while you were still at school that you got paid for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - well - well any wee jobs that I did was to help grandma, you know. Just -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You didn't work for anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So your first job was when you went to the minister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. That was before I was fourteen. I shouldn't hav
e - been leaving school - 'til the June of that year, but in the beginning of the year, an elder that we had in Tampland, of the church, he came up to see my father and mother and said he'd heard of a grand job for me, and if I would go. So mother said wh
e
re was it, and he said, well Mrs Neil Rae likes to get a young girl - and train them for house and table work. If I'd any notion to go, and so - my mother says, oh she - she'll no be left school till June but - I'd been through the classes you see, I was 
t
wo years in the last class. And - my father wrote to the School Board, it was the School Board these days, and - knowing that I was up to standard you see, I got - exemption and off I went to the Manse. So - mother went down with me, - it was just two mil
e
 and a half from home. And it was a lovely day and we were walking down. I just had a wee case I didna know whether I would like it or not you see, but - I was there three years. And - it was table work. I've often said - that at that Manse they had most 
b
eautiful silver - that I ever saw in any of the places that ever I was in. Beautiful silver they had. And - Mrs Rae I think - must have had money in her own right, because they kept a lot of company, more than what a - a Manse usually does, they're always
 
having visitors. And - on communion Sundays they had all the Elders in to dinner. All the time I was there, they don't do it now. But - they had a - what a spread they used to have. They had a cook you see, and then there was a Mrs Manners that lived just
 across from the Manse, she used to come in and help when there was anything extra on. And everything was made at home. There was nothing bought in. For dinner they would have big s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 i}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 rloin - of beef. Four roasted chickens. Beef steak pie. And - what was the 
other thing, there was the four things. Oh a tongue, pressed, ox tongue, and that was sent from the butchers and they had a big press that the cook did all this herself, she'd a lot of work. And - all that was on the table for Sunday dinner, and there wou
ld be trifles, the - the puddings were all - all cold at Sunday, blanc}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
mages and - trifles and - apple tart, but - it was just - put into the oven when they - come home from - communion, it soon heated through, it was cooked, I mean just heated. And - tea o
r coffee, and biscuits and cheese. Well - the afternoon communion was at three o'clock, so they didna go away, just stayed in the drawing room, it was a big - big Manse, beautiful big rooms they had, and - they had tea before they went out again. No, I'm 
t
elling a lie, they went out they had a cup of tea just in their hands in the drawing room, and then had the tea, so that we were well treated. I remember telling Mr Gibb, he was the minister - about four, five, six years ago, since he went away from Lochm
a
ben, and he asked me one day, he said, I've been hearing that they used to always give the Elders and anyone in connection with the church dinner, I said, so they did, because I was there - and helped to wait at the table, you see. And he said, dear me, h
e
 says, what a work it must have been. I said, it certainly was. And - all these communion clothes were washed at home, there was sending - no laundries these days you see, they were all done at home. But this Mrs Manners used to come and help the cook to 
do the washing. And I had to do the cooking.
