\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What was your job when you started there first, what did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - when I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080  house}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 table}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 maid I was, between the house and table, they had a woman come in to help with the rough work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So what sort of things did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye, just was to train me for this you see. And - the first thing was to - in the morning, was to light the study fire. They usually sat in the study, what was the minister's study. And - when they were alo
ne had their meals there too, but if there was any visitors the dining room was always used. And - then - after I had the fireside cleaned up and - the room swept and dusted, I used to take up - their breakfast, they had no early morning tea. I'd to take 
i
t up to their bedroom, they were elderly you see, they were elderly people. And - each had a tray. Mr Rae's was a - a little - sort of table thing sat on legs, oh but first of all I had to give them their - morning doses. Their morning doses. Mr - Rae too
k
 Eno's Fruit Salt, you know, and Mrs Rae took something else, Saline of some sort of I had that to do first, and then - take up hot water in a jug and - and there was cold water in the bedroom you see, and give them each their morning doses and then - the
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 ir breakfast. Mr Rae - took Sco}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
ts MOF food, that was - and then just a plain breakfast after, marmalade, toast, and - or a roll or something like that. Mrs Rae - sometimes had a cooked breakfast, sometimes not, but this was always ordered the night before s
o that I knew - and then - after that was cleared away I used to - in the wintertime, it was cold days you see when I was there, I had to clean up their grate while they were in their beds, they didna get up early. They'd always a fire on in their bedroom
.
 No labour saving devices with gas or anything like that in these days, it was all coal fires. So I had that to clean up, but that's all I did like, just cleaned up the grate and - and - if it was cold morning lit the fire again. Depended on how long they
 were going to be in bed. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What time did you have to be up in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh I was always up about six o'clock there. Six. And - it was a coal - range in the kitchen, of course that was the cook's job you see. And then - if the drawing roo
m had been used at all, it wasnae - used much - unless - on her afternoon, she had afternoons for ladies coming in, and the fire was on then but - it was only to dust over you know if it hadnae been used. So - I washed the breakfast dishes - after that, a
n
d then - I used to sweep the stair down or - do - do a job like that, you couldnae do the bathroom or anything like that 'til after they were up. And - some days I had the silver to clean, I canna remember - the order of that now, but there was plenty to 
d
o. I mean it wasnae a hard place but you were kept at it. And - the cook had a lot to do, she was - kept very busy, she did all the baking and everything. All sorts of scones, I'd never seen so many scones of - every description, potato scones and - and -
 
oatmeal potato scones. And - they used to make scones with maize meal, they believed in all these sort of things. And she'd plenty to do. And big ironings you know after the wash and - there was - always a lot of iron, I used to help her with that, servie
ttes and tablecloths and everything was done at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She wasn't really just a cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No, she was a cook general. That's what she was. Cook general. But if there was anything special on or when they had visitors we always got help. This Mrs Manner
s used to come - if they were having parties or anything, she used to come in and help in the evening. And they'd always a lot of visitors in the summertime. Friends of their own, and they went away too. And every Friday they went always to Worthing or so
m
e of these places down south for the baths you see. And - what was I going to say - when Mr Rae was away we really - didnae get our holidays because there was always a minister too come in his place, so we had to stay there, but we got it easier you see b
ecause - there was just the minister staying there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 There wouldn't be entertaining to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
There wasnae so much to do, there was just his bedroom and - he was a younger man that came always, so - he got up early, I didna need to carry the food up the stairs, and that sort of thing. But they were -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about your holidays then, did you get any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes, we got holidays. But we got the holidays at different times. I remember once - I got my holidays when they were away, but the cook didn'
t because the minister was coming, but she had a sister came to stay with her, and they asked me if I would take the dog with me. Oh dear. My father says, dear me, when he saw the size of the Girlie - Girlie they called it, he says, how on earth do you fe
e
d that dog? And I said, well it just gets what we got you see, but - being at home it couldna get the feeds that it got at the Manse. He says, I'll be sending a fine big bill, but this was only a laugh, only fun. I remember my father laughing when he saw 
it. It was a nice dog but you - it did take a lot to keep it you know. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What was the food like for you at the Manse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh splendid, we just got what they - got. Grand food. There was no lack of food. No, we just got what they got. And on the Fr
iday evenings, I was thinking about this this morning, I was cleaning up the grate, I'd always to go in - they had one son, and he was out in - Africa, and every Friday evening, in case they had forgotten - about five o'clock - I'd to go and ask them if t
h
ey had remembered Mr Neils letter, because - they were forgetful, a bit forgetful. Mr Rae wasn't so bad, but Mrs Rae was kind of forgetful, and - if they had - had forgot to get it ready they would be writing it all week you know, their own daily - what w
as going on, and I had to - go and remind them, sometimes they had forgotten, and it would have been - goodness help me if I had never remembered. I had to keep that in mind. And on a Sunday we got home - got no evenings out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 None at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 None at
 all. Church every Sunday morning. And - on - second Sunday after dinner, I got away home. But on the Sunday that the cook was out, Mrs Rae told me to invite my sister down - for the afternoon. So - she, my sister, was down every Sunday afternoon. Ad - I 
used to get going up the road a wee bit with her, about six o'clock she usually went away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What time did you have to be back on the Sundays that you went home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Half past nine for prayers. We got prayers every night and - I tell you a story about 
that. Didna matter if it was - rain, hail, thunder or lightning, you'd to be in for prayers, and if you were late they waited for you. Would wait 'til you changed if you were soaking, it wouldna matter whether you were soaking or not, they would wait for 
y
ou to change. So - after I'd been there maybe about two years, Mr Rae found that - there was two services every Sunday you see, he found that things were getting a bit - too much for him, so he applied for an assistant. And the first - he had three assist
a
nts while I was there, and the first one that came was a Mr Hunter. And - he was a - well - he wasn't middle aged, he was further on than that, but he was quite a good - preacher. And he stayed in the Manse for a little while, but this was going to be too
 
much work for the cook and she complained. And - they found a place for him to - to go. And - what happened to him, something happened to each of them. It came - very frosty weather, and they held the curling on the castle wall at Lochmaben. And this was 
-
 at a weekend, they were having a curling match. Well - Mr Hunter - it appeared was very fond of watching it so he was on the loch this day, and Mrs Doctor Sanders was one of the ladies sitting - up at the window of one of these villas that looks onto the
 
castle, and she saw the ice breaking through her glasses, and a man disappeared, the first one was her own husband, Doctor Sanders, but they got him out, the ice had been - melting a bit in - right in the middle of the loch. And the next one that went in 
w
as Mr Hunter, the minister. And - he got a chill and was very very ill for a long time. And after he - got better I think he had pneumonia looking back, he didn't come back, he gave up the job. So the next one that came was Mr Ure, Ure, a young minister, 
q
uite a young - student he was, very nice, tall young man, I'm sure he was six feet. And he got in at this same place where Mr Hunter had been staying. And he studied so hard that he went off his head. And had to be - had to go away, and was, you know, in 
a
 place - he would get all right, but that was what happened to the second one, wasn't it unfortunate? Well, the third one that came - was a Mr Tate, a man I should think between thirty and forty looking back now, and - the cook - had left by this time, he
r
 mother died, and she had to go home to keep house to her father. So we got another - girl - Geddes was her name, June Geddes, and she came from Hightae Moss, a cottage there, and - she was a very pretty girl, I can remember her, she had - black - curly b
l
ack hair, wavy, you know, not done with pins but - really naturally. Beautiful skin she had and red red cheeks, she was a very fine looking girl. And they called her mother, she must have taken after her mother, the Moss Ross. That's what she was called. 
W
ell, this Mr Tate was the new minister, and couldn't - we used to sit - there was the minister there, and Mrs Rae there. And Mr Tate was just there, well we sat just beside the bookcase, just at the side of them, and you know he fastened his eyes on this 
g
irl - it must have been love at first sight I think because - I left, I'd been three years there and I left, but I knew fine - I - I was getting on, I would be what, I would be fourteen, fifteen, sixteen, I would be - over sixteen by then, I knew fine tha
t
 there was something between them, because if he got a chance he was always talking to her you see. So after I left, she told me this herself, we corresponded, and - there was one day - Mrs Rae was out at a meeting, and when she come in, they were - so bu
s
y standing talking at the hall table, that - they never heard her 'til she was right in the hall. And she just looked at them, she'd never suspected anything you see, and she says, what are you doing here June, get to the kitchen. Just like that. So Mr Ta
t
e - turned round and said, Mrs Rae, this girl - I hope to marry. He'd proposed to her and everything was all done and nobody knew - he'd been to see her parents and everything. And - here I happened to meet her one day in Lockerbie, I was in Lockerbie the
re, and she was beautifully dressed, she was a fine looking girl, and - she told me this and I said, and are you getting married, I said, good for you? Marrying a minister you see. So she told me this -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did Mrs Rae have to say about this then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh - furious. Furious. Fair furious, and so were all the girls in the choir for they were all setting their caps at him. They really were, you know. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Why was she annoyed, because it was from her house they were meeting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, because she
 didna know anything that was going on, and she would like to think it was above her, it wouldnae be above her at all, I mean he was - he was a clever man and had got on, but they were quite nice - decent people. So - some had more money than others that'
s
 how I look on them. Well - anyway, she told me that they were getting married in such a like day, and that - they were going to Hawick, he'd got a church Hawick, but alas - it never came off. It appeared - oh I was sorry for her, the last time I saw her 
she was fair heartbroken. She'd a beautiful engagement ring on and everything. And - it appeared - that when - now this was the funny thing about it, she was ill}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 gitimate, she'd been born but - her name was Geddes, well her mother's was Vatchet, she'd been 
born, Mr Watt wasn't her father you see, she'd taken her mother's name, and - the church people - shows you how strict they were, gave him the choice to marry her and give up his church, or - take the church and give up - and that's what he did, he gave u
p his church, or - take the church and give up - and that's what he did, he gave up here. Wasn't it terrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I didn't think the church would have been as strict as that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Neither - oh but that church was. That church was, and the Rae's were terri
bly strict, if you were - at that time - I don't know, it's not now, but - if - if any girl had made a mistake and had a child like before she was married, this was taking place when I was at the Manse, they would not be admitted into the church again, un
t
il they had stood what they called the session, Burns writes about that. Yes, but it was in my day too. That's honestly now, and I could quote you two or three instances of it. And Mr Rae once preached from the pulpit about brides coming to the church you
 
know and not bridges at all, and - these Hoskiths left the church over it because both of their daughters was expecting when they were getting married, and they took it for themself, well - these girls had to come in front of all these Elders and admit - 
a
nd the minister - admit that they had done wrong, and - asked for pardon. And what I couldnae - I didnae see it then, but since, when I grew up and knew the character of some of them that was Elders, I didna think it was right at all, and I spoke out my m
ind and told them that. But that's what they did in these days, so - you see - when they knew that she was ill}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 egiti}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
mate, that - the - Mr Watchet wasn't her father, and that she would only have her mother's name on - you see - on her birth certificate they w
ouldnae have him - as the minister, unless he gave her up, or - went out of the church, and he gave her up. She - she married a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It doesn't say much for him does it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It didnae, I - he fell in my estimation, I thought he was a nice man, of cour
se so did she. And - oh my, it - what consternation there was because Mr - Watchet, he was a gamekeeper and he was a - he seemed to be a very strait laced man, he had a daughter of his own, Mary, and she was working in Lockerbie, of course I was in Locker
b
ie then, and Mary knew me through her sister. And - she used to go with a young man, and do you know - on her nights off - she never knew where her father would be - about the street watching her to see that she was - behaving herself. And - one night - w
h
en her mother woke up, he was sitting in bed with a razor, going to cut the mother's throat, it put him off his head. Put the - father off his head, the worry - about this. Aye. So he was in the Crichton for a while, but he got all right and of course - h
e died, Mrs Watchet, died and I never heard anymore except, that Jean - married - a soldier, in Edinburgh, she went away from - her native place altogether, and she married a - a regular soldier, I heard that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were the Rae's very fussy about the way you behaved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh mercy, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh but if you had had boyfriends as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh got no boyfriends in. We did - they - everybody that came - to the door - had to - come to the front door, there was no back door. There's a big gate - it's still there
 yet at the Manse, and that was kept locked. And - if anybody wanted out all the bowlers - boards, you know, for bowling, carpet bowling - was kept in - one of these sheds, but they had to come to the front door and get the key, and then we had to lock th
e
 - gate after them, they'd to come to the front door always, no - we werenae allowed - you were allowed visitors like, but unless you were - engaged to a young man or - well - there was nobody there, I mean I was too young, and - I think Maggie - Wilson, 
that was the cook's name, she'd had a young man but he'd been killed and she never had any more time you know, she never married at all, because I knew of her until the day she died. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How did you get on with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - she was a - you know,
 she was a hard working - woman, but I liked Jean best because - I'd only been there a day or two - the young girl that had been - a funny thing, the young girl that had been there before me - got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080  table}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
maid's job at Newpart where we were before we came 
here, with Mrs Keswick of Newpark and she used to say to me in the morning, have you not that done yet? Have you not finished in there yet? Eeh, you're not like wee Jean McGeorge. This was always - well - well, I was only new, but - I mean apart from that
, she was - you know, she was a good cook and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did you have to call her, did you call her by her first name?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Maggie just. Aye, oh yes, we sat together you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And what did Mrs Rae call you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Martha. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She used first names, what did you call her, did you have to call her madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh no, just Mrs Rae. Oh they were - they were nice people, and - they were - they were really good - good to us you know, in every way, we got whatever they were getting we got, we didn'
t have anything different than what we had, and - they used to - when I - when I left them there I got that Bible from Mr Rae, he gave me that Bible. And - she told me how to - you know, gave me a great lecture about walking the straight and narrow path y
o
u know, of course it was all for my good - before I came away, they were very - very - religious people, very strict, and - he went on a bicycle up to visit you know, Templand, the folk round Templand, and I'd always to lace up his boots for him, he could
nae - I'd lots to do for them you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You were a personal maid as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
I was a personal maid. Yes. And he used to say tome, now - if you bring me down word - when you go up today, where's your grandpa this weather that he's no coming to church.
 So I had to bring him down. But they were kind you know, they just made you like themselves, they took a - a charge of you, it was just - really like being at home. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of place did you have to sleep, did you have a room of your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes, we had a room of our own. And - I was going to tell you about - one night. Oh dear, I'll never forget it as long as I live. One night - when these bowling boards were out, these two lads - we knew them, we knew plenty of lads but we darena have them
 in, and - this one was a joiner, and he had a fancy for this Jean you see, and - they - one that worked with him, he was a Lochmaben lad too so they said - are you not allowed any lads in at night? And we said, no. So - they said, well - come to the gate
 
tonight. What time have you to be upstairs? Ten o'clock. Well, come to the gate about half past nine, and we'll have some chocolates for you, for both of us. So they did, they brought us boxes of chocolates, we were standing talking at the gate, we know t
hey - knew they were quite safe in the study. But Mr Rae always come through to my pantry, the last thing at night, for - he always took whisky, and - what was it - seltzer he called it, I made it, they learned me how to make it, a great - big }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 siphon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 , you g
ot the powders at the chemist. Soda water is was really. And he always come through, so - while we were standing there, I don't know whether he was early or not, but we saw the light going on in my pantry. Oh we just about dropped, so we left the lads, yo
u know, and slipped in the back }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 oor and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 We slipped into this bee room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What was the bee room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Bee room? Bee. Bee. He kept bees. Bees, the minister, and he got them - got a lot of honey, and this woman that used to come in, Tibby they ca
lled her - she was grand at - at - helping the minister with bees, I couldna - I didna want to learn anything about them because we'd had them at home, and I was frightened for them. But Tibby could work with them too, they'd a lovely big garden, an enclo
sed garden, and he used to work away there amongst the flowe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 rs, they got a man to come in a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
nd do the vegetables, strawberries and - beautiful garden they had, and - we stood there in this bee room, 'til he went through to the study and we were past - past o
urselves because we'd to go past the study door and up the stair and we took off our shoes, it was after ten o'clock you see, and when we got into the bedroom - we both went into Maggie's bedroom and we - of course it was Jean then, and - when you recover
 we said, never again will we do that, and we never did. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you feel homesick when you went away first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh terrible. I remember mother used to come down and see me sometimes. Saturday afternoons. Mrs Rae would say, now when your mother 
coming down to see you, tell her if she's down - for messages to come round and have a cup of tea with you, they were very good that way. So - they took her into the study, and of course I didn't know anything that was - passing, but - Mrs Rae had said to
 her - that I cried and I cried, so I did, you see, my wee sister was just - well I was nearly leaving the school when she was born, the youngest one you see, and I used to take her out in her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 pram at night, and - I missed her terribly, it was her I was mis
sing more than anything. But after about three months, it took me three months to get - I never thought about wanting away or anything, I knew that I was - doing right to the working you see, but - I would have been quite happy if mother had said, come ho
me. But - I stuck in it and I stayed there for three years. That was as long as she kept them, this was the training you see. Only like my husband did, I only got three pounds - in the six month, that was all he got. But he had good food and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You were lucky with your food weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. Oh were lucky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about clothes, did Mrs Rae give you a special uniform to wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. White - linen aprons in the morning and - nice fancy one for the afternoon. You know, muslin they were. The - t
he morning one - was - linen you know, that unbleached calico - stuff, when it was boiled they - they - turned white you see. Maggie did these but - but - and Mrs Manners, but I took all my other things home. Mother told me to take my personal washing hom
e and she would do them, because -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get a dress to wear under your aprons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did Mrs Rae provide that for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Either - either blue - or - print dress, either blue - I had a blue one - and I had sort of - reddish one she gav
e me too, dresses to wear. And black in the afternoon when you had your wee - fancy apron on. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you ever have to do any of the shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was that one of your jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I used to go out often and do the shopping in the 
morning. There was a little fish shop - not far off the Manse in the high street, and - Mrs Rae would maybe have - told the fish lady the day before - he'd have some fillet in the morning, she took a breakfast, Mr Rae didna always take it, so often we had
 fish, we'd always something for breakfast. Bacon and eggs or boiled eggs or - fish or something like that, we always got our breakfast, we did - every morning. We didna get porridge - thank goodness. I'd had enough at home. Oh I hated it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So you were fed very well then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye. Aye. We were fed well. Cup of tea - ten o'clock, cup of tea. Ten or half past. Or - you know, dinner was at one. They had a dinner - through the day always, and then just a supper at night you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You would have to wait 'til after you had served their dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well, I'd - they didna want you to wait on them when they were alone, you just took it in - and Mr Rae - gave out - I had to pass Mrs Rae's hers you see, and then - you're finished. They didna keep you w
aiting on them - when they were there alone, but when they had visitors you did, always waited on them, so go ours in between, taking in the next course like dinner, we would - we would take out - I would take in the meat, and - then as soon as it come ou
t if it was roast or whatever it was, we had our - meat, and then - take the pudding in, by the time I come back from putting the pudding in, Maggie had the meat cut up for us and we got our dinner, we just had it - along with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It sometimes wouldn't be very hot then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh well - maybe she heated it, I don't know, there was always a grand - got a beautiful big range, she maybe put it in - when I brought it out she maybe put it into the oven, I can't remember that. But it was grand food. I think -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was it a big kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. A monstrous big kitchen. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was that the only place that you had to go apart from your own room when you weren't working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, just the kitchen, but it was comfortable mind. We'd - had - comfortable cha
irs each, and - we had each our own pantries, Maggie had a pantry and I had a pantry. And I had to save all the tea - all the tea that was left, you know, sometimes the teapot wasn't emptied, Mrs Rae watered all her flowers with tea, she'd the loveliest g
l
ossy leafed plants and that's what she said - put water in it like but she always did that. She looked after all her plants herself, in the drawing room window and - at the dining room window, there were great big - all her windows, the drawing room windo
w opened into the garden, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 F}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
rench window. It was a nice house, old fashioned now, it's still the same - Mr Dibb told me, he says, we still have the stone floor in the kitchen. And - it's not a Manse now, they call it the - what do they call it now, it's a 
name - St Magdalen's - no, Magdalen's House, it has a different name now, but - the Manse now is - the Barras. The Barras Manse. But - it's let to a - teacher, there's a - a Mr Roberts I think his name is, he's in the Manse now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say there was a stone floor in the kitchen, did you have to wash the floor,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh no. No, Maggie did that herself. Or else - Tibby, that woman that come in to do the rough work, it depended if we had visitors, they always got help - so they must have had means because I mean - a minister's stipend wouldna have run to all that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say Mrs Rae used to have the ladies in the afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of folk came there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mrs Douglas of Halleaths came, the lady from Halleaths, she was up there - a consta
nt visitor, and - she used to come up and - and a basket of fruit handed me this, this was for Mrs Rae from the greenhouses at Halleaths. She was an awful nice lady, a real lady. And all these maids used to come to church, and they all had little bonnets 
o
n. Oh the staff they kept, you know, the butler and - and footmen, she'd always a man with livery with her, you know, it was a - a carriage and pair, you know what I mean. Not a motor car. Aye. A brougham. Well that's what used to come for her and then - 
i
f she was going to make a long visit he used to go away and she would tell him to come back at - maybe half past four, this would be afternoon tea they had brought in the drawing room, a - big silver tray and - oh - they'd beautiful silver, I told you tha
t before, and the nicest silver ever I saw. And - in any of the places.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did she have more than one visitor at a time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes, it was an open - afternoon. Unless she had asked Mrs Douglas specially, but she just used to come, and - ladies th
at she knew, canna remember them all, the doctor's wife used to come, Doctor Reid. And - Doctor Reid's wife and - and - lots of ladies that lived in these villas you know down by the loch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It was all the people from the bigger houses that came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh aye. Oh yes, but they used to have other people in too. It would be her at home day. Mr Rae used to - there used to be people come for advice to him you know, and he used to - treat them very nice. It was really a - a nice - they were really a nice cou
ple.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How did she get on with just the ordinary folk in the village, the ordinary people in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh they all looked up to her. Aye, they - she used to have a - a guild afternoons too, and - there was the Girls Friendly Society, that's the 
young folk you know, they still have it. And - they used to - they used to have an afternoon for them, and they used to be in the drawing room but get their tea in the dining room all round the big - what a big table it was, and then they used to have gam
es, hoop-la and - enormous ground they had in lawn out through the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2039055\charrsid2967080 F}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
rench window. She used to have - lots of things like that, she did a lot of entertaining. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about the people who came to stay, what sort of folk were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh they were 
very nice, very nice people. Mr Rae had a nephew I think he would be minister of Brydekirk, the Reverend C.A.A. McVane, I could remember their name, I can remember things - and - oh I've a good memory, and they used to always to be in spare bedroom with t
h
e dressing room, there was a dressing room attached to this - to the big spare bedroom, and they were always in there. And - they had morning tea taken up, you see it was different for visitors. And - used to have their friends came from down south and - 
M
r Neil, the son was never home while I was there. From Africa, he never was home, of course I was just three years there. But he never was home. They went away when they left Lochmaben they went to live in Edinburgh. And I saw first - Mr Neil Rae's death 
and them Mrs Neil Rae's. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When the visitors came how did they treat you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, just the same, they were just like themselves, just the same. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 None of them sort of bossed you about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. They didnae, no, they were very nice people
, they were just - just like themselves. I - I've - often though - how nice and friendly they were you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You were there for three years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mm-hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Where did you go after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - I went home after that. By home I mean - Mrs Wilson 
of the Commercial Bank House in Lockerbie - wanted a house table maid, and of course - she knew fine there - that you got a good training from Mrs Rae, so Miss Wilson - arrived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 This was before you actually finished with Mrs Rae?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Before actually
 finished. And - of course Mrs Neil Rae wouldnae know anything about her you see. Or she wouldna have advised me to go, so - I said that I couldn't do anything until I had - seen my parents, but that I would get in touch with her. So I can't remember how 
much they gave me but it was quite a good}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 wage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did you get from Mrs Rae, after the first year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well I - it went up every year, but I really can't remember, now that honestly I don't remember, but after the first year you got more, you see, 
you were getting able to do better. It would be to - sort of encourage you, you see. Well anyway I can't remember what I got when I left, but anyway - they were giving me more there, I can't remember what it was really, but - when I talked to my father an
d
 mother they said, well - it's quite near, I mean Lockerbie wasnae so far away, although they did - I didna know Lockerbie. So - mother - went with me, I got - agreed to go. There was - Mr and Mrs Wilson, they were bank - he was a banker, commercial bank,
 
and Miss Wilson, at home. Mr George was in a bank in Edinburgh. But he was at home for holidays. So - when we got to Lockerbie we'd to come up from Lochmaben with the train, I was carrying my case and I - we didnae know where the place was you seed. So - 
I
 said to the porter, or mother would say - can you tell me where the Commercial Bank is? He looked, he says, the Commercial Bank? Are you going there? And I said, yes. Eeh my lassie, you're going home. Now I kennedit - you see, he meant it wasnae a good p
lace. I was dumped right away. So - we went and rung the bell, same there, the back door locked. But worse, there was bars on the window there, you see, for the bank.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Not for your benefit, for the bank?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So - no. So - mother says, well - you'll n
o be staying if it's no a good place, so dinna worry yourself. So - she seemed quite nice, we saw Mrs Wilson, I hadnae seen her up to then. She was an elderly lady too and her husband too but he was still - working there. He was still manager of the bank.
 
So - they were quite nice and gave my mother a cup of tea, so I thought oh it's maybe no so bad as - as they say. And - there was a girl came the same day, we both knew - from Closeburn Jenny McDowell, and she was an awful nice girl. Her father was gameke
eper at Barraby Castle at Closeburn. And he seemed a nice man, he came there, of course she was older than me, and we were good chums for a blessing, we got on well together, because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of job was she to do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well, just the same work
 but Jenny had - cook general you see. And - after mother was away we were set - sitting at our own cup of tea, and I says, well, I telled her like what the porter had said. She says, well - I didnae get a good report about it either, but, she says, that 
w
asnae 'til after I had engaged to come. And - Mrs Wilson came - there was a speaking tube in the kitchen, you could speak down from the dining room. And she said she would come down and tell us about our work, after we'd had our tea. So down she came. And
 
- she said, now - at ten o'clock - lock the back door, and lock the front door, this was me. Jenny to lock the back door, lock the front door, and bring the keys up to the dining room on a tray - a wee - silver tray. So I did that. Now the house had been 
on fire we couldna have got out, because our bedroom, we'd just the one bedroom there, the bedroom had bars on it you see for the bank - premises were down the hall. The kitchen had bars, the pantry had bars, every place had bars, we were barred in.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You were sleeping downstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Sleeping down there too, with bars on the window and a very small bedroom it was. But as long as we were happy together it didnae matter. So the following morning - I had the dining room to do, it was the dining room they 
sat in there, they had a smoke room, a dining room and a drawing room on the first floor, but mind they were up a stair, it was a heavy place to work. And then - the old people's bedroom was on the same floor as the dining room. But Miss Wilson slept up -
 
on the top, very top. Like its up - one, two, three, four storey building. It's still there. So - in the morning - before - the town clock had stopped ringing six I had to be up for the keys. And - sometimes it was a scramble because - they often had part
i
es too, and - you were lte getting to bed and sometimes slept in. I've seen me just - running up with my frock on, nothing underneath to get the keys and then what a job to get dressed, because as soon as you were up she was up. The first morning I was bu
sy doing the grate - in the dining room when I heard a squeak, I could - I could hear better then, here she's standing at the door to see if I had the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 drug }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 it down on the top of the carpet in case I was doing anything she hadnae told me. And - she jus
t seemed to go about all the time from the time you were up watching. And - I'd to open the window - showed me the window that was opened to air the room, see, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 V}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 enetian blind, oh my goodness, they were the bane of my life. Big one in the middle, two at the
 side, and then two - further over, and on a Wednesday I'd to go up and clean these when they were in the room sitting, they watched you like hawks, if you missed one - you missed one, they sat and watched everything you did. Well - we didna get fed there
 
either. The food we got, margarine, no butter. Everything locked past, sugar, tea, and everything locked past. And - Wednesday was her at home day, and used to sit at the dining room window watching - the street to see if anybody was coming to her at home
 
days, we discovered this through time. And then - if they saw any ladies like or any cars stop in the road - cars in the vogue by then - they used to - they had a sort of gas - I don't know what you called it - it was a - a long thing like that, and you l
i
t it, and stuck into the heart of the fire, you see, and this blew up the fire like as if it had been on for ages, and the room would be stone cold, 'cos it was always the drawing room if ladies come in. Well, when the drawing room fire was on you had to 
put }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 drug }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
it from the door, right up to the fire, you daren't walk on the carpet, she thought it was too good you see for us to walk on, and - clean the grate that way. And she was up as usual watching. But - what was worse than everything she used to put ha
lf crowns and things below the carpet to see if we lifted the rug. But I told her one day, I said you don't need to put that money - there to tempt me Mrs Wilson, because I don't steal what's not mine, I just said it. Oh, she says, I didn't do that. Now, 
I
 says, if that money dropped it couldn't drop right into the middle of the carpet, but they never hid it, you see, everybody knew. So at once Jenny says, well I don't know about you, she says, I was ill for about a fortnight, just malnutrition I think, an
d they got my sister - Nean to come - and - do my work, they wouldna let us home because they knew fine I wouldna come back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How long were you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 A year. Well - we didnae get any money, we were only paid once the six month we were engaged. J
enny McDowell says, now, she says - please yourself, but she says - I'm leaving. She says, suppose I get nothing, she says, I couldnae stick this, so she wrote to her father - to come, and - get her away. And - her father arrived a nice - big - nice looki
n
g man, and he said, would you ask Mrs Wilson if she would speak to me. Well, what could I do, I had to go up to the dining room and said Mr McDowell - would like to speak to you. I'm not going to speak to him, she says, send him in to Mr Wilson in the ban
k. I says, by }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 J}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
ove, that's the very bit I wanted to get. So in he went to the bank, of course I didnae know what took place, Mr Wilson had a room to himself in there. There was three or four clerks, but they all knew, the clerks and everybody knew what a pl
ace it was. So - he said, my girl is not getting fed here Mr Wilson. He said - they're not - they're - neither of them are getting their food, he says, of course I'm speaking for my own daughter, and, he says, it's no place at all this, he says, you've an
 awful cheek to advertise for girls to come to this place. He said, but could she have her money, she's worked and deserves the three months pay she's worked. No, you get no mon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 ey}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080  he says, six months engagement, if you br}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
ak it you can't get any money. Well
, he says, it doesn't matter for the money, and he opened the door then, so that the clerks would hear him, and he says, never did I think such people as you existed, in the - at this enlightened day, but, he says, I'm taking my daughter away now, and tha
n
kful to have her in my - under my own roof tonight, and all the clerks was - they were pleased you see. So - Jenny went away and there I was left. So - when I went home, we got a weekend, I forgot, once a month. I said, mother I must get away from there b
e
cause there's no cook now, and she was coming down and - it was worse than ever, and just myself, no one to talk to. So my mother says, oh - the - the - she seemed all right. You see, she was all right with my mother and they would think I was just - mayb
e
 being led away with Jenny, with her. They got an old woman, I forget her name, she was seventy, and she couldn't cook at all. She came in, and she was no company for me, so I says - mother says, you stick this six month - we'll get you away then. Well - 
f
rom then they were far nicer to me, but this was what was coming on the turn you see, and I must have been suiting them because they - they honestly didna want me away, and in fact after I left them at the year's end - Miss Wilson saw me from the window a
n
d came and said, would you not like to come back to us and - and mother'll give you - I forget how much money, but I said, oh no, I'm not coming back, and I hadnae got a job, but I said, I'm not coming back. So - when I went - to one of the places I did g
o
 to eventually - the lady went to Mrs Wilson for a reference, you see, you had always to have two separate references. Oh, she says, I wouldn't take her, she's not at all a strong girl. She was ill several times while I - while - she was with me, and I do
n
't think she's really suited for the - for the work. So - she had - wanted me to go, this lady, and she said to the - to the - husband, well - I've got neither - not such a good report of the girl, she's not very strong. He says, how long was she at the b
a
nk? She says, a year. Well, he says, take her, she deserves a gold medal for staying a year. That's as sure as - the lady told me herself. Oh yes, I forgot about that. They were having a - a big do, Mr George - was coming of age, and they were having a - 
a
 - it was really a dinner in the middle of the day, and I hadna been feeling well, it was just the - want of proper food. The - what they gave us was these pickled eggs and you know half the time when we broke them they were rotten, and therefore we had n
o
thing for our breakfast, just bread and margarine. Not - not even butter. Just margarine. And - the - this big party was coming on and Miss - I forget their name that was in Gillespie Hall but big nobs, but they were coming to this luncheon party - and th
e
y had a - a Miss - Jessie - what now - Jessie Munro was coming in to help me to wait, oh they were - liked all their orders there waiting on the table, even when they were alone I had to wait on them. Well - the day before I wasnae feeling well at all and
 was pains in my stomach and I think it was a ch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
ll I had got, and I - oh I couldna hardly do anything, so - in the finish about a quarter to one I went up to her, I said, I'm very sorry Mrs Wilson, but I could not wait the table today. I said, I'm feeling 
so ill, I said, Jessie will have to manage on her own. And there was not many coming. She says, you go downstairs and I'll come down. Well she come down, and she brought me - what would be half a glass of whisky, and she put twenty drops of laudanum in it
 
to kill the pain. I never knew any more. It might have killed me. When I wakened it was one o'clock, it was ten o'clock at night, I couldna believe when I saw the dark, and I could hear them still washing the dishes through in the pantry, from the bedroom
.
 And when Jenny - Jenny they called this old woman, Jenny what - I can't remember her name - when she come in she says, we thought you were gone. We thought she had killed you. Well she might have. When I told my mother what she had done she says, that's 
t
errible. Counted the drops - into the - wasn't that terrible. To kill the pain, it would certainly kill the pain. Yes. Oh dear. Well - we heard the greatest tales about - about the girls that had been at that place you know, the people in Lockerbie told u
s
 about them, they were having a party one night, and both of them, both the cook and the table maid had been up stairs helping maybe carrying down dishes, and they were taking off their aprons and they're down and they had their cases packed and a cab and
 away, and they left them with all the dishes to - isn't that a terrible place mind.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You would take it terribly hard after being with such nice people before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, it was terrible. Well I just stayed a year there. By jiminy it was a hard year for me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 If you had gone straight there from home you wouldn't have known what a good house would be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. I wouldn't have known what a good place was. Well - after I'd been there -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It would be a bit different at the Grove because it was a great big place wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
There was a staff there, yes, I was one of the housemaids, I went in for the house - I liked housework best, I liked the table too you know, but I liked housework best. So there was three housemaids, and - funny thing, at the Gr
ove there was three holidays, will you believe that, there was one holiday, I was one, Halliday was my name, Halliday was Effie, the head housemaid's name, then there was me, and there was Bessie Anderson, that came from Glen Lee, New Galloway, her dad wa
s gamekeeper in Glen Lee, and the ladies maid was Miss Haliday. Wasn't that funny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You weren't related at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No relation whatever, wasn't that a funny thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How did you get the job there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well, I'd been - I had a rest for a wee whil
e after I left - Mrs Wilson's - and one - one day I was walking - just across from the bank where they lived, and - here Miss Wilson had seen from the window, and she come down and she said, we noticed you from the window. She said, have you got a - not w
o
rking yes? And I said, no, not yet. She says, would you like to come back to us, because we would like you? I said, oh no thank you, I said I'm in hands for a job, well I wasna, but it wasnae certain, but to go back there I'd no notion. I was glad to get 
a
way from it. So - this job was in the - paper, in the Dumfries paper, but Miss Faulds was the lady at the - had a register office at Dumfries and I had put my name in there. And I went in to see her this day and she had this - housemaid's job, she says, h
o
w do you like that? So I said, whereabouts was it. And she said at the Grove. It was Maxwell's of the Grove, but it was let to people - the name of Church. And - I didn't see the place or anything before I went, a lady to wrote to me when I applied for th
e job and she said she thought that I would be suitable, and would I come - I forget now how much I was to get, it was more than what I had at the bank, and - would I come on a certain date, so I just went out, I'd never seen the place. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It would be difficult to get away out there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Ah - from Dumfries. She told me what to do like, to get a cab and they would pay it, they conveyance out. So - I didn't know whether I would like it or not you know, so many, because I'd been just used with the - 
two. However - they were quite a cheery lot of girls, and - they had a butler, and they had a hall boy, and a housekeeper and when I went she was a very nice person. Mrs Wright they called her and she must have taken to me just as I took to her, and - she
 
was leaving thought when I went, which I was very sorry about, she left there and went to Capenoch, Gladstones of Capenoch. Well - Mr Bonwick the butler said - I'd been there maybe - three weeks, he says, well girls, one day in the hall, he says, well gir
l
s, he says, you're getting a housekeeper that they had in London, they had a house in London. And he says, they had eight housemaids in six month, when she was here, and why ever they'd taken her back, he says, I do not know. But she was a splendid organi
ser. Very strict, you know, print frock she wore and all starched you know. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was she English?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She was English. Mr Bonwick was English, Thomas was English too. You see, they - went so long to London and so long up in - Dumfriesshire.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they take some of the staff with them when they went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No, they didnae take any of the staff with them, because they must have had staff there, in London. Maybe they would be on board wages you see, to keep their house, you know, to keep their house 
aired and that. Give them less wage but they would be getting their food. There wouldna be no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 They wouldn't have the same work to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, there would be somebody in the house anyway, we didn't learn that, but they never took their staff from D
umfries with them. So Mrs Haller came and - the butler and Miss - and the housekeeper and that, there was what they called the pugs parlour, that was supposed to be where the upper servants - took their food, but they never used it, we all sat together in
 the hall. You see, we all sat together. But the under ones weren't allowed to speak at the table, unless to say - please pass the butter or pass the bread, no conversation, wasn't that terrible.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were you included in that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I was included in that
, just the - the head housemaid, the lady's maid, the housekeeper, and - Mr Bonwick, these were the ones that could talk, of course they could address you and you could address them back, but you werenae allowed to carry on - conversation with any of your
 
own friends. So - one day the - chauffeur came from Terregles, Galbraith's of Terregles, and it was quite different there, they were free and easy, they were allowed to talk. So strange to say he sat down beside me, you know, he come in for his tea and hi
s
 people were in having afternoon tea, and of course he started to talk and I was just answering him and no more, I wasnae carrying on a conversation, so when he rose to go out he says - thank you for my tea Mrs Hall, and he says, and Bonwick, this was the
 
butler, he says, the next time I come put me beside a girl that can talk to me. Of course Mr Bonwick told him outside we werena allowed to, he was a new chauffeur then. And he apologised, but he thought I was a dummy I think. Oh dear. Yes. There was a - a
 
- governess for the children, there was three children, and I had that - I had that part of the house to do, the schoolroom. And - I was up at five in the morning, no wonder I get up at five, I had to because - you know, there wasnae the labour saving dev
i
ces you have now. And the first morning, Margaret often laughs, I though Effie the head housemaid would have been up, she showed me the night before what I had to do, I had the outer hall to keep and a great - great big fireplace, all steel, old fashioned
. Crikey. And marble mats just about the floor, I expect it's the same yet. And all round about all sorts of game, but I'd nothing to do with that, the butler and the hall boy used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Game did you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well, heads. Lions and tigers and all thes
e sort of things, I expect that would; belong to the Maxwell's you know, and - they used to take these down once a year and do them - brush them and do them all with Keaings powder and that and everything, when the people were away. So the first morning I
 
went down I went, I went through off our landing, our landing opened off their main one landing, and a candle. And I put my foot in a tiger's mouth, you know, there was tiger - and down the hall I went flying. Nobody heard me, and what a job I had to find
 
lights, because you see all was strange to me really. Oh dear me, I thought I wished I'd never come here, that was what I thought. However, it was quite nice as long as Mrs Wright was there. I quite enjoyed it. But after Mrs Hall came - she used to have a
 
- a terrible manner. And first of all she fell out with the ladies maid, the ladies maid sat beside her - at table, and Mr Bonwick the butler sat at the other end, and she used to be so taken to Miss Halliday that we fair felt it you know. And - Miss Hall
i
day used to rise up from the table sometimes when we were at our food and she would be in tears, the sort of way she spoke to her. And - she told Mrs Church that she was leaving. And I think Mrs Church would speak to Mrs Hall. And - they were - you know, 
they spoke but it was - it was terrible for us because you felt if you were speaking to one the other resented it. It was terrible. Well the next -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It's not a nice atmosphere is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. The next one she fell out with was the butler, Mr Bonwich, 
she fell out with him. I don't think he - thought about going away because he knew what she was you see before she came. 'til in the finish there was nobody speaking to her but me, and it was - the rest used to say, I don't know how you - you can keep wel
l
 - I wasna in the habit of fighting with people you know. However - it was Bessie's afternoon off, there was nowhere to go. You would - you hadna time to go to Dumfries, there was no transport, I was one - once in Dumfries - the six month I was there, and
 I never was home all that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you not get much time off at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No, we got Sunday afternoon off - one - one morning, and Sunday - you went to church, well I was glad to go, for somewhere to go to, Irongray Church, I liked going to church. 
You used to go through the gardens and it was quite near. And then - you were in for the rest of the day. The following Sunday you got out for the afternoon, but there was no place to go, you could go for a walk but there was no place to get anything to e
a
t, you had to come in if you wanted something, and unless you came in the tea hour you didna get any, you'd to wait to - nine o'clock for suppertime. So - sometimes we didna go out at all. So this day - Bessie was out, and there was drawing room tea to ge
t
, there was some ladies in for tea, and Bessie said to me, will you manage the hall tea? I said, oh I'll manage it. So I had the two teas to do. And - when Mrs Hall went up for her hour's rest she said to me - please tell me when the post comes, that was 
four o'clock, she never put her letters down on the table like us, she came down and gave the post her letters so that we wouldna know who she was writing to or anything. Secretive she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did the postman come up to collect the letters at the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
The postman came in the afternoon and waited on the letters, we used to have them on a table just in the passage, but she came down to him. Well, do you know, I heard the - I heard the post - but it - I was busy cutting thin bread and butter, you know
, I was - I was - had too much to do really. And I let him away, and I never thought about Mrs Hall or what she had said. So Bonwick says, did you tell Mrs - oh, I said, I forgot. Well, he says, the fat's in the fire now. He was English of course. He says
,
 you'll be getting it next. So - she come down with a nice smile on her face, you see, she was still talking to me, and she says, is the postman never passed yet? I said, I'm very sorry Mrs Hall, I forgot to tell you, I said, I had so much to do, getting 
t
he two teas ready, and - huh, I might have known as much. Just like the rest of them. She says, so that was her out way with me. So the next thing was - she was a going away, she got the sack because nobody would stay. Previous to this Bessie had given he
r
 notice, the kitchen maid had given her notice, she couldnae - and I had given mine, because I wanted away, you know, back into - civilization. It was a nice place mind you - beautiful situated place but no - nothing to do on your afternoon out or anythin
g, you couldna get time, you'd to walk to Dumfries, my - I and the kitchen maid walked once in the time we were there, for a good long walk, four miles - out and four miles in and - so -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What size of house is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, a big house. Aye, a big hous
e. Beautifully furnished house it was then. And - Mr Church had a - a business room. Now what - what was his business room, I had - had to keep - always to the back of the house, and - he used to do a lot of carpentry, making - things to feed - the grouse
 
and that you know how they used to bring out - pheasants, when you'd pheasants and - grouse and that, he used to make these things, hoppers he called them to feed them in, and he had the place littered with shavings, you never know what you were going to 
have to clean up in the afternoon when you went in, but you had to keep it tidy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 This was just a hobby of his?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Just a hobby. He'd nothing much to do. And - he was retired from the Army you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of age would he be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well t
hey were quite young people, I mean, between forty and fifty I should think. They - master Jim was just three when I was there so - they wouldna be very old. Judy and - and - Geggie they called the eldest one, I don't what their right names was, that was 
-
 there were three - two girls and a boy, and you know, I've seen his name in the papers, Colonel - George something Church, it'll be him right enough. No so long ago I saw it in the paper, and - she was a very - lady like but very strict and stern, I didn
ae care for her, you know they was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
ae like a - a bit homely, they just thought themselves superior to you, I daresay they were in a sense, they had more money and everything but - even ladies treat you like human beings don't they, when we used to hear her 
coming down the passage we used to slip into a door not to meet her, she was always looking for work for you, something else to do. There was a great big passage - from the dining room right past the butler's pantry, right down - right - and right to the 
k
itchen door, and a wide passage about half the - width of this room, brown linoleum, it was scrubbed twice a week and I had to do that. And she came along one day, I didna hear her, and I was just at the head of the stairs when she said - I was just think
ing, this passage could do scrubbed three times a week, wasn't that awful for the rest of the work you had to do I thought to myself, well it'll no be scrubbed by me much oftener.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What other jobs did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mostly - I had the - schoolro
om to do in the morning before they governess come down. You see. They had their tea in a wee room off the schoolroom, Effie did that, thats the housemaid, but I had the schoolroom to do for they kept - there was a nice - fire to do, and fireside to clean
 
up, all black lead and - no modern grates like we have now. And - brass - fender to clean too. And the carpet to sweep, and there was just sweepers, you know there was none of these cleaners then. And when you did - did it out thoroughly, tea leaves down 
to keep down the dust, oh - couldna - Effie was supposed to do that but she was never up. That's the truth, the head housemaid was supposed to do the so I got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was she kind of lazy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, she was - she was a good worker, but she wasna - an early r
iser in the morning. And - you see, the schoolroom was a thing that needed early to get into, Miss Hunt they called the teacher, the governess, she was up early and you had to have it done so that you were out of her way. I had that to do, then I had this
 
front hall to do. And a passage - right past all the rooms. Effie did the drawing room. And Bessie helped her with the dining room. Effie did the drawing room on her own, that was the head housemaid, Bessie had the - the dining room. And I had the front h
all to do. The schoolroom, and this passage, I had a lot to do, that's why I got up so early. And - that was how we had to in the morning like. And the head - and you had your own room to keep, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of room did you have there? Did you have one to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No. My ma and I shared the room, Mima was the kitchen maid, and - there was - Bessie had a room on her own, Effie had a room on her own, Bella Moore, she was the nursemaid - she'd a room on her own. And there was really two rooms - I 
could have been in a room on my own, but it - it looked out on the back, it was an awful dull room and Mima said - Eslpeth, the one that had been before me, and I - brought a bed in here, but she said if you want to go in to this single room, I said, oh n
o
, just leave it where it is, you'll be glad of somebody to talk to. She was a nice soul. She was engaged when I went, this Mima - Mima what was her name? Oh I remember her name then - that day, she was engaged to a chauffeur at Capenoch, Thornhill, where 
M
rs Wright went to, and told me something, they called here - he used to come and see her, and she left before I did. And she went away down to Burley in Wharfdale, Yorkshire, and she corresponded with me for a long time, and she got on with another lad do
w
n there, George, for all she was engaged to Tommy. And - she used to come up to Penpoint was where she came from, and - she used to write and tell me, she says, I don't know what to do, because when I'm up here I always think I like Tommy best, but when I
 go back I go back to George, well she married George in the finish. And it was as well for he was killed in the war, Tommy. I saw his death in the paper. Aye. He was -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What was the position about boyfriends there, were you allowed to have visitors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
You were allowed if you asked and it was in the - and the housekeeper was on - was pleased enough to have them, there's the only the - servants hall to have them in, and it meant - that - if you had them you had to have them at a time when your work w
as finished, you couldnae neglect your work to have your boyfriend there. No, Mrs Wright was all right, she dinda mind you having anybody in but Mrs Hall was a different problem. So - I canna say I enjoyed my life there on the whole.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What was the food like there, was it a bit better than it had been at the bank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh was splendid food. Lovely food, we got as much as we ever need - could eat. And - at night - they had late dinner every night you see, I think it was half past seven, I'm no just - I c
annae just remember that, but we had our supper in the hall at nine o'clock, and we got whatever was left over from the dining room was put on the table, and what I remember was - they used to make - the cook used to make a lot of that peach melba, that w
a
s one of the things on the - and I thought about having it but you know I canna do ice cream now, so I said to Margaret McCarthy, you take it, it's lovely. But they didna, - they took trifle. Well it - by the time it come our time to ask what pudding they
 liked there was none left, for all the top ones got it you see, and we'd to take what was left. Aye. So I was quite pleased to get away - from - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How many staff were there altogether in the servants hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How many? There was Mrs Hall, I - 
I can - I'll - I'll just - there was Mrs Hall at the top of the table. Then there was Miss Halliday next to her. Then }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 this}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
 was another Miss Halliday, Effie. Effie she got. And - who came next to Effie now? Bella Moore, the - the nursery maid, Bella Moore. 
And - and there was Mr Bonwick, there was Thomas, there was Bessie, myself - wait a minute now 'til I think - myself, Mima Tweddle, that was the kitchen maid. How many's that? Nine. There was ten. But I'll tell you what they did - in the busy time, which 
w
as the summer months - they had a - scullery maid as well - to help, because there were big - always a lot of visitors in the summer months, but I didnae see much of that - I was just six month there, it was the end of the year when I went, November or De
c
ember, January, February, March, April - I didnae see very much, they did have two or three visitors mind, the time I was there. I remember Mrs - Church's sister came, and she had all her food - with her, had to take it up to her, she seemed to lie in her
 bed an awful lot, whether she wasnae very strong I don't know, but - Mr Bonwick used to shake his head when he was getting the trays ready, he says, young people lying in their bed to this time of the day. No, he didnae approve. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you come in contact with the children at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes, they were nice children, very nice, and the wee boy was a nice wee soul, he was just three, and - they ran about you know and - we saw them outside you know, if we were out shaking the mats and that, they alw
ays came and talked to you because they didna know that we were servants, you know what I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did they call you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - they called you Halliday. That's what you got there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You just got your surname?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh you just got your second n
ames there. So did Miss Halliday too, not Miss Halliday, she got Miss Halliday, but Effie just got Halliday, I got Halliday, and - Bessie Bessie - what was her name, oh she was an awfully nice lassie. I wrote to her too for ages. It's queer how names - I 
can remember her first name but no her second her second, that's funny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did you call the children when you were talking to them, you called the wee boy master?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh we just called them by their - the children? Oh Master Jim. Miss Judy. And - a
nd master Jim if you were talking about them, but if we were talking about them a - amongst ourselves we just called them their names, Bella did too, Bella Moore was the nursery mai}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 d}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080  you see, she used to take them out. She was a nice soul too. In fact they were all - they were all nice, we used to go and have wee chats in each other's room, you know, when we went up - we -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When you had time off did you go to your own room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 We went to our own room, we always did because if you went into the hall w
rite letters and Mrs Hall come in it was misery. And - well there was no other room except what they called - the servants hall, it was a nice comfortable room you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were there comfortable seats and that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh they were comfortab
le, yes, oh yes. But - Mrs Hall used to go up for an hour up to her room in the afternoon because she'd to be down again for the dinner at night you see. She come down for tea. Sometimes she sent word that - she wouldn't be down for tea, we used to take h
e
r a cup up, I was glad to do it to get her to stay. Well she was always nice with me up to the last - and after that she never spoke, but I had no long to put in. I had - was it Bessie and I left on the same day, or Mima and I, no, I think Mima was away, 
I
 says to Bessie, how are we going to get our money because - they were away, and nothing had been said. And - we'd ordered a cab to come for us you see at a certain time. So it was a beautiful sunny morning I remember, and we took Mrs Hall's cup of tea in
 
at ten o'clock, she was sitting in there. And we were just having ours at the kitchen table. And she said - she never spoke, so I said, we're going off this morning Mrs Hall. I said, Mrs Church didn't say anything about pay did she? Oh yes, I've got your 
p
ay. So she give us our pay. You're getting a lovely morning to go away, and that was the first time she'd spoken, so I say's to Bessie, that old Besom, she condescended to say that, so I says, we're getting our pay all right, so - we were quite pleased to
 wash our hands of the whole thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 If you had been there longer would you have got holidays do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - must - we must have got holidays surely, yes - aye, we were kept at the whole time. And - the only time we were free was when - they 
were away in London, we did the spring cleaning it was done before our - you know, before - before we left, all the spring cleaning, it was a big house too, but we were cheery you know, and - were - were working, the rest of them were all right, but - wel
l - when -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did the mistress give you your orders for the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh no. You knew your orders, you knew what you had to do. Effie was the head housemaid you know, if there was any change or anybody coming - she told Effie. But - she only came once - 
in the morning, ten o'clock to the kitchen, for orders for the day, there was a slate at the end of the - and Mrs Hall would have the menu written out for the day. Now, if she wanted it changed she would consult it you see and say - so and so was coming f
o
r lunch and she would like - this changed you see, and - if there was any - orders at all she left it on the slate and Mrs Hall used to tell us at teatime when we had our - elevenses as they called it. It was just after she went away at ten o'clock, and i
f there was any different orders she told us. We never seen much of them at all you see, except they were - coming into the rooms while you were cleaning them, you were just trying to finish before they would be in their places where they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 As long as you did the work they didn't interfere with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
They didn't, no, they never interfered with us, no. Oh no, they never interfered. They were out a lot and - and they had a lot of visitors too. They were out shooting you know. My goodness, we used
 to look into the - larders were down under the - in the basement, and you used to look in and see this stuff hanging you know, shoots, big shoots and - hares hanging up, grouse and - all sorts of - poultry and everything down in here where it was refrige
r
ated you know. Oh. I did - didnae care for it and I said never again would I go into a place like that. No. They said at Terregles it was quite different, they were all friendly there. But it was unfortunate that she brought that Mrs Hall back again when 
she knew fine that the maids wouldna stay there. She must -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Id Mrs Wright had stayed on you would probably have been a lot happier?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh she was nice, yes. She wrote to me too after she went away to Capenoch. She used to - get writing paper and th
at from me when she ran out - because just }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
oing I had laid in plenty of stocks of everything you know to go with, and after she went away she sent me a nice - box of writing paper and thanked me for being so kind to her. She was a nice person, I don't kno
w how they didnae get on with her, but - she must have rubbed them up some way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How about the governess, did you have much to do with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, no much to do at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did she consider herself above the rest of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She - she - oh she wo
uld, I think so, yes, she spoke to you, she was quite free if she met you, you were outside she always passed the time of day, but not friendly. No. Oh no. I wouldnae -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did the children spend a lot of the time with her, do you think they would see much of their parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh - they just went down at a certain time, down into the drawing room, aye. They didnae see much of their parents at all, just were always entertaining, having ladies and - gentlemen in for tea or out shooting, that was th
eir life you see. But they used to go down into the drawing room, Miss Hunt would take them down at night - or maybe through the day if they were going to have people in in the evening. I expect Mrs Church would go up and see them in their beds very likel
y
, I don't know though. I know they went down to the drawing room at a certain time. Funny life isn't it? Aye. Funny. And she did the flowers, Mrs Church did the flowers herself. There was a room where she - oh and the mess she used to make you know, in th
a
t flower room, you know, just - dirty vases left and - and - flowers thrown about, water all over the floor, you'd always to go - even although you had tidied it in the morning you'd always to go in again and tidy it up, because it was - and she'd have be
en saying something if she'd - went in later and it no tidy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You said you liked to go to the church as somewhere to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I did. And I saw Jeanie Deans' grave there, you know, at Irongray church, and I looked for that right away whenever I went. So
metimes - now they were very - they went to the church too, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they make all their servants go to the church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Not so many of them. Bessie went with me one Sunday morning, Thomas was off one Sunday and he went with me, but I never knew Mr
 Bonwick to go. He would be English church you see, and - this morning, I happened to there on my own and here I saw them coming in, they sat near the front, and - when she - I'd seen Mrs Halls she said, never say - you - spoke when they passed me you kno
w
, and they walked through the garden too, they sometimes didna take the car and she spoke, said, good morning, and - quite nice they were to speak to - ah, but that was all. So she said to Mrs Hall, a very poor attendance, was there no one out - no one of
f duty on Sunday morning, there's not much to do on Sunday morning. I didn't see very many at the church, had spoken about that, there was only me out of the lot of them. I was glad to get out you know, get - get out for the fresh air. Aye. Oh dear.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So you were there for six months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Just six month, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have another job to go to be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 ore you left there, or did you just hand in your notice and then look for something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Now wait 'til I think, oh I handed in my notice, I determined I 
wasn't going to stay there. They were all leaving you see and you didna know what you were going to get, new people coming. And - I don't think I had another job to go to. Was that - was that - I'd been to Wilson's, yes, and then to the Grove. Well - my s
i
ster was looking for a job about that time, she was younger than I, and - they'd seen a job in the paper, and this was to go to Highfield, where my husband worked. And - they sent word for my sister to go - in and she was rather young, you see, it was her
 
first job. And - the - Mrs McJerrow had said - she's rather young, well my mother thought about me, and she told her about me, she says, yes that would be - suit us better, she says, she's rather young - for us. So - mother told me and I went in to see he
r
, and - here she was away to Watford. Her eldest daughter was in school down at Watford and had taken ill. And - she was staying with the granny at the time, the girl like, Norah, but there was Miss Beele, the governess there, and she interviewed me becau
s
e she had been with them a long time and she knew just what they wanted, and she said, I think you'll just be the very - one to suit them. So - there was only Marjorie at home, she was governess to this wee girl. There was two of them at home really, but 
-
 Noele, the second one, was going away to boarding school, just when I went. So she went away to boarding school and Marjorie was - she was my - baby all the time I was there. She was a nice wee girl, I liked her, and - I went to them and then - that was 
w
hen - 1913 it would be, it was the year before the war broke out, and then the war broke out, and - they got a Belgian lady and wee girl to stay with them. The Belgian girl - what was her name again, the Belgian girl. I know this name - Julia, I was think
ing Judy. Now she was just of an age with Marjorie and the one was good for the other because they learned - Marjorie learned French off her, and - and Julia learned -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How old would they be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well they'd be coming on - she would be - six, sh
e would be coming seven, about seven. And were both good for each other, and - her husband was the Consul, Madam Oester-Smitt, and he was left there you see, and - she come over and - they had the schoolroom, what used to be the schoolroom was made into a
 
bedroom for them. And each had separate beds, the wee girl and her but both in the same room, a great big room it was. And - there were with us a year. And - Madam Oester-Smitt used to come through and ask for confiture, that was chocolate, so that I woul
d
 learn - learning French too, quite picked up a lot you know. The time she was there. And - Mrs McJerrow - I don't think she was very happy with them there really, because - it made a terrible turn up in their way of life, the priest used to come and see 
-
 Madam Oestersmith, you see, she was a Catholic, and they werenae you see, and of course - she'd always to go out of the room and leave the room and she was - deaf, Mrs McJerrow and she didnae hear just all that was going on. And then - Miss - Bell, she w
a
s the governess, and she left - through - bereavement at home, and Miss - they got a Miss Thompson, now she was a happy go lucky - soul, you know, really she was - into everything of mischief and went to the dances and - got on fine with her. She come fro
m
 Cirencester, away down in Gloucestershire, aye, and - she stayed a wee while. About two years I think, and then - she went away, and a Miss Sadler came. Now she was - I think she'd been very strictly brought up, oh a dainty wee soul she was, no very big,
 
and - nice looking wee creature and - her - her father was a painter - Dan - Den - Denbigh Sadler, that was his name, had painted, beautiful pictures and she went in for photography. And - I don't think they liked her as well as they liked Miss Thompson a
n
d Miss Bell, because she was more sedate you know, and - I think she was - come of really - good class people, and - she used to be - I - I think she was miserable for a while, she didnae understand our ways. And - she used to confide in me that she wasn'
t very happy. But however - she stayed a good long time with them and - and - it came time for Marjorie to go to boarding school, and - they got rid of Miss Sadler. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What other staff did they have then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 They just had - the cook, and - myself
, and - they'd a woman come in - to do the wash. And - if any - extra cleaning was done we got a woman to come in and help with that too. Oh the - the work - when these Belgians came there was another family - poorer class people - what was this his name 
w
as, I remember - Pouhlart, Pouhlart. Pouhlart, and - Madam Pouhlart used to come down and help with the work and they'd a woman come in to do sewing. You mind Miss Davidson, used to come in and do mending and sewing for them, they'd plenty of help you kno
w. And - it was quite a happy place, and you came - after I'd been there about a year, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You were there first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. That's right. And - and - after you went away to the war, you mind the cook left, Jessie - Jessie Byers. And I thought Alic
e came, was Laice there before you went away? Aye. Well - aye, she was English and had different ways.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 If surprises me, the number of English employees.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I don't know. You see, Alice - was like this, she needed to get out to early communion, whi
ch meant that I had the breakfast to do and all these sort of things and I had my own work to do as well. And if you were a minute past the time and the boss was down he was looking daggers at you because he liked everything didn't he, just on the dot. An
d -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Everything run by the clock was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye, clockwork for him, the same at dinnertime too when you brought his thermos with him for - for his tea, and I had to have his tea put in and his piece made up and he took it - up to the office with him 
to save him going out in the afternoon. But if he come down without it I used to go in and say, did you bring your thermos? Oh I forgot it, that meant I had to go up with his tea. He wouldna go out and have it at the - tearooms or anything. But my - I'd t
o take it up to the office and Marjorie along with me. It was a grand excuse - aye, but I'd things to do you know. And - she used to s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 ay, are you going up with daddy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 's tea today? And if I was going - I used to take her into Gladstones and buy her some sweet
s you know, sweets were cheap these days. And she had a wee doll's pram. Eeh she was an awful girl and we had a cat, a black cat, and she used to dress this cat up in doll's clothes and up we went - I told her I didna want her to do it, but I couldna refu
s
e it. She says, no it won't, I'll look after it, I promise. I says, well it's you for it mind. So off we set and everything went well, got up to the town, we were about half road home when a dog came sniffing at the pram and out jumped the cat. And away o
v
er the fields. And what a job we had to get it. Oh dear. And then - at night when she was put to bed - the governess was very strict, this Miss Sadler with her, always remember her for this, she got me into a row over it. She said to me, Marjorie hasn't b
een doing her lessons at all well today, so she's to have bread and butter for her supper only. So I said, all right, now that was orders from Miss Sadler, she'd made th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 
is this evening. However I took}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080  in the bread and butter on the tray, she'd her supper ea
rly you see. And a glass of milk. Mrs McJerrow looks up. Is that all the child's getting for supper? And I said - that was Miss Sadler's orders. She says, nonsense. Go and get her her scrambled egg, now there was the way you put in and of coursed - Miss S
adler never said to me she was sorry about it, I got into a row, she - you'd have thought I had done it, it was Miss Sadler.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 Too many }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 bosses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, too many bosses. So - she used to put her to bed, Miss Sadler, and in two or three minutes I could 
hear her, Martha, Martha, Martha, and this was for me to go up and read her a story, and I used to go up and read her a story, but she liked one made up better, if I would - could make her up - and sometimes Mrs McJerrow, oh that - bad person's up - the s
t
air again, this was me, but she never said a word. She was quite pleased for me to - to do it you see. I remember one day she was asked out to tea, and - it was to Jean and Olive Mares, and - I took her up to the know and the road roller was working in th
e road outside the gate. And - at six o'clock Mrs McJerrow said, will you go up for that child and bring her home, so - she'd promised to leave her 'til seven, but she says, she must get back}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080  
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 tonight. So six o'clock she saw me, oh, I'm not going home. Yes, I says, you're coming home, that's your mother's orders.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She wasn't wanting to come home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
She wasnae wanting to come home. So - she never spoke to me when I took her out - took her by the hand but she wouldnae have my hand. So came to the place
 where it was all messed up with a road roller, and she had on a beautiful - blue, I can see it yet, pale blue knitted coat and wee bonnet to match, she looked nice, but her mother had just sent away and got it from Harods. And she ran away from me, tripp
e
d and fell in the mud. This beautiful coat, that was because she was bad, I told her after, I said, now that's because you were a bad girl and doing what you shouldn't have been doing, calling me names. And she said she was sorry, she was always like that
, she said she was sorry. But I said to myself there'll be some facin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 g with this, so he and the mist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
ress just met us at the front door. Oh dear, me, she says, whatever have you been doing. I said, she was a bad girl. I said, she was angry because I went for
 her early, and, I said, she's been calling me names all the way home, and she fell because she ran away, she tripped and fell. Well she never spoke. Got her supper and she got bathed and away to bed. And here she went into you wee place you know where th
e basin was and she set to, and when she come out with this it was - you never saw anything go out like it, she never had it on again. The coat was ruined. I don't know - it went - instead of - you know, keeping it's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 A knitted thing like that it would be difficult to keep its shape.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - but - but even when she come out with it, just out of the water, it was - it was the length of that and she just took one look and disappeared. She never mentioned it again. No, but Julia got it. You know she 
was a wee bit bigger than Marjorie and I don't know what Madam was - did to it but it - it looked quite all right. And she - never was on Marjorie again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How much did Mrs McJerrow have to do with Marjorie then, with bringing her up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well - th
ey went out together, she took her out you know when they were going out driving or that, they went out with her, but Miss Sadler really had charge of her during the day, in the evening when lessons were finished - it was all right a
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 But you would say she had more to do with her daughter than the Church's had to do with their children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes, oh it was different altogether, it was more homely. The Church's - I - I think they just entertained themselves you know all the time, I don't think they 
needed - who did the work or what - what left them or anything, they just - you were just there for a purpose, you know what I mean. They werenae - like - lesser people. I mean that was the idea with them, they're not all the same you know, but they were 
very stand-offish people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get on well with Mrs McJerrow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes, oh she told you everything, aye. She was just - she'd just lost her daughter when I went and she used to - I used to be vexed for her, she - used to say -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 The one that was ill died did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
The one that was ill died, she was fourteen, and she used to say if it had been either of the other two, and I said, don't - don't say that, it wouldna have mattered which one it was. Norah was her first one you see. And they ar
e all dead now, the whole lot of them. They're away too. But - I liked Marjorie, my husband liked the second one best you know. I'd more to do with her. And - at night my sister used to come down, she went as housemaid to the King's Arms later on, and she
 used to come down at night on her night off and Julia was her child and Marjorie was mine, and after supper we used to have such fun in the kitchen, playing games with them you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well you weren't all that old yourself were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. I wasnae, just about eighteen. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So you got more time off there did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes, yes, and used to get weekends away home too. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You were nearer home then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 We were nearer home, yes. And got out to the church every Sunday evening - once I
 must tell you about a - an incident that happened. This Sunday evening, we were supposed to go to church but the time was our own, we could do what we liked as long as we were in again for half past nine on a Sunday night. So Bessie Byers, the - her peop
l
e had a farm down at Mungo, and she says to me, what about going down to see my folk tonight instead of going to church, it was a lovely evening. I said, right-o. So off we set. And - how many miles would be? About four. Well - we came to the house. It wa
s
 locked up. She says, well they canna be far away, because a farm you know. And - she says, they'll soon be back, we'll wait about for a wee while. We couldna get in for the door was locked. And - at last she saw a window open, the pantry window, she says
, by }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 J}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
ove, it's the pantry window open, I'll get in now. We're both young. So she climbed through the pantry window, and she went into the larder and there was two rhubarb cakes you know - pies. She says, we'll no go back hungry and we - even if they don't 
- they don't come back. So she put two glasses of milk, the cows were milked, and we sat and had this - pice of this rhubarb tart and milk, could have got more but we didna want it. So when we got out, we were just down out the window, and coming down the
 
avenue from the farm we met the minister, Mr what was his name - oh dear - I - I canna remember, but anyway, he says, good evening Miss Byers, of course he didna know me you see, but she said who it was. He said, is your father at home? She said, there's 
n
o one at home, Mr whatever his name was. He says, oh well, I wanted to see him on a small matter but I can see him again. He says, have you walked from Lockerbie? She said, yes. Well come down to the Manse and have some tea. Oh no thank you, she said, we 
n
ever told him we'd been in the house. No thank you she said, we really must get back to Lockerbie, we've got to be in by half past nine. So - we didna hear anymore about it - for a wee while 'til she was back home again. And the minister had gone up later
 
on and got them in, they'd only been at a neighbouring farm. And - he said, you had two visitors the time you were out. She says, oh yes, but they hanna get away hungry anyway, she said, they've been at my - telled him about this - I was going to meet tha
t man, you know, he would have known us again, I ca}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
