\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You had plenty of men there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
We had plenty of men. Whatever women had we? We'd - there was - oh maybe Jean was there. Well we had a lovely party, I canna mind - pork pies she got us and - we'd a nice supper, and - and there was singing. Had we dancing, I canna remember? Aye.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have to have it in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 In the kitchen, it was a nice big kitchen. So - I remember - my father and - and uncle had come with the train I think had they. There was
 no buses in these days but they'd to walk home in the morning. We carried on - for best part of the night. And they had to walk home in the morning, and I remember my father, it was my uncle that was the mischief, he says, when we went past Mount Pleasan
t
, he says, it was just breaking daylight and they picked up a handful of gravel and flung it up the windows of the folk that should be up, to waken them up. I says, you didna do that. Oh they knew them. These were the kind of - these were the kind of thin
gs they did. Oh dear. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What were your jobs at Highfield then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 House table maid, just the same. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you do some cleaning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. Yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And waiting at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. They - they didna have much waiting at the tab
le unless there was people there, you'd just the plates to hand round you know, Mr - McJerrow did the carving, he handed the plates round, but they'd often people in, they were - entertained a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of people did they entertain?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - 
I canna mind you man that come home from Africa. I - I've often - this old man, he - he used to come and - and - he was a great one for the ladies so they - Mrs McJerrow said to me - has he brought you any sweets? He - used to bring us sweets every time h
e
 came to the door, this man. He - he dis. She says, oh he's a great one for the ladies and I think he'd rather taken a fancy to you. I says, oh well, I havena taken any to him. You cold say anything to her you know. And - she used to say, you're not like 
-
 this was always struck me - tickled him, you're not like an ordinary - girl, you're more like one of us. This is - they used to say that. She used to say that. Used to take me out sometimes with them when they went you know. But - it was just because Mar
jorie was fond of me, she was. She - she - her mother said to me one day she said, Marjorie says she'll never forget you. You've been so good to her, because I was fond of children you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You didn't have to call her Miss Marjorie or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 A
ye. She thought when we had Margaret you know - she ways, well, I did think you'd have called the child for me, or for Marjorie. I never thought about it. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How long did you stay at Highfield?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Four years. Four years I was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you remember what sort of pay you got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh - no, it was better like than what we had had, but it's funny do you know, I - and it's really true that I can't remember what I had. But we - oh I don't know now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When you were young like that what did you spend your money on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you buy clothes and that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye, well - we - we used to - did we get it monthly? Aye. Got it monthly - oh well, of course your mother was the one that seen that you spent it wisely, I know mine did anyway. And the clothes werenae so dear then you see as what they are now. But you -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you hand your pay over to your mother usually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I think so, she would give me so much back for pocket money, I had always pocket money. Oh she was always 
good to - to all of us, no just to me, she was always good, when I think - how little they had, I often wonder how she was so generous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were you interested in clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes. I remember - I - I went to - well, I'd been to dances before, the cou
ntry dances. But I remember when Miss Thompson was there - we were asked to a dance up in - in - Town Hall, I cann mind what that dance was - and Jessie Byers, she had a lovely evening dress. And she said, I wish you could come. And I said, oh I cannae co
m
e because I havenae anything like that to wear. Now when Miss Thompson heard of that - she'd a pink - dress that was too tight for her and she made me a lovely evening dress and - I was fair complimented on it. Pink it was, it was nice. Aye. She was kind 
like that, Miss Thompson. She was a harum-scarum wasn't she? Oh she was a harum-scarum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She seems to have been a nice person though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She was. Aye.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did you do in your spare time usually, your time off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well ......
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you go home most times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Mostly. I got a bicycle, mind Mrs McJerrow, one of her aunts sold a bicycle a new Hudson, and I bought it off her, I don't know what it was - how much it was, five pounds I think. I think so. So that was my sister and I in Lockerbie 
now, 'cos she was housemaid at the Kind's Arms, and I remember - we learned - well wasna very proficient, but we partly learned to - cycle, but we'd only the one bike. So - this night, it was a nice summer night, we made up our minds we would go home. And
 
what we did was - say I set off, and I went a certain distance and left the bicycle in the roadside, my sister kept walking on then she got it and - we got home - aye. The next - time we went Hetherington's had bicycles - for half a crown for three hours,
 so we hired a bicycle, and we each went home. So - that was how -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say you went to country dances and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you go to them in Templand or Lockerbie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, Templand. Went to the dances there, 'cos we knew all the folk
 about there you see. I remember the first time Jessie and I went - Jessie Byers, she was a keen dancer too. We got over all right but we'd to walk back. And we stayed to the last minute, mind you we'd to be back for the breakfast. Well - we stayed - we w
ere living at Corncockle Cottage then and mother said, now before you leave come up and get a cup of tea and no starting off for - Lockerbie, but she didna ken we were staying to the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What time did the dances finish in these days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 About five o'clock in the morning. Aye. They danced all night you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So you just had time to get your breakfast and start the next day's work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, so - well, we went up and had a cup of tea, and Bob Bryden for the shop - was with Jessie and Alec Va
rner was with me, and I'd only time to walk to Millers Bridge, that wouldna be half road would it, they couldna come all the road because it was time they were back for their - and off we set. And we got into - Lockerbie when the bells were ringing six. S
i
x o'clock in the morning, by the time we get down to Highfield that was just when we were at - you know, where the - Charters lived, that's when the bells started ringing six o'clock, so by the time we got down it was coming on for seven o'clock. And just
 had time to change and get Mrs - McJerrow's hot water and in to work. And the worst of it was this was a - Saturday morning, Friday night the dance had been, and Jessie was going away the weekend, I was left with everything to do. In the afternoon -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You would be tired by bedtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Four o'clock. Four o'clock. I was sitting in the basket chair at the fire thinking about what a happy night and I was - half - I think I was nearly a half weeping because it was over, when the door opened and Mrs McJerr
ow come in. She said, now - you're overtired, you're not going back to any country dances, I'll let you to them all in the town that you want to go to but not to come walking back at that time of the morning. It would have been all right if Jessie had bee
n there to do her work, but I had her work to do too. So I don't think we were ever back again after that. We went to the ones in the town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was Mrs McJerrow interested in your boyfriends and what you were doing and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh she was interested, yes. Aye, she was interested.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She was the sort of person that you could speak to quite freely about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Certainly, oh she told you everything didn't she? She told you all her affairs. She had. Aye. Oh they were very friendly. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How did you get on with Mr McJerrow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Very well. He was very fair. He was very fair. I remember - once night - they had visitors, and I always remember him for this - they had visitors staying in the house, there was somebody in the spare bedroom, it was Mr a
nd Mrs - the minister and his wife from Brydekirk, that was who - it was, and - here he brought that Colonel down for billiards. And instead of being just a supper he wanted dinner, now fancy phoning down that. Aye. So - he wanted the billiard room fire g
oing, the dining room fire and the drawing room fire was all on for the - minister and his wife was there. And I was rushing here, there and everywhere, and he - he says - how are you managing? I said, oh all right, sir, but, I said, the bill}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 ard fire hadna
e been on for a while and it wasnae drawing. And he says, when I - when I phoned down - that there's - extra, you ought to get someone in to help. He was taking my side because I had too much to do. She was quite off. She says, well I - do what I can. She
 was there. Oh he was fair enough that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So he entertained separately from his wife sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - having Colonel Byrne in, no they would all have their food together, but they were playing billiards you see, and he had to have the fire -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And Mrs McJerrow was left to entertain the minister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
She would be left to - entertain the minister and his wife in the drawing room, and I don't know if the minister played or no, but you see there was the - there was the governess and that - an
d the children too at that time and there was a lot to do, you know, when there was anybody in. And three -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 The children wouldn't eat with their parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh no, they did. At dinner time, through the day, but not in the evening. No, they had supp
er before. Of course when Miss Norah got older - they had - they dined at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did the children eat separately at Highfield?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. They ate all together in the dining room. Aye. They had their dinner through the day. Like I mean it wasna like di
nner, just a supper. They had their dinner at one o'clock. Mr McJerrow used to come down from the office in time, he was always punctual - for dinner, and they had all dinner in the dining room. The governess, Mr and Mrs McJerrow, two children when I went
,
 but Miss Norah was going away to boarding school so she wasn't long at home. It was just the young one. Then of course - when war broke out - this Belgian lady and her wee girl that was the same age - they were all in the dining room and all had their fo
od together, wouldna bother with two tables or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about if they had visitors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well - it was just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Marjorie wouldn't have her food separate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. Always had it - had it together. It was mostly aunties an
d uncles and - used to be granny, the granny I think and grandpa was only once there from Watford, they came up - from the South, and it was mostly aunties and uncles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 That was different from the Grove?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How was the cooking done in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
They had a - big range, you know, an old fashioned range, and - an electric cooker. Aye. Electric cooker. They had - so there was - I mean - they had good meals, good food they always had.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And you got the same food as they did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Just got the same, whatever came out from the dining room we got just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How about breakfast time, did they all have breakfast together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, they all had breakfast together, they were all up for breakfast, eight o'clock I
 think wasn't it, eight o'clock breakfast I think so, eight o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they have a big breakfast, did they go in for cooked ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Always had cooked breakfast, bacon and eggs or sausage or sometimes it was fish, they always had something cooked
. There wasnae - well they didnae bother with cereals in those days so much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No porridge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, I don't think I had porridge. No. Just a - breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about your breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, just the same, yes, cooked breakfast if we wanted it, i
f we didna want it we didna need to take it. That was when Madam Oast used to come out and ask for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8941568\charrsid2967080 comfiture}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
 if I'd forgotten the marmalade. The first - the first day I didna know and I - and I thought - what - what have I forgotten, I remembered what it was. Aye. Aye. So - that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Then they all had their dinner together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was that about one o'clock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 One o'clock for dinner, yes. And - and - as I told you before we took up Mr McJerrow's tea, if he didn't bring his thermos with hi
m. When he had - he used to lay his thermos on the hall table. And - I used to - prepare it between times you see and I put him his - whatever he wanted to eat, he was very fond of cake, and a scone, something like that, big slice of fruit cake, that's wh
a
t he liked, he'd a very sweet tooth. And - they had just tea in the dining room, if it wasnae an at home day. Wednesday was Mrs McJerrow's at home day and she often had ladies in. Just the Lockerbie people. And they had their tea, they had their tea in th
e
 - drawing room, and maybe Marjorie and Miss Sadler had theirs in the dining room, just at the end of the dining room table. Unless it was people that they knew. If it was - anybody in the town they just had it all together. Marjorie used to like to get i
n with us for our tea.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Into the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. Oh she didna mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 The governess was sort of accepted as one of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes. Yes. Oh she was. Yes. They were all - they were all nice, Miss Bell had been with them, the first one, s
he'd been with them for years and years hadn't she. Ting they called her. She never got anything but Ting. Miss McJerrow - would be calling up the stair, Ting, are you there, and Mr McJerrow too. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of supper did they have, they had another cooked meal then had they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes, a cooked meal at supper time, not so much at supper time but they - they'd always something cooked. Of course Marjorite didnae have much, she had hers on a tray, because she'd got to go to bed and the - the grown ups
 had supper together, but they always had something cooked for supper. Unless maybe there was anything cold, such as the summertime, if there was cold salmon or anything like that they'd have sal - salmon and salad. Aye. And - Mrs McJerrow had a glass of 
h
ot water last thing at night, nobody else took any - thing else, but she took a glass of hot water, last thing at night, first thing in the morning I had to take her up hot water - to drink. Never did I know her to take medicine all the time I was there, 
remember one day she was very sick, she couldnae get up in the morning, and I said to her, you should take a good dose of medicine, once your stomach's - oh I never take medicine, she said, never. Just a drink of hot water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you ever make jam or anything like that in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes, I made lots of jam because there was a lot of fruit in the garden you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was that up to the cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well that was the cook, aye, she did that. Strawberries and - and rhubarb and apple jam and - whatev
er there was. And - aye - And I know one thing I used to go with Mrs McJerrow to pull you know cranberries in the woods. Oh dear me, what a woman she was for these wee tiny cranberries and we used to go with her, she used to take me with her to help her t
o
 pull them up, I fair hated the job. She had - glayberries, aye, she called them cranberries, but - you know she fair loved it and then they used it along with - cranberry jelly with turkey and like that you see. She never got that much that it lasted so 
long I don't think. Unless she -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Did Mrs McJerrow organise this sort of thing herself or did she just leave it up like to Mr Shearer and the cook, if he was to say the strawberries are ready will bring some up?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh aye, he just brought them in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Or did she keep an eye on these things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, she didna bother, she would just tell you likely - that - they want some strawberries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they ever pickle anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, they used to pickle things too. Oh beetroot, they used to do a lot o
f beet root and - different things, she used to - go a lot to the market at Carlisle you mind, you used to take her, and she used to bring different things home to pickles, chives and all like that you know, and wee onions. That sort of thing. They had lo
ts of that in the cupboard. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did the cook make your own bread there or was the bread bought in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh the bread was bought in. Not - not so much - bread, scones - a lot of baking of scones, tarts, you know, and - and - when we used to get aroun
d to it used to - we used to make wee fairy cakes, I remember one day - she'd gone out to tea, and - to Mrs Geoffrey, oh I'll never forget that day, and - Jessie Byers, she was busy in the back kitchen and she says, there's not a bit of cake in the house,
 
she says. And her brother was coming to see her that night, she says, will you make some wee fairy cakes. And I was finished like my work then. So I got them going when the door opened and in she came. She hadna been feeling very well and she just knocked
 at the door and come in, she says, I'm deaf but I have a good sense of smell. Oh dear, she didna get them, we didna give her them because they were four ourselves, she'd plenty in her tins you see, but we had nothing. Ours had - well, we'd used them up.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You kept separate tins did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes, they had tins in a cupboard, because - I suppose she would often give Marjorie a cake or that if she asked for it, you know, she spoiled her. She spoiled her, but you couldna help it, she was a nice wee girl
, and - sometimes she would say - she bought a - nice piece of - perhaps that brides cake like when she was down - Carlisle, she would say, I'll give Mr McJerrow a piece of this today, she would give me a - piece to put in his tea parcel for a surprise fo
r
 him. Oh he loved sweet things. My husband's known him - come and ask for a - section of honey, and it was finished at teatime, and - he said, to Miss Norah, how did you like the honey? She said, honey, we never got any, daddy's eaten it all. Aye. Such a 
sweet tooth he had. It's true, honey just fresh off the hive.
\par <subject2>Mr. S. And once I was away - golfing with him, I took him up to Moffat - to play golf. And - he was playing with his brother who was home from Africa, and it came on a shower, and he sa
ys - we were near the club house, and he says, come on, we'll go in and shelter. And - his brother Tom said, oh, he said, we'll just have our tea when we are in. And I just sat down at the table along with the two of them you see and - Tom - his brother T
o
m poured out the tea and sugared it, put three lumps in each cup. And when he got his handed to him he pulled the sugar and put - other five in. I said, it's already sugared. It's what? Aye, I was looking for it dropping over the top of the tea.</subject2
>
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mrs. S. Isn't it funny to be so sweet toothed. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So that would mean plenty of jam and things for the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they keep any hens or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. Oh no, we'd no hens, no. Nothing like - like - that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they have meat every day in the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes, every day. Either meat or fish. Thursday - was a busy day, market day in Lockerbie and we used to clean the dining room that day, and they were in the breakfast room, which was a much smaller ro
om. So - we used to turn out the dining room every Thursday, and - always on a Thursday it was shepherds pie. The cook helped me you see to do the - the dining room, and it was shepherds pie - made from what remained of the cold roast beef. We'd have had 
that on - Sunday, cold on Monday, and then it was left over for Thursday for a shepherds pie and it was good. Aye. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they ever use any tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Any what? Not much at all, no, it was all fresh meat - beef steak pie, and - fowls and phe
asants in season. They were very fond of salmon when it was in season too. They used to have that, oh they always had - good food. Always good food. Sometimes it was three course, soup and meat and pudding, but always two course - it - I mean it was never
 
just the one course, there was always pudding, and - one kind of pudding Mr McJerrow did not like was railway pudding, you know, what railway pudding is. Railway pudding. Now I don't know why they called it that. But - it's just a sponge mixture, you know
,
 in a flat tin and - and you spread it with jam, and - and turn other half - away, he used to - look daggers when I come in, and Mrs McJerrow used to say - you'll have to think out some other kind of pudding, because he didn't care for milk puddings, it w
a
s all fancy. Aye. All fancy puddings. We used to have floating island, I can remember. Floating island, well it was just a - something - sponge at the bottom, custard on the top, egg custard like, not the - the - the tin, and then on the top - stiffly whi
p
ped - white of egg. He liked that. That would be sweet, plenty of sugar in the custard. And steam puddings, lots of steamed puddings, he was fond of them, apple pie or - like apple dumpling, I mean, oh he liked apple pie too but he liked apple dumpling. T
here was always - something like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did Mrs McJerrow say what you were to have, or was it just up to the cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes, she used to come through and suggest things. The cook - we had a - a girl - after Jessie Byers left there was a girl Alice 
- what was Alice's other name - it doesnae matter, she came from Richmond, Surrey. Richmond. And - she used to do a lot of suggesting to her, and - sometimes Mrs McJerrow - didnae just want what she proposed but she just let her - you know, make it, then 
she used to say to me, I don't think Mr McJerrow liked that. But she did what Alice wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about the messages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh we - we wrote out a list, a list - used to tell her what was getting done, I used to tell her if I needed anything, and Alice 
used to tell her, and Jessie, and then - she took it up or sent it up to Mr Ewart, he - his brother was the grocer you see, and it came down with the boys brought it down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say that you took Marjorie out for walks sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I had - used to t
ake her, oh I took her always up the street - she liked going in especially with this pram with the doll in it but - I don't know - the cat in it, she used to go with her doll, she'd a lot of dolls, I didna mind that, but when she took the cat I was fair 
in terror the whole time, especially when this dog's sniffing the cat. I thought we would never see it again, it bolted right over you field you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you ever take Marjorie to your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Canna remember that now. Did I ever take Marjorie to my house? Oh like to my own house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When you went home to visit your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye. That was too far, I don't think so, I cannae remember - my mother used to come in of course, she knew them fine. She used to always to take her through a
nd so did your step-mother too, she used to always have - if you had your mother's in she used to tell them to come through to the dining room and talked to them, and - any place I ever was they were always nice with mother, never at the Grove, but all th
e other places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 The Grove seems to have been on its own.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh the Grove. Oh - I would never go back to yon, you know, back. No, it - it was unfortunate you see, no many places, even in these days - kept you down like what they did, I mean not allo
wed to speak at the table and that - that was terrible. And - they used to tell us about Terregles, they were as free and easy as anything, they never made any difference although there was - head servants and lower, and - you were all working for them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It wasn't just the size of the place at the Grove?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. No. No, it was the atmosphere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you ever go away for the day with Mrs McJerrow or Marjorie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh they were often away, they used to go down to Rockcliffe for the day, Mrs -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you ever go with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No, I don't think so. I used to go drives with them certainly when they were - just round about, going round about for a drive but I don't remember ever going way, picnics or anything like that. We'd always something to do wh
en they were going away. Maybe turning out a room or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they go to church regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 We never got out to church there in the morning, because - Mr Ewart, that's the brother, and i
f the sisters were there they were always down for lunch on a Sunday you see, so couldna get out. We always went at night, except the time I told you about going to - oh we just went - in these days, there was just the one church in the evening, Trinity o
f St Cuthberts or the parish church, and we just used to go round them, whatever one it was we went to. They didn't all have a service. Just one at a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Which church did the McJerrow's go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mr.S. The English church. But Mr McJerrow went to - Trinity.
\par <subject2>Mrs.S. Aye, I think Mr - Trinity, aye. But - I mean they went together, they didnae - I mean - Mrs McJerrow would go to Trinity, and Mr McJerrow would go to the English church with her, I mean, but they really belonged to the - English 
church Mrs McJerrow, and the girls went there along with her.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they go to a Sunday school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, they didna go to Sunday school, No. Didnae. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they say grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - I don't think so, no. No, I was in the din
ing room, no they didna say grace at meals, except the minister was in. And of course he was in he said grace, they had to ask him, but they didna say grace. No. If - if there was visiting minister or a - any of the ministers were in seeing them, Mr - Geo
r
geson used to come visiting, and - that's the parish church minister, and - the English church minister used to come, who was at Trinity, Mr - Mr Whitefoot, yes, they used to all to come, and the - and the - the minister of St Cuthbert's just lived two or
 three doors off so he used to pop in too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He would be a friend rather than a calling minister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, quite friendly with them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When you first started working in the Manse you had prayers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have anything like that in any of the other places you worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
We had - we didnae have prayers at Highfield. We didnae have - no. No, just the manse and at Mrs Thompsons. That's the last place I was at Inveresk, we had prayers. Castle Street, we'd prayers every evenin
g. If it was our day matter, no matter if it rained - heavens hard, they should wait 'til you changed yourself. I used to say to - to Polly the cook, say that I'm soaked through, and coming on the bike, I'm not coming tonight. Tell her we'll wait on her. 
Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was Mr McJerrow interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, I don't think - the business was his one aim and end on life. Business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He was a solicitor was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Solicitor. Fine looking man he was. Handsome - man, wasn't he, fine looking man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You said he went to golf?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did he do any other sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He did, he'd go - he went to bowls. Aye. He did, he was interested in that. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did he ever go in for shooting or that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He had guns. Aye. Not when we were there I don't think, he was getting on then you see. He had guns, there was plenty of guns about.
\par <subject2>Mr. S. I went several times to shoots with him, and he would just say, oh you carry my gun Robert, and I used to shoot instead of him. He - he just went for the walk he wasn't interested.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Mrs. S. I remember one thing they had in the - in that breakfast room, they had a framed letter from David Livingstone, I used to read it often, from Samoa, you know, when he was out there in Africa, aye, I used to often read it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh just - he must have written - aye. Aye, it was business. Maybe he'd been sending funds you see, of course I didn't ask but I used to often read it because it was there for anybody to see. And I use
d to think, fancy having a letter from him, you know, it was interesting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did he ever go out to any clubs? Were there clubs in Lockerbie that men would go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I don't think so. No. Mostly - just - the meetings - in connection with the town business and that, he was often out in the evenings.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 The council meetings and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, council meetings he'd always that.
\par <subject2>Mr.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 S. And he only played golf for exercise.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mrs. S. I think so, he sat such a lot you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He wasn't really keen on sport as such?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. Not - not in our time, he might have been when he was younger, I don't know. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did Mrs McJerrow find to do with herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh she was always working. I'll tell you what she used 
to find to do, when it was cleaning time - she used to say, I'll come and give you girls a hands, and there she would come with a wee - tiny brush, nail brush, and she would be scrubbing, she would take hours, and she would say, oh I know fine I'm just in
 
the way, but I'm enjoying myself, we used to wish she was further. That's what she used to do. She was so pernickety wasn't she, and she says, I know fine what you're thinking she used to say, you're wishing I was out of that door. Well I'll go now and le
ave you to it. She was good you know. She used to -
\par 
\par <subject2>Mr. S. I used to tidy up the front Wednesdays and Saturdays, and on the Wednesdays I used to cut the grass, edge all the flower beds. And - tidy up the flower beds. And -</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did she go on any committees and do any charity work and that sort of thing?
\par <subject2>I don't think so, I don't think - she was very deaf you see. She - that would be - was a drawback. But - she - sewed a lot, she used to - and I tell you one thing she did. She 
had a Turkish carpet - in the dining room, big thick carpet, and - she went to Carlisle and she bought canvas and wool and she set to, you remember, and she made a hall carpet, taking the patterns off the dining room carpet, and it was most beautiful, gre
a
t big rug, and you took it to the shows for her and she got first prize at every show. She'd taken it - she taken it to some show and they were so delighted with it people seeing it, that they wrote and asked her for Moffat show, like the Dumfries show, I
 
don't remember. Eaglesfield show, just for the sake of seeing it. She was very good at taking patterns off you know, and sew - and she was always sewing, a beautiful sewer, both plain sewing and fancy sewing, tea cosies and - cushion covers and - she used
 
to sit in the dining room window and you go in and she would be going at it, she was always doing something. And it was just yesterday I was saying to my husband, I remember her - she used to say, oh I must get at that man's garments, this was - he - he w
ore wool and that - fine wool}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
en underwear, and you know how quick it tears, and she was always nibbling at that, and it - she wouldna have it unless she lifted every stitch. And it wouldnae do just in a hurry, she had to - oh dear, me no, she sat for hours
 at that. Oh she was very pernickety.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She did her own mending?
\par <subject2>Mending, she did the mending, aye. She did.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they go out together much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh when they were asked about, but - it was mainly with - the governes
s and - and the children, because he was - always had somewhere to go on business. Very very little time to go anywhere. They used to go their holidays together, but half the time - they went away one year to the Continent and he only stayed a fortnight a
nd wired to say he was coming home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He didna like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - he - he'd business to attend to so he said, but I think he couldnae stay away from the desk making money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How did you get on with the Belgian lady that came?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh she was very
 nice. Very nice indeed she was, and - Mrs McJerrow went away for a holiday down to Watford, and Alice the cook asked for her holidays at the same time. And - she said to me would I - well I'd to - do what I could like, in Alice's place, I said - oh I'll 
d
o what I could - I can, but I said how long's she going to be away for? So - she said, two weeks. And - Madame Oast knew and she says, never mind, Martha, I'll help you. I'll help you all I can, she was a good soul. But oh dear me, we didna care much for 
h
er cooking, for it was very greasy. One day - that was when you were away and Ritchie had come in your place, his younger brother - she'd made - salad cream, and you could have cut it with a knife, I never seen her - how she made it, but - I just had one 
t
aste and I - I just left it, and - Ritchie - I put some on his plate, we were having our dinner, and - he says, what's this? I says, that's Madame Oast's salad cream. So he says, oh no thanks, so - he cut up what meat he had left, he says, even the bloomi
ng cat ignored it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So you didn't like the Belgian cooking very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh no. Everything was very - you know, they work with lots of fat in everything. Mr McJerrow never said anything but - I don't know whether he liked it or not but she was very g
ood at helping, you know, swept the - floor and did the sweeping, and did what she could to help me. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about other visitors that they had to stay, did you get on well with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 With the governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 With any visitors that they had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes. Yes. Got on very well, they were all very nice. And - after about a year - they'd been with us a year, well - the priest - used to come and see her, and in the town - there was one or two Belgian families, we hadna much to do with any of them 
except Madame - and Mrs Poulhart, and her daughter, they were working class people, and Madame Poulhart used to come down and help when we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 need}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
 it, and - the husband took to coming down at night, I don't know what he come down for, he just used to sit in
 the kitchen and get his supper and go away again. Isador. Isador. Isidore, do you mind him? So Mrs McJerrow said one days, she says, what's - Madame Poulhart's husband coming down for, and I said I don't know. She says, unless he has a fancy for one of y
ou girls, this was what she said. Well, the cook says, he needna bother himself, there's not one - but Madame Poulhart had been jealous. We didna know but Madame Oast told us, she says, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 M}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 ark - don't encourage him. I says, we don't encourage him, Madame Oast
, I said, he just comes down of his own accord and, I said, we don't ask him to come back. So we got him stopped, the cook made an excuse that we were going out or something, and to make him think so we put the shutters on the back kitchen window so that 
i
t was all dark. Well - Madame Poulhart and these other people used to come - ringing the bell and both - and Madame Oast to sort out their difficulties, they'd difficulties with language - and - shopping and that, and in the finish I think Mrs McJerrow go
t
 a bit fed up, and - honestly before they went back to Belgium, Madame Oast used to be crying, and I used to go up and do her room, I used to be sorry for her. And she said, oh - don't say anything Martha, but I wish I was away back to Belgium. And I said
,
 well, Madame, I said, it's all these people coming out I said, and Mrs McJerrow not hearing, and I says, having to go out of the room when you're interviewing them, you know, it made a big upheaval in her life. So in the finish she got away to somewhere 
e
lse, but I never told, you know, anything about her being unhappy or anything, and - after they went back to Belgium they - they kept writing, because they really were good to them mind, but they just got fed up. And she began to be fair miserable, Mrs Mc
J
errow, wishing they were away. So - for a wee while, and nobody else in the town offered to take them, or - for a week or two, wasn't it a shame. I used to think it was a shame in - my own mind, that no other family offered to take them even for a fortnig
h
t or a month, it would have relieved them. And the priest used to come so often you know, and - the first time he came - he must have thought I was a Belgian, I don't know what - what he thought or whether he thought Madame Oast - had a house you see, and
 
he said, oh - well I didn't know what he said, but - Madame at home? I thought - took that's what he said, so Madame Oast come out of the dining room and she said, oh it's all right, it's Father somebody, I don't know what she called him, so I said - what
 
did he say to me when he came to the door Madame? Oh nothing Martha. I said, oh he said something. He says, you little Belgian darling, to me. Oh - she didna want to tell me. That's - the first time - oh, he says, you are English, in his own - in their ow
n language.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How did Mrs McJerrow get to know them in the first place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 They just had put their name down - to take a Belgian family, you know, that were - that - just like these - people -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Like evacuees in the last war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. And -
\par <subject2>Mr S. Being town clerk he come in for all these things.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Mrs. S. So - they got the schoolroom, what was the schoolroom, it was a great big room that ran all the length - of the house, the side of the house, and they had each singles b
eds, and a nice fire and a guard round for the wee girl, it was a lovely room and they were quite happy, and she brought her own - great big bed with her, a single bed Madam - Oast, but it was feathers, you know, puffed up like an eiderdown but three or f
o
ur times - and they didn't like on that, it lay on the top of you, it must have been nice and warm. And Julia was a nice wee girl and she turned out a famous painter, and they sent Mrs McJerrow a beautiful picture, this was what I was going to tell you, a
nd - two beautiful - copper things made out of shells for the drawing room fireplace. After they went back, they were quite -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you think Madame Oast was the same sort of person, the same sort of class?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He was a Consul. Yes. He was a Consul you
 see. Aye, he was kept there but he was well looked after by the Germans you know, he couldn't get out. Smith was her name you know, Oaster Smith, she told me, Smith in your language, she got quite proficient in - in English, aye, and so did Julia.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you think the McJerrow's were quite happy with their life as it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Or do you think they would liked to have been higher up the scale a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh I don't think so, no, I think they were quite happy. I think so. Think they were quite happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 After you had four years there you went to Mrs Thompson in Dumfries?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Went to Mrs Thompsons, yes. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Why did you leave Highfield?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - the cook - Alice, she was so much away, you see, and - she was out to communion Sunday 
morning, there were a lot put on to me, not that I resented it mind you, I didn't resent it but - it got just a bit - too much, I didna mind it for a wee while, but it kept on and on, and it meant that I - did the dining room, fried the breakfast, set the
 
breakfast on a Sunday morning, and it used to be a rush you know, because we werena supposed to come down stairs to seven but I used to get up before - sooner than seven because you could never have managed it. Alice was out early you know to go to commun
i
on, and it was a good walk, it was about twenty minutes walk up to the town. There was no buses or anything, she had to walk there and back. So that our breakfast was ready by the time she come back, I'd had to make two you see. And - it just got a bit to
o much, and I thought, well - I think I'll get away from here now, and - look for something else, so I got - to - Inveresk, now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was it advertised in the paper or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, it was in - well it didna say where it was for, but house table ma
id wanted. Housemaid, and I thought I'll have a go at this and see where it is, so here - she wrote tome and I went in to see them, and she seemed a nice old lady, which she was she was eighty four then, and - very - I was very happy there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was she all on her own in that big house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No, she had Miss Lane - her companion from Forres, and she was nice too, great big tall lady she was about six feet, and they were very homely, they just made you feel at home, just as if you were - on a footing with them. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What other staff was there there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
The cook too, there was a cook, yes, and myself. And a man used to come in do the wee bit garden, it wasnae much you know. And he used to potter away amongst the flowers themselves. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It was quite a big house to keep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh it's a big house, yes. But - they - mostly - kept to the dining room, it was on the - the - street level, cos she was an old lady to climb the stairs, her bedroom's up the stairs and so was Miss Lane, and they had two d
rawing rooms and the small drawing room wasna much used, except in the summertime. She had - at home days too, but they just used to - if it was people she knew - just had them in the dining room, to save - climbing the stairs, it was nicely furnished. An
d -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of people came to the at homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
The - do you know, I've often tried to think, there was a man used to come - I can't re - it's funny how that name's gone out of my memory. But he came from Catherine Street, he was staying with someb
ody there, I could go to the house yet where he lived, and he used to always to say when he came and rung the bell, any gingerbread on the go? That's what he - can't remember his name, see well this gingerbread was homemade. Aye. And - ladies that they kn
e
w from about the town just, somebody from Newall Terrace, that first house, Mrs Mc something they called her - coming from the station. Yes, Newall Terrace, they used to go up in there with the British Israel Bible Notes you know, that - she believed that
 
Britain was Israel, you see, that was her idea. And according to the - the teaching she used to teach us you know it could have been, she thought we - we were one of the lost tribes, the ten tribes you know, that Britain was. That was what her belief was.
 
She went to Greyfriars church mind you, and I used to go with them, but I used to go to St Mary's and -St Michael's, just - any of them. Just - just - I just went to - and - the cook was a Salvation Army - girl, and I used to go with her and she used to c
ome - with me to the church when we were out together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You had a very religious life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, we had, yes. Very.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You say that you had prayers there too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Every night, yes, half past nine, every night we had prayers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Where did you sleep in the house, where were your living quarters?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - we were underground really, down the area steps. The kitchen was to the back, and - and we had a wee sitting room to the front. That was - with a gas fire in it. And we could sit in there. Now 
- our bedroom was right at the top of the house, one - two, three stairs up really. And it looked right onto the Nith. Aye, it was nice, we used to sit up there when we knew - well the - finished with the tea, we could go up there, because you knew they w
o
uldn't - we could hear the bell, and Miss Lane would have called up, we used to say to her, we're going upstairs, we used to have the window way up and watch the boats going up and down on the Nith, it was nice, it looked over into Barrie's garden too you
 
know, the Moat Brae, aye. And - it was quite nice up there. We just had our - own bed up there, a bed, we used to come downstairs, we used to put our dressing gown on and come downstairs and we kept all our clothes downstairs, so - if the place had gone o
n fire during the night we had - we'd have been going out in our night attire, that's what we used to say. Oh we had great times there. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Would you like to tell us your story about your man in the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, it was an awful night. Polly h
ad gone to Hacks, that was where here home was, Racks Road and - her mother worked at Brocklehurst, that's the big house, but her father died, and the mother was left on her own. And - on a summer night we used to - when we were doing the spring cleaning,
 
like - maybe about May or June, they usually went away on their own. And - we used to get - work all day to six o'clock but as soon as we heard six o'clock we downed tools, and got ready, got our bikes out and away to the Racks, and sometimes we used to t
o
 go away to Templand, biking up to Torthor walk, but we'd to get away a bit earlier if we went there, to my home. And this night it was Polly's night out. And - she was away home. Well afternoon, we got away about one o'clock, as soon as the lunch was pas
t
, the quicker we got washed up and that. So off she went, and - when she come home - I knew about the time she would be coming home you see for prayers always. And - I heard the front door bell, and I thought, good gracious, who's this at this time of nig
h
t, and it was always locked after dark you see. So - when I opened it here's Polly, she looked frightened, and I said, what are you doing here, and she had her bike. She says, oh there's something white lying down the area steps. I darenae look over, I ne
v
er looked over. I says, isn't that terrible. I said, what'll it be, a paper, oh no, I don't think it's paper. She'd her bike turned down the step you see and bicycle lamp showed it. So - Doctor Gouldestcourt lived just across, that was Mrs Thompson's - do
c
tor, and - I thought to myself, I wonder if I should - but by this time the old lady was out of bedroom to see - who was at the door. And she says, dear me, Mary, they called her Mary, I always called her Polly, whatever's happened? And she says, oh I got
 
a fright Mrs Thompson, there's something - white lying down the area steps. She says, well phone for Doctore Goldescourt, so they - he wasnae long 'til he come over, and we never went out to see what it was, but here it was this naked man, he hadn't a sti
t
ch oh him. He must have been used to going to bed, you know, and - and - his boots and everything was - was on the first step, and he had all his clothes neatly folded, he wasnae that drunk but you ken he was near, and Doctor Goldescourt got the police an
d they got him away to police station, I don't know whether they took him to the infirmary or whether he was just put into the - police station for the night, but you ken -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they put his clothes on first before they moved him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh I dinna ken 
what they did. And when we heard it was a - a man, naked, I said, you'd have got a bigger fright if you'd been right down. So we never - we never went out like to be late again. We always - tried to get away so that we'd get home before dark. We didna go 
out in the blackout because it was the blackout after that, we never were out again. We'd no inclination to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was there a black out in the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes, there was a blackout, yes, there was a blackout. Aye. That - oh there was a blac
k out. Aye. There was. There's a cut - there's a cutting in there yet that was - you know, up in one of the windows like, a blackout curtain, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have to provide your own uniforms for the jobs that you were in or did you get uniforms provided?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, you had to provide your own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Evan at the Grove, a big place like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
A big place like that, yes. Just provide your own, take your frocks with you for the morning and frocks for the afternoon, black for the afternoon you know that w
as. And any kind of print in the morning, it didna matter. And - you - usually - in these big places they have uniforms you know, because this place - where we lived, Halleaths - when I was quite young at the manse these Halleaths - maids and the butler a
n
d them all used to come to morning service at this same church at Lochmaben, they had a pew up in the gallery and they used to look up at them and wonder what they were doing with these wee - bonnets on, this was the uniform you see. Well it's rather like
 - smaller of course but rather like - Salvation Army bonnets, and tied - with strings, and this was the uniform for the - place. But the Grove didn't, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You had to provide your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Had to provide our own. Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you remember how much money you got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Do you know, that's a - a - do you know, money - money must never have bothered me much, because - we - I seemed to have enough - Margaret was just asking me when she was here, she says, can you remember about your pay? I 
says, that's a thing I can't except the first - when I was at the manse. I know it was more because I would never have gone for - for less. But it was always more. Pay.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Even when you were older did you still give your mother some of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well
, mother didn't - we gave her what we liked when we got older, she said, now - don't give me your pay now, you're old enough to - buy your own things, she - look - if you said well you wanted this, that or the other, she would say, well buy something sens
i
ble, and she always approved of what you bought because we'd been taught - what to buy, but we used to always give them something because our pay would be bigger and - and we got our food in - and lodging, you know what I mean, we hadnae that to pay for, 
i
t was just our - frocks and shoes and - things like that. But we seemed to have plenty - and - we just used to maybe if we had two pound over or something like that used to take it home and - mother kept it, she was always giving us, it wasn't that we - w
e needed to give her but you tried to pay her back a little for - her kindness, you know what I mean. She made us all alike. The whole family, she never gave to one - but she gave to the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How often did you get paid when you were at Mrs Thompsons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - at the - at the - at the Grove - we just got paid once a month. Once a month. And - I think at - at - Highfield we were paid every week, I think so. But you were on monthly - basis like. If you wanted to leave you had to give a month's notic
e, you couldnae just go in a week, you'd to give a month's notice. It would be so much a month, and - if you wanted your pay - if you wanted it early - you cold get it, I mean if you needed it for something. For shoes or slippers or something like that yo
u could get it, but things were so cheap then you know. It wouldnae be so easy to cater now. They're such a price.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you tell me a little bit about what it was like at Mrs Thompsons? What sort of jobs did you do, what was the routine in the house?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh well, in the morning - Polly, that was the - cook, she did the dining room grate, she had the grate to do. And sweeping the dining room floor, and I did the dusting. Because I had the - morning room to do, they didn't use it often but you had to dus
t it and keep it tidy, and then - if they had had anyone in, the drawing room would be in use, it had a - lot of stuff in it you know, more than what they would have nowadays and - it was a big room to do, it was right down the next flat over the dining r
o
om, we had that to do, and - the rest of the - rooms, I kept. Polly - Mary was her name but we called her - I called her Polly, did the front hall, and I did the inner hall. There was like the hall at the front door, she did that. It was that not polished
 
for the sake of the old lady, just wiped clean, scrubbed and - wiped clean. And then I had the stairs from top to bottom to do. And there was a spare bedroom, and a bathroom - behind the dining room, I mean on the same flat and the morning room. Now this 
m
orning room went out - over a - a week bridge, you see, the - area - was at the back too, and you could get into the garden, so sometimes - you know, their dirty feet coming in off the garden, you had always to go over it and keep it tidy. And - there was
 
two drawing rooms, there was the big drawing room and the small drawing room. It was mostly the big one that was used, two bedrooms in that flat, and then - on the top, very top, another stair up - there was a - what they called the red bedroom and a bath
r
oom on that flat too. But the bathroom - was on the same flat as the dining room for the sake of the old - I expect all these houses are the same, and our bedroom was right up - as I told you, at the top of the house. And there was lots of - you know, dow
n
 the area steps and in at the back door there were lots of - there was a place where you cleaned the knives, there was a knife machine for cleaning the knives. And - lots of cupboards where they kept - cases, travelling cases and that. There was two or th
ree, I think these houses will all be the same but these didna}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080  need anything but I suppose P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
olly did these two, down on her - my pantry was downstairs, and then I had a small one - on the dining room flat too where I kept the - spoons and you know, tea ware and everything like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did the old lady get her breakfast in bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Not often. No. Not often. Was quite spry. She come downstairs, of course - she'd - she'd - bouts of asthma, and if she was - no very well with asthma well she stayed in her r
oom for her - breakfast but - took it up on a tray to her, and she was always down by dinner time again. There was only once I remember her being - really ill, and - Miss Lane, that was the - companion, she slept in a bedroom next and she'd been in - ther
e
 was a little - bed put up in the corner of her room, and it was right at the gas fire, you know, there was a gas fire. And - Miss Lane hadnae got much sleep for a night or two you know, and oh dear me, she said, now I don't like asking you to do this but
 
I wonder if you'd come for a night or two and - and - sleep in my room to let Miss Lane get a rest. I didna fancy it then, as this gas fire was the thing, the heat was - it was a big fire, kept a bowl of water there, but - all night long I never shut an e
y
e. She'd a repeater watch, a gold repeater watch and - she wasnae sleeping you see, she was sitting up you know, pillowed up, and she was always putting on this watch and - even if I did want to fall over this new noise - wakened me, I wasna deaf in these
 
days. So she knew fine that I wasnae sleeping, so after two nights I got up to my own room, and Polly come down and - slept with her and by that time she was getting better. She didnae impose on you, she didna like - to think that you werena sleeping or a
nything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She wasn't the kind to tell you to do things, she would ask you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh no, she just left you to your own devices. They never bothered you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they go away much?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 They went away - in the summertime they took a house - down at Auc
hencairn, you know, at the shore. I went to see it two years ago when we were round - and - it was there, just the same, but - just across from the cot - it was a cottage, now wait a minute 'til I tell you the story about that cottage. It was the cottage 
w
here the man - that writes all the stories down there had lived, now I should remember his name - he writes all these stories about Heston and Auchencairn, isn't it funny, it's gone out of my mind, but I'll maybe mind it. But he had lived here in former y
e
ars. And - the lady that owned the cottage was a Miss McGuire, and - she usually went away at holiday, and - look - allowed anyone to take the cottage, I don't know how they heard about it, but they told me they were going here. And for two weeks I went. 
And then - after that - I went home and had my holiday. My summer holiday. And Polly came down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How long did you get for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Two weeks. Yes. And - we had a parrot, and it - it was a funny bird, they had a canary too, and this little canary used
 to get out and fly about in the dining room, and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
olly was jealous of it and one day it landed on its cage and it broke its leg, with its beak. Yes it did. So it liked me, that was the funny thing. Always at tea time - four o'clock, took the tea up to the
 dining room and - you - you know what Indian corn's like, that yellow stuff that - well - you had to boil that, the cook had to do that of course, boil this Indian corn 'til it was soft. And - it was a funny bird, it used to go to it and say, scratch }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 oll
y. And it would put down it's head. Only at tea time. It learnt that. Scratch. And then - I put in its corn, and this day - this special day that I'm going to tell you about, Polly had forgot to put on the corn, it wasnae very soft. So she told me, and I 
s
ays, by jove, I'll need to get out of the dining room in a hurry today, because it could talk you know. So - I pushed in - I filled up its dish and pushed it in and - and was hurrying out of the dining room, and she went - hard, hard, hard, you could hear
 it. And she says, oh is it hard }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
olly, it hasn't been boiled long enough, and it wouldn't eat it. And - in the morning - at - in the evening I should say to being with you covered it up with a cloth and it said goodnight. Goodnight darling, it'd say to me.
 And - in the morning - the cook was frightened for it, and I think it knew that, she had to clean it out, it was her job to clean it out, and she used to be terrified, it could nip you know if you didna watch it, and instead of - putting in her hand to g
et out the stick she used to turn the cage quick and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 Po}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
lly would float down into the top of the case and she got out the sticks, it didna like this. And she was never at home with it. But - when you came in in the morning and opened it up it would say, good
 morning darling, it could talk you know, it was quite a good talker, they were very fond indeed of it. So }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
olly was to go for holidays to Auchencairn, and it wasn't very well when it went away, I must say, I don't know what was wrong with it, but it wasna
e very grand at all. And - its cage went, in the train, and it went in a - in a basket with cover over and air got in, so when we got home it was to come to me - it was to be in the kitchen because there was a fire in there always, it was the summertime a
n
d they didnae have a fire every day. So - Polly settled down, but - it wasnae eating very well. And - I tried to do the best I could for it but it stopped talking, it never bothered. Mrs Thompson was in an awful state, so she said to me one day, do you kn
o
w what I think I'll do? I said, no. She said, I think when the doctor comes to me today I'll ask him to come through and look at Polly. So - the doctor came, an Auchencairn doctor - the doctor at Dumfries would write to this one you see and he used to com
e
 up and just see that she was all right and give her her pills for he asthma. So the doctor came through, he seemed a very nice man, he said, what's wrong with the bird? I said, I don't know doctor, I said, it's no - bright as it usually is. So he asked a
bout its age and that and he says, you know it's getting on to be an old bird. And - he says, we'll leave it for a day or two, and, he says, if it doesn't get better - it was sitting, you know, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 moping}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 , and - that was all right, so in the finish - the doctor
 said that he thought it should be put to sleep, and it hadna been talking for days. And do you know, when that man came in to put it to sleep, it says, will you walk. Oh doctor, she says, I couldn't have anything done to it, it's getting better. And do y
o
u know, it did get a bit better and got bright. So - the first thing - first thing Polly - the maid said to me at the station at Dumfries, how's that bird? I said, oh it's no been well at all but it's a bit better now. She says, I was hoping, she was hopi
n
g it would die for she was frightened for it, but of course they didna know that. So I said, well it's getting better. So I went and I had my fortnights holidays and I got word to come back - early in the morning so that I would have the fire on and the h
o
use opened up, the windows opened, so I was there, and when I met them at the steps, the bird was here because the basket was here. So - I said, how's it been keeping? Polly said, oh it's no very grand, it does - I think it's missed you, she said, I bet i
t
 would because Polly had no time for it. So - the very night they came back home they went along to Mr Bier the vet, he lived in Castle Street, and asked to come along. And he came to look at the bird. He said - I think the bird's had a chill. He said, it
'
s eyes are bright, but I think it's recovering from a chill. Well, I said, it's bound to have had it a long time, he said, maybe the shifting about wouldnae help it any. He said, who usually works with it? Well, I said, I feed it and that. So he said, wel
l
 tonight - he said, I want you - it was in the dining room there of course - I want you to take it down where you can have the fire on all night, that was the kitchen. We stocked it up you see. And - give it a tablespoonful of brandy. You ever know anythi
n
g like that, I don't know whether he knew what it would do or not, and he said, wrap it well up with - blankets or something warm, and he said, I think that'll sweat it out. Well do you know before we went to bed the bird was staggering about in the cage,
 
it was drunk. It was drunk. And I was always up first and when I come down in the morning, you know, it had got its head through the bars and it got hanged. But I never told the old lady. I said Polly had died. And - she just thought it - you know, that i
t
 - natural. I took its head out of the - so - then the funeral took place, and they had a box lined with green satin, the pair of them, and invited me to the funeral. Polly wouldna go, she says, oh I'm no hypocrite, I'm not going to its funeral. And they 
b
uried it in the garden you know, the - the - the nephew had brought that bird home from Africa to them when it was young, and they had taught it all that it knew you know. And it could sing, and it said - Polly put the kettle on, you know, and all these t
hings, it was just - something for the old lady you know. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It would be just like a child to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
It was, yes, she was very fond of it. So Polly died, and - that was the end of Polly. But - one day - it - it used to go out in the garden with
 them in its cage when they were sitting out in the garden and this day - they called down - Miss Lane came in, called down to - just to put the tea in the dining room, just to take their tea outside - as it - a cold wind had got up and she thought Mrs Th
o
mpson should come in, so of course it wasnae time for the Parrot to come in, and do you know what it did? The only time it ever bit me, it was fair angry, because the sun was out, but it was a cold wind. And I went to lift the cage and it just got me like
 that and took the bit right out. Oh, she says, Polly, whatever have - are you doing, she was ve}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 x}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
ed with it. I had to go about with a - a thing on my finger for long enough. It didna mean it you know, I don't think it would have done to me but - it was angry at being taken in before its time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It seems to have had a mind of its own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. Oh dear. So that was - that was the end of Polly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How long did you stay with Mrs Thompson?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Four years. Four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And then of course you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh aye, the time I was there though I was married. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you work after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes. When - I remember my - my mother coming in to see me and she - my mother happened to see her in the dining room as she always did, and she said she wonde
red if I would come back to her because she says, I don't think I'll let her away if she won't come back - to get married you see. So I went back to her, and - you didna come home 'til 1919, during the - 1919, so - in the March, I said to her, I think you
 
should really be looking for someone else because - my husband'll be home any time now and I'll want to get home. I didna know just exactly the time. So funny thing - she'd written to Mrs McJerrow for my reference - when I went to her, and a girl that had
 
been there applied for - the - to come - no, but she didna get it, she let me read the latter, and she said unfortunately she couldn't recommended this girl like she had recommended me. So - there'd been something they didna like her 'cos they didna take 
her. But they got another girl, and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you work at all after Mr Shearer came home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh no. They wrote to me - the - the - I forget what they were going - they kept in touch with me, and - they were coming - coming through Lockerbie, and they w
rote and asked me to meet them - at the station to see them, they were sorry when I left you know, and - then - they called Inveresk after the place where Mrs - Thompson had been brought up, that was Inveresk, Musselbourgh, and went away back there. And M
r
s - they both died and - oh of course that's years ago. I forget who it was, I think it was Polly - sent me a cutting out of a paper - to - I have it somewhere - that Mrs Thompson had died I think in her eighty-eighth year, Craigen - Craigengar, Musselbur
gh that was the name of the place. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You liked working for her did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye. But - when - once while we were there - she was forgetful you know, and - if they had been there - like I mean at Dumfries she was leaving Polly and I furniture, we s
aw this writing out in the - werenae spying or anything, when we were - when I went into the dining room her writing desk was open and papers all scattered all over the place, and it was lifting them up off the floor, she must just have gone off to bed ma
ybe meaning to come back and tidy up and forgotten. And - I think it must have been the time when Miss Lane was ill because I couldn't help seeing my name and here this was all what - what they were leaving us, and I says to Polly, by }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 J}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 ove, if we're here we
'll get our houses furnished. She says, how do you ken? I said, because I've been reading - the papers that she had left, I couldnae help but see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get anything though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, you see, I went away. Everything had been sold they'd only tak
en what was - necessary with them. And - and she had that old lady, Miss Bell, staying with her, she was her sister, and she wrote this British Israel Bible Notes in her seventieth year, I have a copy of that, and - she went a wee bit funny you know. Well
 
- she thought it was my house, she thought Inveresk was my house, I used to do her - her grate and that in the morning before she was up and she used to talk to me, she was a nice old lady, and she had a - a companion too, Miss Scott. Just a wee wee soul 
she was, and - Miss Bell was a great big tall lady, and - she says to me - Fordyce, that was Mrs - Thompson, wants me to go away from here and I don't want to go. It's getting too be to much for her having me here, so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Here sister was put in a home was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No, not in a home. So Miss Scott said to me she said, just talk away to her as if she was going to be here, she says, you know, she forgets, however - they arranged with this - these people up in Musselburgh to - give Miss Scott and her rooms 
each and the used of the dining room. And it was a June day and they asked me to go with Miss Scott for company. Well - it was Miller, a motor hirer on the Sands that did the - don't know whether they're still there, don't think they're thr}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 e now but it wa
s the son that came to take us. And at Moffat - it got very very warm in the car so she wanted to get out and walk about a little bit, and Miss Scott let her out and could hardly get her in again, way up in the moors. Well - eventually - we got her - and 
w
e arrived at this place, and from the very start I didna think that it would be a very suitable place for her, because the bedrooms were upstairs, and Miss - Bell wansa very good at climbing stairs, and - they stayed there about a year and then - they wen
t
 somewhere else, and eventually Miss Bell died. Died like - I heard about her death, told me Miss Bell had passed away. But Miss Scott was never happy up there. They were happy with us, but - it got too - much for the old lady, she was older than - you kn
o
w, she - they were never at peace, she was always imagining things, and Miss Scott used to take her out walks and sometimes he couldnae get her in. One day she went into the vet's, she said this was where she lived. You know, the people about there all kn
ew her, and she started to take off her coat and things and this was where she'd come to - so it was a - rather a burden for the old lady. But she was a nice old person, Miss Bell. Yes, she was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you tell me how long you had known Mr Shearer when you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh, I'd known him - all the time - he was there do you see. When - when - when he came there, four years, he cannae hear us now, if I tell - if I'm telling anything wrong he canna hear us, he's deaf. About four years. And of course - 
oh more than that because it was - at - Inveresk about two years you see before I got married. 1917.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Your homes were quite near each other weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 My home, yes, quite near.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 But working in the same place you had quite an advantage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you write a lot to him when he was in the forces?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes. I wrote - I wrote a lot to him and - and - he wrote to me when he could. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I wouldn't always be convenient to get letters posted back to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye. Well - I just used to write every week, and - sometimes he didna get the letters - be a great bundle come at once - in the end - a chum that he met in - down at Bullford I think it was had given him the address of somebody in Africa to call on, a cha
p coming home, coming this way to - service into the forces and these people wrote tome and said that - he hadnae called but that they'd had a letter. Nice people they seemed to be, they'd had a letter from him apologising, instead of going Africa they we
n
t over to France and down through Italy, down the Suez canal, so - oh I got one or two scares the time he was away there. I got a cable came one day to say he was in hospital dangerously ill. And - hepatitis was on the cablegram, I didn't - no idea what t
hat was. So Mrs Thompson said for Doctor Gordon Scott to find out and he said had he ever had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 dysentery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
, well he had after he went, a bad climate it was, and he said it might have been an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 abscess}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
 left on the liver from this, and it would just depend - if it
 was deep seated they couldnae do anything, so - for about six weeks I'd - I wouldn't answer the door in case I got - another cable from him but he said I might have known when there was no word that it was better news, but of co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2644963\charrsid2967080 urse you always - think the wor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
st, and it turned out it wasnae that at all. They had him on the table to operate and it was double pneumonia he had. No that hepatitis at all, he told me all this when he come home. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you remember the very first time that you went to meet Mr Shearer's parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Parents? Well - I'd met them you see, I'll tell you how. The day that they came they had a wee pony and trap and they brought him over, you see, and of course I met his father and mother then so I really knew them. Aye. Oh they
 were very good while he was away. They used to come and see me - in that time and of course they went to see my parents too, and - and they had a - they had a wedding in the family - the time he was away and invited my father and mother to the wedding, t
hey were very nice, and I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were they much the same sort of people as your own folk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes, very nice, homely people. Very nice. She was always very nice with me for she fought with all her other daughters-in-laws I must say. But I must have kep
t the right side of her. She'd her funny ways you know, she was very pernickety over things and she sometimes said things in a manner that you could take offence at but - I just bit my tongue and didna say anything and - I helped them all I could when his
 
mother was very ill before he died - I went for three months and helped - granny had to stay upstairs with him you see, she was never out of the bedroom, except someone was - came up and Nellie had the Post Office to do so she'd to be there so they needed
 somebody. And - he used to say to me, when - if I'm spared to get better I'll buy you the best fur coat at the shop. But he wasnae spared, it was cancer. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Before you were married and Mr Shearer was away in the Army did you go and visit them then too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes, I used to go and visit them, I had my bicycle, I had a bicycle, used to bicycle from Dumfries and sometimes instead of going to my own home I used to go to them, yes, they were very kind.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You really got on well with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Got on very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did you call them before you were married? Did you call them Mr and Mrs Shearer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, uh-huh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, grandpa - grandpa and grandma, because that's what they got at home with the other grandchildren you see. Aye. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you remember the first time you took him home to meet your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - I don't - oh well - I think - you see, with mother coming in - I don't know that my father had been, but mother used to come i
n often and see us so she would meet him then. Like they knew him fine you see. At least mother did. And - they quite approved of - us getting married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have any other boyfriends before that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh aye, I had boyfriends before that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 The kind that you took home to your folk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes. The one - the first one I had, I think I would just be about fourteen year old, and - well I didna care for this man at all. He - he worked on the farm, nice fellow mind he was looking back. He seemed - he 
was a nice decent sort, and - mother used to say that - my youngest sister you see was ten years younger than me, she was just a child when I was there, just a wee girl, and he used to bring her toys and - always when he went away maybe for a weekend he u
s
ed to always bring her something back, that was, mother used to say, that was just the way - for him to get up, you know, to bring something for Joan, and - then he asked - asked if he could see me home when I used to go to the bank. And - I never took hi
m
 in because we wasnae allowed, and he just used to turn on his bike, he seemed quite pleased to have seen me home and - and through the week he used to - write and oh I used to be - wonder how I could get off with him because I didna care for him in that 
m
anner, I was too young, and - in the finish he changed his job and I told him then that I didna want him to write anymore. So it was a funny thing - he married in later years and - one night we went to the pictures, my sister and I in Lockerbie. This was 
a
fter we were married. And - she said, this is Mrs Deacon. Deacon was his name. And I said - where does your husband work, I was wondering if it was him. And she says - he works at Southfield, near Lockerbie, she said, I've biked here tonight. I said, I us
ed to know a lot of Deacons, I said, what was his - it was him, Tom. And my sister says, eeh, he used to be a lad of Martha's.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She spilt the beans did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. Right out you know. She's just like that. Oh that was in the days of long ago.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did your parents ever warn you off any boys, did they ever tell you not to go with certain boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No. No, they were - they seemed very decent boys, I had another boy - well it was - my father and - and his people were very friendly, and - my father wa
s a great fiddler, you know, violin and - both his - father and his brother, and they used to come a lot to our house you know and have nights with the violin, three of them, and the - the - this younger one came and I was on with him a long time, in fact
 I just stopped going with him when I got on with Bob.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How did you start going out with Mr Shearer, how long had he been at Highfields before you got friendly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - oh a good while. A good while, because I'd got another boy up in Lockerbie then, 
and he used to come down and see me. Not going serious, just friendly you know, he would have liked to have been serious this one but - he was killed at the war. And he turned out to be a great friend of my husband's in the Army and this lad, he worked in
 
Mr McJerrow's office, and how I met him was just going up with Mr. McJerrow's sea you see. And - he asked me out and I used to go out with him and go to the pictures with him and that but just friendly you know. And - then I started going out with - with 
Bob. And that's the way of it. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You said you went to pictures with boyfriends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
It was silent pictures in the Town Hall. And there used to be another thing come, they called it the geggie, I don't know how it got that name, but it was a - in a
 hut up in - football field, it was a big hut and they rented this for - a week or a fortnight and - they had variety turns on this. Acting and - pictures too, they had it fixed up for pictures as well, and - it wasnae dear I think only sixpence a night, 
a
nd there used to be a change three times a week. And - used to go - there was always something to do. And there was plenty of nice walks about Lockerbie, used to you could go a walk it was three miles away around by the cemetery and up the Dumfries Road, 
that was a - usual walk for - young folk in these days. Yes. That's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 And you used to go to dances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How often would you do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well, they didna have them as often as what they have them now but they used to have th
em - maybe once a month or something, I didn't go to them every time you know, but quite frequently. Used to like the country dances but - put a stop to that after we walked back and - I was - oh aye, I was ill and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When you started going out together how often would you be able to see each other and go out at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
To go out like? Oh well, we - we were off every - I had my - afternoon off and evening, but we usually went home, my sister and I, my sister was in Lockerbie, went home, Sundays. On
 Sunday, Sunday evening, instead of going to church we used to go away for a walk. And the cook had a - young man too, so we were both the same, she couldna tell on me because she was doing the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You didn't all go out together though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh no, no. Just the two of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You didn't go on any holidays together when you were courting did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No. No, not when we were courting, no. No. You see the - in the holiday time I - at Highfield - we usually had to have our holidays when they were on
 holiday, and then they needed someone there to look after the house. Well I would maybe get away a fortnight and then - the cook would get away a fortnight. That's the way of it - they worked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did he actually propose to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Properly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes. That was when it was at - we - we were going together a long time, but we got engaged about a year before we got married. Maybe a year and a half I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 That was when he was away in the Army you got engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. Yes, -that w
as when the war started, and - he - we were down the Dock Park, that's where we were sitting in a seat, that was when he asked me to marry him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did he have to go and ask your parents permission first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes, he went and told them anyway. And they were quite pleased. Because we - we were going together for quite a while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Then did you go and see him folk and tell them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Ah well, he did that, and invited me over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get an engagement ring?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, I'll show you it, I cannae wear it now. Went together and chose it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You didn't give Mr Shearer a ring did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 That wasn't the fashion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, it wasnae the fashion, I gave him a cigarette case. I think he lost it in Ireland didn't he. Didn't you lost the ciga
rette case I gave you in the Army? Aye. Aye, he said he lost it. I got it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When you got engaged was it in the paper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh no, no. No, I didnae need to be in the papers it's not long in a village -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have a party when you got engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No. No party, no. We had no party. And - when it came to the - fourteenth of November, 1917 was when we were married, well - our own minister, he only got leave for - what leave had you when we got married, just for two days or something. Aye. Our own
 minister couldnae marry us you see because he had a previous engagement, and he was very sorry about that, so - Mr Lane of the Barras manse came and married us. We were just married at home, and we had a party that night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Supposing it had been normal circumstances and you had both been living at home would you have been married in the church do you think?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
It was quite normal in these days to be married at home or in the village hall, or in the school, as the weddings were held - in my time, but 
- for some reason we couldnae even get the school that night. The following year, 1918, my sister got married, she was engaged at the time, and she got married in - wait a minute, July, July the fifth, she was married on - my father and mother's silver we
dding day. The date like. And - it was in the school. It was held in the school and we had all the celebrations there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 To go back to your wedding, did you have time to arrange it all beforehand or didn you just get short notice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well, they did i
t at short notice, we'd a wedding cake but it was a wartime wedding cake, and - they made it very nice, it was - wasna much fruit in it, it was more sponge because you couldna get it, and it was decorated with - flag - you know - you know what - aye, and 
t
hey really made a good job of it, the short time they had, McMichael - the same McMichael that's there yet, they did it, and - at - in occasions like these everybody helps in the village you know, just like the golden wedding that was there, the village p
eople all helped, baking - everybody helps. So - we had a party, it was very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How many people would there be there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Nearly - don't know, about - between fifty and sixty anyway, because most of the village was asked and all - the relatives we
re mostly near at hand you see. My brother - that was to be best man, he was the only one that was - far away, he was at Ramsgate, he was just in at the end of the war, he was a young - fellow then, and he was just eighteen and in - to service, and in the
 finish he couldna get - so - my sisters - young man stood in for best man. And - and my sister -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have a bridesmaid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, my sister was bridesmaid, she laughed all the time. She - you know, she's a - she's so cheery, she laughed all the t
ime she was getting married I may tell you that, because the minister's wife, Mrs McCall, she asked - Mr McCall, this was our own minister asked if he could come to - bring Mrs McCall for she'd never seen a Scots wedding, she was English. And - mother sai
d
, certainly, so - she happened to be sitting next to me, we didn't know her because they were just newly come there to Lochmaben, we hadnae got to know her, so she says - my isn't she happy? She was laughing all the time. Do you know what she was laughing
 about? Wally had been put - she'd held out two fingers and he was putting the ring - and she couldn't - and she couldn't \{BLANK\}
 for laughing, we found out afterwards that's what the laughing was for. And she says, well if that's an augury of her married l
ife it's going to be a good one. So she says, you'd another sister married hadn't you just a wee while ago? I said, it was me. Oh, she says, you, I thought you were about sixteen. See she must have thought I was younger. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It all went well for your wedding did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, oh yes, everything went well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You would have a rush to get a wedding ring and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I had no wedding dress, I had just as it happened - I had just got a new nigger brown costume. Nigger brown, and - wasn't it funny
, I had never even worn it, and - that stood in for my - my wedding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What was it like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It was nice, and - and Miss Lane, that - lady I was with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 The companion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I had a white - blouse just and she gave me a beautiful collar, it's in th
e house somewhere, of Maltese lace. I had that on, it was very nice. It's - sort of creamy, it was more creamy than white, and - I had a brown hat, velvet hat, big hat. And that was - that was what I had for - both for my wedding and for going away in. On
l
y went down to my husband's people, you see, he - he should really have been back but he stayed one night, and - I went right back to my place, I never went home again because I knew I'd be fair homesick. So I went right back to work. And it was a lovely 
sunshiney day. Polly had sent me a telegram, that was the - the - and she says, well, you got the sun anyway even if it was November, lovely sunshiney day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did people send telegrams to weddings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. Yes. Aye. She sent me a telegram.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about your wedding ring, did you have to rush away and buy one just before the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh - yes, we went to Dumfries and bought it at - now what was the name of the man, it was near - you know where - no, wait, it's not Youngs. Where - yes, it is Youn
gs. Youngs is right on Buccleugh Street, no, I'm wrong. Do you know where the - the fish shop is - wait 'til I think, you know the street where Woolworth's is on the High Street, well further down - there was a fish shop, Turners shop, is Turner still the
re I'm wondering. I've nae been in Dumfries for ages, then next to that there was a jewellers, Anderson, and that was it. Aye. Went there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You had enough money saved up to buy it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh had enough money, oh - we'd been saving up you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you save up for quite a while?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes. Yes, whenever we started - going together we started saving up for the - great day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have a bottom drawer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh aey. Lot's of things, yes. I remember - the girl that went away from Highfield, Jes
sie Byers, she went to a place at Moffat after she left, she was away before me and I remember the first thing I got, I have it still, was a teacloth, I saw a teacloth she sent me, she says, you know what that's for, that's for your bottom drawer, and I w
as always getting things from friends and - anything I saw myself that I fancied I - I'd quite a good - gather up by the time I got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did your mother save things for you as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. Yes, oh mother was always giving us things. She was. An
d in those days - there was - rugs made, you know, not rag rugs, I don't mean rag rugs, but mother used to do them with a pin. Pinned rugs. I have a wee - mat in the lobby, I could show you what I mean - mean by that, and she made beautiful rugs. This gir
l
 at Inveresk could - when she seen them - she was making one once - when she went and she said - if I ever get married Halliday will you make me a rug. Poor Polly, she never got married. And - mother had one or two rugs made for me you know. And - used to
 \endash  save up rags and you know, wash them - and dye them, you could dye them all colours, and they lasted for years, these rag - what they called them rag rugs but - these done with the pin were what they called crocheted rugs. Aye, crocheted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have any special goings on when you left your work to get married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You know sometimes nowadays if there's a girl leaving to get married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have a party the night before or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh no. I know they do 
that now but no. No, there - there wasnae anything like that then. They used to - in those days I can remember they used to do terrible things to the bridegroom in the villages like. But - of course they couldna do anything to Bob because he wasna there y
ou see. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What sort of things did they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh, they used to tar and feather them you know, the way do, oh they used to do terrible things, and - keel - they'd to put on - on - they used to sometimes do them all with this and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was this like sheep dip or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye, that - oh the things they - and it would be sore mind you. Oh dear. They used to do it in these days, just the village boys you know. Full of mischief. I remember once - the bridegroom arriving in a cab, and he could
na get out, they had - they had the - the door handles, I don't know how they did it, but they had them all tied and he got quite angry in the finish, and the minister there waiting on him to go into the hall, in the hall then, and he couldna get out - oh
 
and they were laughing, just the folk were as bad as them that had done it - because they were just laughing. But he got quite angry in the finish. And I even remember - when - we lived up at - Wallbut, that's - Cross Michael - the tablemaid got married, 
w
ell we were there and we were invited down to the church to the wedding, and - Mary was there, this was the bride like, and was in the ante-room and Jim was twenty minutes late, and this was what had happened to him. They had tarred him, and he couldna ge
t
 it off, and - and - no only that - they had tarred his face and he had done it with lard and everything, and he come in quite flustered and - and - they had - tied up his cab, his motor, they had it tied up too, and - and he - that was Mr Fisher and he w
a
s a very strait laced man, and he was very angry about it. He said fun was fun but that was going a bit too far, Mary could hardly stand. She thought he wasnae turning up. That's what it was. They're still alive and live at - eeh now wait a minute now, wh
ere was that lady that died? Oh dear me, what a memory - Buchan, I've just remembered the name of the writer, Buchan was the name of the writer. Aye. And - what do you call the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How did you get people invited to your wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you just have to go and ask them yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, that was just what happened, just had to go and ask them, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How much warning did you get that he was coming home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No - well - we knew that he was coming home but we wasna sure when, that 
was the thing that - that was getting a leave but we werena sure when but we knew it would be about that time. And - that's maybe the stickman Bob. He'll no hear us. Think of it now - both my brothers had bicycles, of course the one was away in the Army, 
b
ut - I had another brother, and my young sister, maybe they would go on bikes, I expect that was what it was, my father had a bicycle too, we had his - his chum there, so - that's - my father's chum so that's how he would go, he'd just bike up and ask the
m, it was only - about a day or two's warning we could give them. But I got lots of presents. You know, we got them - if I didna get them at the time - I got them afterwards you know. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have showing of presents in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh I had
nae - they used to, my sister had a show of her presents, she got a lot of nice presents too, but - we didna make such a fuss about it as what they do now. In those days, when you went to see the presents - mother would just say, come up and see the prese
nt, you know, there werena anything put in the papers or anything and - it was always a cup of tea, a home-baked cakes and scones and - cup of tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I suppose Mr Shearer would just have to wear his uniform?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 That's right, it was a war wedding and f
unny thing was - the next day when we went down - we went down to Lochmaben, we got a hire to Lochmaben and his father was to meet us there, they had a wee pony and trap and - we read our own banns out in the church. Wasn't that funny. They were put out i
n
 the church door you see. Because there was no time to do anything else. And we were married then but we read them before his father came to - to get us. And it was only like the night and then - the next day I went to Lockerbie with him and that was him.
 So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You had your sister as a bridesmaid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did she do about something to wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - she had something handy, yes, she'd just wear something like what I had on myself, I think she'd a navy costume, I think that was to - not exactly navy, it was more - a sax blue. Oh we'd not time to get anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get flowers or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I had - orange blossom, it was real orange blossom, we had a tree. Aye, we'd a tree.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How many people did you have in the house for the actual wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh there were - they were all there, they were crowded - they were crowded in, it was a - fairly big living room. Fairly big. They were all crowded in, some of them werenae sitting, they were just standing. Aye. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get any photographs taken?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, not then. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get one taken afterwards?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Later, yes, larger on. Aye. Not then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about confetti and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh yes, they had confetti and rice too, rice was a great thing, they t
hrew at you in those days. And - before - before I went in - we were still looking for my brother - come you see, and - here - my father disappeared, he was to take me in and - couldna see him and Jean says, I wonder where my father's gone, he's not to be
 
seen, and she went outside to see if he'd gone outside, and here he is opening a telegram - by the light of the - car lamp, there was somebody there with a car, and she says, what on earth are you doing father, they're waiting on us going in. And he says,
 oh - it's just a wire to say Tom canna come, that was my brother, just at the last minute. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about the food, did your mother have to do most of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh she had. Aye she had. As I tell you the villagers always very good, we had - a tea, li
ke it was just tea, and - cooked - cooked - I think grandma had boiled - boiled the ham, must have got a fairly big ham, and - mother had roast roast meat. You know, at a time like that - the butchers stretched a point and did what they could for you. Aye
. Yes. That's right, yes. And that's what we had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was there room for everybody to sit down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh there was plenty -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Or was it just a hand round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, it was - we all sat down. Great big - two tables there was - in the - the big bedroom, t
he bed was taken down, you see, I don't know where they were or anything, I mean - they must have been in somebody else's house probably, and we had two big long - boards from the hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Trestles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, trestles. That's right. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did anybody make speeches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh they made speeches and wished you all the - luck in the world, oh they always made speeches, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Would your father make a speech and then Mr Shearer have to make one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I know my father - he never did say much my fat
her, it would be very - just a few words saying that he - he hoped the - bride - the best man of course - did the toast, and - and - I heard somebody shouting did he not - did he no wish he'd been in his shoes, because I used to go with him. That's as sur
e as I'm - sitting in this chair. I thought it was bad taste though, it's a shame. Yes. Aye. That's true.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Then did you have dancing after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, they had dancing, they cleared all the - the - things away and we had dancing for a while. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you have singing as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes, dancing and singing, there was plenty of good singers amongst them, my father was a nice singer and so was my mother, and grandpa - every time there was anything like that or a concert or anything he always go
t my - my mother to sing - come on now Jeannie I think I hear - Neannie was my mother's name, sing us the Grand Wedding. It was a sort of comedy and she used to sing it for him, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How did long did the jollity's go on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Right on to the morning. Right on 'til about four o'clock in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you stay as long as that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. We stayed as long as that. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 I thought you would be more anxious to leave when you'd just a short time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - there wasnae anything else you 
could do because I mean we werena going away anywhere do you see, we were just going to - Bob's people for the night. Aye. They had a wee party for us that same night down at them, and - auntie from the Moss was up and - and some of her relatives to meet 
u
s supposed to be. Just a nice cup of tea you know and they didnae stop long but it was more just to meet up. Very nice, and then - the following day we'd to go away, get off at Lockerbie and I just got the train, I don't remember if I had much time to wai
t, I don't think so. Mother said, now I'll look for you back. And I said, no, don't be surprised if I just go back right to my work, because I think that 'll be the best place for me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You would be tired likely?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, I would be tired likely. I wou
ldnae do any - no, that's - that's right, I just went right back and wouldnae be much to do that day because it was afternoon you see and I wouldna have anything to do, I wouldnae start work 'til the next day. Because they didna know when I was coming bac
k, they were quite glad to have me - anytime. Polly was quite pleased to see me back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She would be wanting to hear all about it I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh aye. Aye, she was a nice -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you get a present from Mrs Thompson?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, I got that - silver
 teapot, where is it, oh in the - it's there somewhere, and after that, birthdays we always give each other presents, Polly and I at birthdays. It was always something, you know, for the house, aye, for the bottom drawer. She was a nice soul. She died a f
ew years ago. While we were at - Carlton Churchbridge she died. We just got word in the morning from her sister to say - she'd passed away and we went to the funeral that afternoon. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you remember going to any other weddings when you were wee that were different from yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, there was my aunt's wedding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 The one that was just a wee bit older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Just ten years, she was married - when we were just - I wasna left the school when she was married. She - married a - grandma
 and grandpa - in their old age - they'd a family of eight, and - the boys as she called them, this was the men - wanted them to go to Paisley, wasn't that an awful move from living in the country? And - they got them a house I remember, eight Caledonia S
t
reet, Paisley. And - it was up one flight of stairs, there was three - living on this flat. And - beautiful house it was inside and furnished all the sitting room beautiful for them, and - Aunt Martha was a very nice looking - I have a photo of her somewh
e
re but I don't just exactly know where, she was a nice looking young woman, and - she'd lots of young - lads you know, but - she went away from Templand and - went to Paisley, and grandpa got a job - with a contractor - Gray his name was, and he used to g
o
 out at four in the morning, get his horse and - lorry, and - do contracting you see. Well, this - man of course came - to the house - Uncle Ken or some of the boys brought him and he fell in love with my aunt, and he was about twice her age, and - it was
 him she married. And - one - girl, Marty they called her too - and - they lived -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was she married up in Paisley then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 She was married at Corncockle - come back - they didna like the town at all. Aye, they didna like the town and they come back a
nd lived next door to us up at Corncockle cottage and she was married from there, and it was in the wintertime, for I remember the snow was falling, and there was two or three young - children - of families coming to the wedding, I mean they got plenty of
 
time to prepare for it. And we - no, and we were left in there sitting with the kiddies you know - strange they were, in mother's house - while the - tea was going on in the other - place, after the wedding, and then - some of the mothers come in and let 
u
s in to get something, but we didn't actually get it along with them you see - owing to that. And they went away - went away in the morning - to catch the mail at Lockerbie, and when they got to Newcastle, where they were going for their honeymoon - it wa
s
 snowing heavy there, and when they went to put up their umbrellas going out of the station all the confetti - the - the firm gave them each beautiful umbrellas, I have a bit of the handle of my aunt's umbrella - in one of their - one of their presents an
d
 of course the porter looked and then the smiles got over their face, they were fair embraced. And when they got - the cabbie took them up to their own place, I canna mind, Cavendish Road or something and he took them to some other road and they woke up t
wo or three families before they got their - own folk. Uncle Tom was fair angry. That was where they were going to spend their honeymoon, with - a - brother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did girls that were in trouble get married in the church in your days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh no. They didna in the - no, our minister was dead against it, oh no, he would hardly marry them at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What did they do in a case like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - they used to - they used to - I remember once there was two daughters of the same family both expecting, and 
- the minister was fair furious and he preached about it from the the pulpit, that - that - father's - Elders of the church - should - be - set their daughters on a proper road and - got up and marched out of the church. That was rather hard you know. I m
ean, he can't watch them all the time. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was there a lot of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
There was a lot of that, yes, there was, oh there's always been that trouble. Always. But I think - it's worse now here. Aye. They - they look at it in a different way now you see that's what it is. They look at it in a different way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were girls looked down on if they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh they were, yes. And they wouldna let them back into the church you know, unless they stood -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Even after they got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. Unless they
 stood the session. That was they'd to go and in front of the Elders and minister and - I don't know what he did, but - he'd get up and tell them to repent of their sins. And like - like what Robbies Burns was - he was doing the same. But - allow me to te
ll you, a lot of these men that were Elders were no better than them, that's what - that's what sickened a lot of the people, and it was do away with. There's none of that now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did people wear white dresses for getting married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh usually, yes, that was the traditional - style.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 If you'd had more time you would have had a white dress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, quite likely, yes, my sister had. She'd plenty of time you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Would a girl that was pregnant be able to wear white?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - now they're n
ot - not these days but now the - lots of them aye. I know, they never, no. But they're not supposed to of course but in these days they were stricter. Aye. Far -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you ever remember your father or your mother being interested in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh they were interested, yes, it was just about the time, you see, that my husband's father was interested, were always Liberals. Both of them, both Liberal - in politics, yes. Oh they talked about - politics you know, took an interest you know the men 
- used to congregate, there was a seat outside - not exactly our house but the next door the men used to come there - at night and have a talk you know. I think the village - on the whole was mostly Liberal. There would be a few - Tories, but - they didna
 come to listen to the - to the other people you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Most of the working people were Liberals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No, the - they were Liberals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Who were the Tories then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - the man in the farm, the farmer, you know, he was one of them, oh he was - 
in fact I think - there was three farms about - near, like, and I think they were mostly - Tories, they werenae - cheeky or anything about it you know, but they no - they were no coming to listen to you sort of style.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 They wouldn't come and argue their own view?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No. No. They used to go to the meetings you know when they held - political meetings, it was mostly in the school, I mean - when there was to be an election there was always someone - like - they sent like from the Tory, the Liberal and L
abour, if there was Labour, I don't know if there was in these days but - I remember always the Tories and the Liberals because I used to hear them talking about them. And they used to go, my father used to go, mother didn't mind you, but my father used t
o always to go and - my brothers, when they got - up a bit you know, of course that was getting, years were getting on them, but they used to go too and listen to them and listen what they had to say then come out and - and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did they get a chance to ask questions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh yes, they could ask questions. And always remember one man, he was a farmer too, and - the Labour had been in for a long time, was it Labour, no, wait 'til I think - no, the Tories had been in, can't remember which one it would be. 
I can remember that his - his name began with C but what his name was I don't remember. But anyway, they'd made some money, this farmer, and he - he shouted out in the hall he says, now - the Tories has allowed us to make - make some money so lets get in 
the Labour know so as you can keep it.
\par <subject2>Mr. S. It was the other way about.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mrs. S. Was that what it was? Was that what it was?
\par <subject2>Mr. S. Aye, they said the Labour had helped them to make a fortune so he says let us put the Tories in to help us to keep it.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mrs. S. And where was the Tory then?
\par <subject2>Mr. S. I don't remember who the Tory was but it was - the man from Bridgenewer, at Beattie that was the farmer that said that.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Then all the men round about were quite interested in what was going on then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes, they were, they were quite interested.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How about you when you were older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well, I - I suppose just hearing my father and mother - talking, you know, in Liberal ways in - 
myself, you know, over the years, I've been more Liberal minded than - than - if - with the Tories, and - I mean to say - if it came to the crutch we've got a - a very good MP in just now from here, Mr - what's that - he's very good indeed. I said if they
 
were all like him I would vote Tory, but unfortunately they're not. He's been very good for the country, and he's done lots of things to help - people in all walks of life. If a person'll - Mrs Munro came one afternoon to our Evergreen meeting and told us
 
- she's a great friend of Mrs Bowetts, that's her President, and she brought her to tell us what it was like being an MP's wife, and it was very interesting. So - but - they - they asked me to give the vote of thanks that day, and - I said, that I hoped t
hat she would tell Mr Munro that we appreciated all that he was doing for the county because he had done a lot of good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Going back to the old days, did you ever see your MP then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - I mean when - when they went to vote for the - the MP they w
ould see him then because it was always their custom to come out in the Standard office you know. To - to make an appearance, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 But did he ever come round after he was elected?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - he came round like before the election, not after the election, because he was supposed to go to Dumfries and see him there you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 If you had a problem?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Some places at that men had to vote the way that their bosses voted otherwise they were liable to lose their job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, they had. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you ever hear of that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Yes. I can tell you tales about that, they went in their boss's car but they didna vote for the boss's I can tell you. No, they didnae. They went - you know, Colonel Kerr for one - he's ther
e now in - in Templand House and he wouldnae take anybody that wasnae Tory if he knew of it. And my brother used -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 He wouldn't employ them in the first place you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well, I mean he wouldna take them to the polling booths. Oh he would employ t
hem, and my brother worked for him for a long time you know, and in the garden and he told him I'll be out for you - such a like day, because he would be talking to him likely and putting the case forward and - I remember my brother saying, I didna vote f
or his man all the same. Oh there was a lot of that done, but if it had been known they would likely have sacked them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It was as bad as that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. Oh they were - they - really wanted - the man in. Funny, I canna remember that man's name that was 
on - Major McPherson's before him. Aye. It began with C you know, I canna remember that yet, I canna - canna remember his name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was it just when there was an election coming up that they were interested in talking about politics or did they do it all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh - often - on about it if there was anything took place like - in the year, through the year they often talked politics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 They'd read their newspapers and keep up to date that way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. Always the newspapers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Can you remember what happened whenever any of your younger brothers or sisters were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When any what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Any of your younger brothers or sisters were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh I can remember - I don't remember my sister, she's - she's - just a year and ten months - yo
unger than me, but I can remember when - when my - brothers were born and when Joanne was born. I remember grandma used - she used to come, of course grandma lived in the village too you know. But she used to always act as nurse, there was no - nursing ho
mes in those days like what they have now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was there a midwife that came round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - well, the midwife in the village was a Mrs Arnold, you know, that was the golden wedding that we were at, her mother, she went to all the - arrivals of the bab
ies you know. Aye. She was there when - when Margaret was born because I was just at home when Margaret was born, aye. Aye, a nice motherly - body she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What happened when they baby was coming, were you kept out of the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh aye, we were ne
ver there, you see - there was - up at grandma's house there was an aunt - aunt that was just ten years younger than me, and it was Uncle Sam at home, we were never - we werena kept at home, we were sent up to grandma's house and grandma come down, and th
en when - when we come down here there's a wee boy arrived since you went away, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You didn't know beforehand that there was a baby coming?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No. I didn't even know when my sister - my youngest sister was born, and - I would be ten or eleven
. 'Til one day I was coming up the road and past out with my friend and she said, there'll be a baby coming to your house some of these days, and I fair stared at her you know. You know, honestly, it's hardly believable now seeing the way the children - g
o about things now, but - I didn't know - oh they know everything now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mind you the dresses they wore when your mother was expecting these babies, I mean they had full skirts and probably an apron on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. An apron, you see, one of these loose aprons, aye. That would be it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 We've talked about the difference between the Liberals and the Tories.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Did you find that there were differences in class in the village where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 In the what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Differences in class where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - I mean - they didna treat you differently you know except at election times. They were going about at election times all being very - nice to you hoping that you would be voting, you know, with them, they used to - try to get us to s
ay but we never did you know, we never told them what we were going to do because - being - like my husband's folk - four miles off the voting booths you see, had to go to Lochmaben to vote, and that was like - four miles down and four miles back, that wa
s eight miles when we lived at the cottage, the Corncockle Cottage, it was a wee bit further out than the village, but - they never made any difference to you - between voting times I mean. They were quite nice to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 What about the landowners, were they different again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Well - I don't know, they seemed - they were very friendly too because - they - my brother - this was my eldest brother, he was once very ill - he worked at Raehills, you've heard of Raehills, old Johnson's place, well - one day 
- he - he came down, Mr Johnson, and - brought him four bottles of brandy. They were kind you know, if there was anything - and he said, now when that's finished - he says, just let us know and we'll have - some more, but he didna need more and that was p
lenty. And - they were really kind - kind enough to us I must say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Were you conscious that they were different from you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well - you looked up to them, I mean to say, you knew they had - they were in a different position than you but - I mean t
o say - except for the money we didna think they were any different, they'd just their feelings the same as - as working people haven't they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 In your village who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh well - the - round about Templand the
re was the - the people from - Miss Seaton Whitemans of Cournace, they used to go about in a phaeton, you know what a phaeton is?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 A wee carriage thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye and then men - men with cockades in their - big hats you know, and I always remember one 
day - my brother told me, he was just a wee boy and he heard this talk and quickly ran in to my mother and he said, oh mummy, here's the Lord coming. This was the - the laird he meant you know, he said, the Lord's coming. I could never forget that. And - 
t
hat was the Miss Seaton Whiteman, it was these two men you know with the big - big - with funeral hats they wear, and cockades - at the side, driving them, the old lady sitting very sedate but I believe they were very kind people, I never had anything to 
do with them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When they drove through the village did you all run out to watch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh well, used to watch that because it was grand to see this carriage coming with the horses. We didna just go right on the road but we used to stand just in - where
 we could see them going past, they never took any notice of you. But at Courance I suppose they were very good, that's a wee village, and - they used to go and - and listen to the children when they had their Sunday school parties and that you see, our v
i
llage was too far off, these were gentry, what were called the gentry, and then - the Raehills ones on the other side, and the Jardine Hall people, Jardine's of Jardine Hall. Not Lady Jardine, they were out of - Spedlands Tower you see, even when we were 
c
hildren they were out. And - that Lady Jardine's - Sir Alexander Jardine that lives in Denbie, that's the real - the real - the Jardine's that got Jardine Hall - were the Jardine Mattheson - Company, from out in China, with their money out in China and he
'd plenty of money - when they had their boat. But the titled people were poor you see. They had very much to live with. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 So it didn't really depend on what money you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 If you were born -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, that's it, yes, if you were bo
rn into the title. Aye. But we used to - we used to go to Jardine Hall on our - school - maybe a school picnic. They used to - the Jardine Hall ones were the ones that came in - give us our school prizes when we got prizes at the school, and she used to a
s
k us back for - a picnic tea, well it was - it wasna a very nice day the day we went for the picnic tea so they'd be marquees up and it was a lovely tea they gave us. Aye, we used to get that. And we used to go - were asked when we got bigger - we were al
lowed in the bigger classes to go on a conducted tour of Spedlands old tower, you know, that was their home. That was their home but it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It's falling down now isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It's no falling down, we go to it every year, it's - it's got no top on 
it, and you canna get inside it now, but that's - been always a favourite place where we went for picnics as children and - there used to be an old man living in the lodge there. Garningham was his name. He was and Englishman, but he never got anything el
s
e but Billy Pond. That was his name. And - mother and father and my uncle, he wet to be a policeman in the finish but he worked for a wee while in his young days at the quarry, and this old man used to work too, at the top end. They called - that's what t
h
ey tipped all the - the rubble, it's still there yet, and - they used to take us maybe for a walk on a Sunday and we used to sit to listen to them tell the tales about the hunting. Hunting at Sepdlands. It was supposed to be - and Sir Alexander Jardine's 
t
ime - time of the horse - horses only, and he'd gone way, put this man Porteus who had a mill - down into the dungeon, he was supposed to have set fire to his mill, I don't know whether he did or not, but that was the tale, and he went away on horseback t
o
 Edinborgh, forgot all about the man. And when - when he come back the man had - eaten his fingers and his toes I suppose with hunger, and - the place started to be haunted then. And - I remember Miss Landale coming, and Miss Landale from Browmoor, Ecclef
echan when I was at - Mrs Thompsons and it was an aunt - sister of hers that was a minister, she talked about this too, and - he went there and went down in the dungeon and prayed and - they left a Bible down and - all the thing went quiet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 That chased the ghost away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Aye, it's supposed to but - that's what they had to leave Spedlands for so they said and they built Jardine Hall just across the water, but it was supposed to - to go - follow them there, I don't know whether it was true or not, thi
s old man - Mr S. Burns said that a - a - a spook wouldna cross the water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was that why they built their other house on the other side of the water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well I thought it was witches that'll not cross water. Aye, Jardine Hall, that's right. So - so 
when this - Scott the gardener the man that used to take us on this conducted tour you see, and when we were going in - oh funny place, it's just wee wee windows you know, just what they had in the olden days - for - shooting, through, aye, just - just on
e
 of these things like Threave Castle and all these, Torthorwalk Castle, the same style as that, and - when we were going across - this place we opened this - what a monstrous key there was, and when he opened the door and took us in you know, walking acro
ss this hall, just stone you know, he says, that's where Dante lives, Dante, that's what they called the ghost and he opened this trap door and it was a - oh down there, a spiral -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You didn't go down to look?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 We didna go down, no. Aye, but that was the witches.
\par <subject2>Mr S. The evil spirit.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Mrs. S. Aye. Oh maybe the man wasnae evil, he had died in agony.
\par <subject2>Mr. S. No, but he left the evil spirit, the evil spirit was there.</subject2>
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Would you say that most of the 
people in the village had much the same standard of living, or were there some of them better off than others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh, much the same standard of living because they all worked in the quarry these days. Of course some jobs there were better paid than othe
rs you know. Just depended what you were - cranemen for instance, they would have more than a man that - that drove the wee engine from the quarry to Nethercluegh he would have more but - working like that, but the men that were working on the stone face 
- and the tip end, they would just have the same. The men at the source have more money I know that, but it would only be a few shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Was there much distinction made between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes. No, no, they were all friendly, seeme
d all friendly. There never was anything else to work at in my young days for the men except that and for long years after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you think it was possible at that time for people to move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 One class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 One social class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Oh well, I don't know, I - I couldnae say about that, I don't remember anybody - moving up the scale at all, I don't think so. Just - no, just - ordinary village life. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You don't know of any cases of people that came down the social scale?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Oh no. They were all much the same I think. Aye. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Do you think your parents ever had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Well - it was just - mother seemed always to make do, I don't know how she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You never had the feeling they were going short?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
No. No. And when anything - came such as - at the school there was a man used to come, a Mr Meikle I remember his name was, and he used to do - to teach singing. He used to come, and - he came for about three months and it w
as tuppence a night to go to - the singing class and my sister and I both went. And - then at the end of that - the three months they had a concert. It must have been a good teacher of course we were young, we'd pick up things - and - they had two nights 
o
f the concert, folk used to come, it was in the school of course, there was no hall in that - in that - early days, and - filled the school for two nights, the people around about so that would kind of repay him for his work you see. And we all got - well
, that could do it, got part.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You would say that was a luxury, that if there was money in the house for that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You weren't really -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye. Of course mind you - in the - in the days I'm speaking about, the - quarry was 
extra busy. There was lots of people came from far and near to work there, and it was hardly a house in the village but had one or two men staying with them. Like my mother had - two - I remember when she had three but - that was - be a lot of work for he
r you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 It would always be a wee bit of extra money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Aye, it would be a help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 When you were living with the Raes, when you went to work there first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 You mentioned that they went for their holidays to Worthing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16673035 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 How often they go and how long did they stay for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6835572 MS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7146469\charrsid2967080 
Fortnight. And they went - they went yearly, they - you know, the minister always put about a fortnights holidays, and Worthing seemed to be the place where they seemed to like to go, and they used to go for a fortnight..
